{"title_page": "System Sensor", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = System Sensor\n| logo = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Honeywell Life Safety Group]]\n| foundation = {{Start date|1984}}\n| location_city =  [[St. Charles, Illinois|St. Charles]], [[Illinois]]\n| location_country = [[United States|USA]]\n| location =\n| locations =\n| area_served = [[World]]\n| key_people = '''John Hakanson''' <br /> <small>[[President (corporate title)|President]] System Sensor HLS</small>\n| industry = [[Manufacturing]]\n| products = Fire detection and notification devices\n| num_employees = 1,900\n| parent = [[Honeywell International Inc.]]\n| subsid =\n| homepage = {{URL|systemsensor.com}}\n| slogan   = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Spectralert.JPG|thumb|right|235px|Wallmount Horn/Strobe SpectrAlert Classic]]\n\n'''System Sensor''' is a company headquartered in [[St. Charles, Illinois]], dedicated to the research, development and manufacture of [[fire protection]] equipment. System Sensor is a part of the [[Honeywell Life Safety Group]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.honeywelllifesafety.com/HLSP1business.html |title=Companies |publisher=Honeywell Life Safety |accessdate=24 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109000000/http://www.honeywelllifesafety.com/HLSP1business.html |archive-date=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nSystem Sensor was founded in 1984 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.systemsensor.com/html/about.html |title=About System Sensor | accessdate=24 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308105416/http://www.systemsensor.com/html/about.html |archive-date=March 8, 2010 }}</ref> to address the requirements of exclusive industry fire alarm products. One of their first products was the MASS sounder series of notification appliances, which came with System Sensor in 1984. Shortly after, in the early 1990s, System Sensor came out with MASS ADA sounders, with a horizontal strobe. In 1997, System Sensor introduced the SpectrAlert Classic, and the MASS was discontinued shortly thereafter. In 2007, System Sensor discontinued the SpectrAlert Classic, replacing it with the SpectrAlert Advance, which has a reputation for how loud it is on the highest volume. Another notable product line from System Sensor is their i3 line of both 2 and 4 wire smoke detectors, first released in the early 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.systemsensor.com/e-docs/data/av/a936-01.pdf |title=System Sensor on the web |publisher=System Sensor |date=December 12, 1998 |accessdate = 24 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970709063939/http://www.systemsensor.com/e-docs/data/av/a936-01.pdf |archive-date=9 July 1997}}</ref> System Sensor was acquired by Honeywell in the 2000s and currently manufactures fire protection devices, flow switches for fire suppression systems and climate control products. In 2017, the company announced the L-Series, which claims to save energy, installation time, and money. The L series used the same horn as the Spectralert Advance. The L series can hold different covers and colored lenses so the device can be used for more than just fire alarm service. System Sensor discontinued most of the wall or ceiling mount horn strobes. All of the horn only devices, chimes, and chime strobes. System Sensor recently released its <ref>{{cite web |title=New L-Series Low Frequency Notification Appliances |url=https://www.systemsensor.com/en-us/news/PressCenter/Pages/L-Series-Low-Freq-Announcement.aspx |publisher=Honeywell International |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>Low-Frequency L-Series devices. They have the same LF sounder, however they also have the functionality to do Temporal 4 coding, for Carbon Monoxide (CO) operations, and like the other products in the L-Series lineup, the LF version also consumes low energy as well.\n\n== Distribution Partners ==\n[[The Mircom Group of Companies|Mircom]] is the largest private distribution partner of System Sensor in the world.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heat detector]]\n* [[First Alert]]\n* [[Insteon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|systemsensor.com}}\n\n{{Honeywell|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Honeywell]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Fire detection and alarm companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = System Sensor\n| logo = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of [[Honeywell Life Safety Group]]\n| foundation = {{Start date|1984}}\n| location_city =  [[St. Charles, Illinois|St. Charles]], [[Illinois]]\n| location_country = [[United States|USA]]\n| location =\n| locations =\n| area_served = [[World]]\n| key_people = '''John Hakanson''' <br /> <small>[[President (corporate title)|President]] System Sensor HLS</small>\n| industry = [[Manufacturing]]\n| products = Fire detection and notification devices\n| num_employees = 1,900\n| parent = [[Honeywell International Inc.]]\n| subsid =\n| homepage = {{URL|systemsensor.com}}\n| slogan   = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Spectralert.JPG|thumb|right|235px|Wallmount Horn/Strobe SpectrAlert Classic]]\n\n'''System Sensor''' is a company headquartered in [[St. Charles, Illinois]], dedicated to the research, development and manufacture of [[fire protection]] equipment. System Sensor is a part of the [[Honeywell Life Safety Group]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.honeywelllifesafety.com/HLSP1business.html |title=Companies |publisher=Honeywell Life Safety |accessdate=24 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109000000/http://www.honeywelllifesafety.com/HLSP1business.html |archive-date=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nSystem Sensor was founded in 1984 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.systemsensor.com/html/about.html |title=About System Sensor | accessdate=24 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308105416/http://www.systemsensor.com/html/about.html |archive-date=March 8, 2010 }}</ref> to address the requirements of exclusive industry fire alarm products. One of their first products was the MASS sounder series of notification appliances, which came with System Sensor in 1984. Shortly after, in the early 1990s, System Sensor came out with MASS ADA sounders, with a horizontal strobe. In 1997, System Sensor introduced the SpectrAlert Classic, and the MASS was discontinued shortly thereafter. In 2006, System Sensor discontinued the SpectrAlert Classic, replacing it with the SpectrAlert Advance, which has a reputation for how loud it is on the highest volume. Another notable product line from System Sensor is their i3 line of both 2 and 4 wire smoke detectors, first released in the early 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.systemsensor.com/e-docs/data/av/a936-01.pdf |title=System Sensor on the web |publisher=System Sensor |date=December 12, 1998 |accessdate = 24 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970709063939/http://www.systemsensor.com/e-docs/data/av/a936-01.pdf |archive-date=9 July 1997}}</ref> System Sensor was acquired by Honeywell in the 2000s and currently manufactures fire protection devices, flow switches for fire suppression systems and climate control products. In 2017, the company announced the L-Series, which claims to save energy, installation time, and money. The L series used the same horn as the Spectralert Advance. The L series can hold different covers and colored lenses so the device can be used for more than just fire alarm service. System Sensor discontinued most of the wall or ceiling mount horn strobes. All of the horn only devices, chimes, and chime strobes. System Sensor recently released its <ref>{{cite web |title=New L-Series Low Frequency Notification Appliances |url=https://www.systemsensor.com/en-us/news/PressCenter/Pages/L-Series-Low-Freq-Announcement.aspx |publisher=Honeywell International |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>Low-Frequency L-Series devices. They have the same LF sounder, however they also have the functionality to do Temporal 4 coding, for Carbon Monoxide (CO) operations, and like the other products in the L-Series lineup, the LF version also consumes low energy as well.\n\n== Distribution Partners ==\n[[The Mircom Group of Companies|Mircom]] is the largest private distribution partner of System Sensor in the world.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heat detector]]\n* [[First Alert]]\n* [[Insteon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|systemsensor.com}}\n\n{{Honeywell|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Honeywell]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Fire detection and alarm companies]]\n", "name_user": "Pendseaadi", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_Sensor"}
{"title_page": "Heidi Parviainen", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=June 2014}}\n{{copypaste|date=January 2017}}\n{{citations broken|date=January 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Heidi Parviainen\n| image            = Dark-Sarah-6757.jpg\n| caption          = Heidi Parviainen with Dark Sarah 2020\n| image_size       = 240px\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1979|3|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Espoo]], [[Finland]]\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = Finland\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[piano]]\n| genre            = [[symphonic metal]], [[gothic metal]], [[power metal]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active     = 1997\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Amberian Dawn]], [[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]], [[Ensiferum]], [[Dark Sarah]], [[Manuela Kraller]]\n| website          = {{URL|darksarah.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Heidi Parviainen''' (born 8 March 1979) is a Finnish professionally educated classical [[lyric soprano]] and a singing teacher. She is best known from her cinematic metal band [[Dark Sarah]] and as the former lead singer of Finnish [[power metal]] band [[Amberian Dawn]]. Before working with Amberian Dawn, she played keyboards and provided background vocals for a band called Iconofear. \n\n==Early life==\nHeidi's musical history started quite early in a children's music playschool. Later on, at a primary school, she went to a music-oriented class. She started taking piano lessons at the age of 11, but soon she said it became very clear that she wanted more than just classical piano playing. After various teachers, she quit taking piano lessons and has played by herself. At the age of 14, she started classical singing studies in a music institute with the diploma singer Raisa Lahtiranta. During more than ten years she had also sung in various choirs and ensembles.<ref name=\"spirit-of-metal.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spirit-of-metal.com/membre_groupe/membre_groupe-nom-Heidi_Parviainen-id-14007-l-en.html|title=Parviainen Heidi (Amberian Dawn)- Musician Profile|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===Agonia, Iconofear (1997\u20132006)===\nThe first contact with heavy music came in 1997 at high school, when a couple of high school heavy-metal guys asked her to sing on their EP. At that time, they played death metal and the band was called Agonia. After a while, Heidi joined the band as a keyboard player and backing vocalist. From 1997, the band changed its form, and its name to Iconofear. After years of classical singing studies, Heidi grew accustomed to the idea of being a vocalist and during the decade with Iconofear she also grew to like heavy music.\n\n===With Amberian Dawn (2006\u20132012)===\n[[File:Amberian Dawn 2.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Amberian Dawn performing at the [[Metal Female Voices Fest]] on their ''[[The Clouds of Northland Thunder]]'' tour.]]\nSo in the summer 2006, she started to look for a band, a metal band, because it seemed to be closest to her interests. The guys spotted her application, listened to her samples and called her, to set up a demo with her and the band. It turned out that she was exactly what they were looking for, due to her ability to both sing and contribute lyrics. This completed the band's lineup, now under the name of Amberian Dawn.<ref name=\"spirit-of-metal.com\"/>\n\nHeidi started to write lyrics which were often influenced by [[Finnish mythology|Finnish]] and [[Norse mythology]], and many songs reference the Finnish national poem [[Kalevala]]. She undertook three European tours with the band and performed at several European festivals.\n\nOn 19 November 2012 the band announced that Heidi had parted ways with them. The decision was made in early 2012, thus meaning Amberian Dawn's appearance at [[Metal Female Voices Fest]] was their last show together with Heidi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amberiandawn.com/parting-ways-with-vocalist-line-up-change1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614133149/http://www.amberiandawn.com/parting-ways-with-vocalist-line-up-change1 |archivedate=June 14, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>[[File:HeidiKasperi.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Heidi Parviainen and [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] with [[Amberian Dawn]] in 2009.]]\n\n===Dark Sarah (2012\u2013)===\nA few days after her departure, Heidi announced that she had started a new musical project called \"Dark Sarah\". She said Dark Sarah \"is making one of my dreams come true, a dream that had been sleeping for many years but now has finally awoken.\"<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darksarah.com/#/infoPage |title=Dark Sarah Official - About |website=Darksarah.com |accessdate= May 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHeidi explained the concept:\n\n{{quote|Dark Sarah's story ''Behind the Black Veil'' tells a story about a young woman called Sarah. She is left at the altar by her husband and she almost has a mental breakdown but instead something wakes up inside her and she changes to another person, her meaner half: Dark Sarah.}}\n\nThe musical style combines elements of film music, metal music and music theater. On the album called ''Behind the Black Veil'', which will feature several guest musicians such as [[Manuela Kraller]], Inga Scharf ([[Van Canto]]) and [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] ([[U.D.O]], Merging Flare). Dark Sarah consists of a talented band including musicians like: Erkka Korhonen (guitar) (Raskasta joulua, [[Northern Kings]]), Sami-Petri Salonen (guitar), [[Jukka Koskinen]] (bass) ([[Wintersun]]) and Lauri Kuussalo (drums).<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\" />\n\nDark Sarah has released 3 albums so far, after an initial EP. The first album, Behind the Black Veil, was released in 2014. This was followed by The Puzzle (released 2016), and The Golden Moth (released 2018). The Violent Roses EP was released in 2014.<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\"/>\n\nIn 2020 the band announced their signing to Napalm Records and a new studio album called \"Grim\".\n\n===Other works===\nParviainen has performed with a few other bands in studio, with [[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]] on the song \"Tears of Autumn Rain\" from the album [[Children of the Dark Waters]] in 2009, and with [[Ensiferum]] on their album [[Unsung Heroes (Ensiferum album)|Unsung Heroes]], providing the choir vocals. \n\n== Discography ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Dark Sarah ===\n;Studio albums'\n* ''Behind the Black Veil'' (2015)\n* ''The Puzzle'' (2016)\n* ''The Golden Moth'' (2018)\n* ''Grim'' (2020)\n;EP's\n* ''Violent Roses'' (2014)\n\n;Music videos\n* ''Save Me'' (2013)\n* ''Memories Fall'' (2014) <small>(feat. [[Manuela Kraller]])</small>\n* ''Hunting The Dreamer'' (2014)\n* ''Light In You'' (2015) <small>(feat. [[Tony Kakko]])</small>\n* ''Little Men'' (2016)\n* ''Aquarium'' (2016) <small>(feat. [[Charlotte Wessels]] - lyric video)</small>\n* ''Dance With the Dragon'' (2016) <small>(feat. [[Juha-Pekka Lepp\u00e4luoto]])</small>\n* ''Trespasser'' (2017)\n\n=== Amberian Dawn ===\n;Demos\n* ''[[Amberian Dawn (demo)]]'' (2006)\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[River of Tuoni]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Clouds of Northland Thunder]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[End of Eden]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Circus Black]]'' (2012)\n\n;Singles\n* \"He Sleeps in a Grove\" (2009)\n* \"[[Arctica (song)|Arctica]]\" (2010)\n* \"Cold Kiss\" (2012)\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Iconofear ===\n;EPs\n* ''Dark (EP)'' (2003)\n* ''The 13th Circle'' (2005)\n* ''The Unbreathing'' (2006)\n\n=== Agonia ===\n;Demos\n* ''Demo I'' (1997)\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n*'''2009:''' ''[[Children of the Dark Waters]]'' ([[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]]) (vocals on \"Tears of Autumn Rain\")\n*'''2012:''' ''[[Unsung Heroes (Ensiferum album)|Unsung Heroes]]'' ([[Ensiferum]]) (choir vocals)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.darksarah.com Dark Sarah Official Website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/HeidiParviainenOfficial Heidi Parviainen Official Facebook]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/darksarahofficial Dark Sarah Official Facebook]\n*[https://twitter.com/DarkSarahHQ Dark Sarah Official Twitter]\n*[https://myspace.com/heidi_darksarah Dark Sarah Official Myspace]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/darksarahofficial Dark Sarah Official YouTube]\n\n{{amberian Dawn}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parviainen, Heidi}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Espoo]]\n[[Category:Finnish heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish sopranos]]\n[[Category:Amberian Dawn members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Tone|date=June 2014}}\n{{copypaste|date=January 2017}}\n{{citations broken|date=January 2017}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Heidi Parviainen\n| image            = Dark-Sarah-6757.jpg\n| caption          = Heidi Parviainen with Dark Sarah 2020\n| image_size       = 240px\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1979|3|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Espoo]], [[Finland]]\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = Finland\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[piano]]\n| genre            = [[symphonic metal]], [[gothic metal]], [[power metal]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active     = 1997\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Amberian Dawn]], [[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]], [[Ensiferum]], [[Dark Sarah]], [[Manuela Kraller]]\n| website          = {{URL|darksarah.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Heidi Parviainen''' (born 8 March 1979) is a Finnish, professionally educated classical [[lyric soprano]] and a singing teacher. She is best known from her cinematic metal band [[Dark Sarah]] and as the former lead singer of Finnish [[power metal]] band [[Amberian Dawn]]. Before working with Amberian Dawn, she played keyboards and provided background vocals for a band called Iconofear. \n\n==Early life==\nHeidi's musical history started quite early in a children's music playschool. Later on, at a primary school, she went to a music-oriented class. She started taking piano lessons at the age of 11, but soon she said it became very clear that she wanted more than just classical piano playing. After various teachers, she quit taking piano lessons and has played by herself. At the age of 14, she started classical singing studies in a music institute with the diploma singer Raisa Lahtiranta. During more than ten years she had also sung in various choirs and ensembles.<ref name=\"spirit-of-metal.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spirit-of-metal.com/membre_groupe/membre_groupe-nom-Heidi_Parviainen-id-14007-l-en.html|title=Parviainen Heidi (Amberian Dawn)- Musician Profile|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===Agonia, Iconofear (1997\u20132006)===\nThe first contact with heavy music came in 1997 at high school, when a couple of high school heavy-metal guys asked her to sing on their EP. At that time, they played death metal and the band was called Agonia. After a while, Heidi joined the band as a keyboard player and backing vocalist. From 1997, the band changed its form, and its name to Iconofear. After years of classical singing studies, Heidi grew accustomed to the idea of being a vocalist and during the decade with Iconofear she also grew to like heavy music.\n\n===With Amberian Dawn (2006\u20132012)===\n[[File:Amberian Dawn 2.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Amberian Dawn performing at the [[Metal Female Voices Fest]] on their ''[[The Clouds of Northland Thunder]]'' tour.]]\nSo in the summer 2006, she started to look for a band, a metal band, because it seemed to be closest to her interests. The guys spotted her application, listened to her samples and called her, to set up a demo with her and the band. It turned out that she was exactly what they were looking for, due to her ability to both sing and contribute lyrics. This completed the band's lineup, now under the name of Amberian Dawn.<ref name=\"spirit-of-metal.com\"/>\n\nHeidi started to write lyrics which were often influenced by [[Finnish mythology|Finnish]] and [[Norse mythology]], and many songs reference the Finnish national poem [[Kalevala]]. She undertook three European tours with the band and performed at several European festivals.\n\nOn 19 November 2012 the band announced that Heidi had parted ways with them. The decision was made in early 2012, thus meaning Amberian Dawn's appearance at [[Metal Female Voices Fest]] was their last show together with Heidi.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amberiandawn.com/parting-ways-with-vocalist-line-up-change1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614133149/http://www.amberiandawn.com/parting-ways-with-vocalist-line-up-change1 |archivedate=June 14, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>[[File:HeidiKasperi.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Heidi Parviainen and [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] with [[Amberian Dawn]] in 2009.]]\n\n===Dark Sarah (2012\u2013)===\nA few days after her departure, Heidi announced that she had started a new musical project called \"Dark Sarah\". She said Dark Sarah \"is making one of my dreams come true, a dream that had been sleeping for many years but now has finally awoken.\"<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darksarah.com/#/infoPage |title=Dark Sarah Official - About |website=Darksarah.com |accessdate= May 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHeidi explained the concept:\n\n{{quote|Dark Sarah's story ''Behind the Black Veil'' tells a story about a young woman called Sarah. She is left at the altar by her husband and she almost has a mental breakdown but instead something wakes up inside her and she changes to another person, her meaner half: Dark Sarah.}}\n\nThe musical style combines elements of film music, metal music and music theater. On the album called ''Behind the Black Veil'', which will feature several guest musicians such as [[Manuela Kraller]], Inga Scharf ([[Van Canto]]) and [[Kasperi Heikkinen]] ([[U.D.O]], Merging Flare). Dark Sarah consists of a talented band including musicians like: Erkka Korhonen (guitar) (Raskasta joulua, [[Northern Kings]]), Sami-Petri Salonen (guitar), [[Jukka Koskinen]] (bass) ([[Wintersun]]) and Lauri Kuussalo (drums).<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\" />\n\nDark Sarah has released 3 albums so far, after an initial EP. The first album, Behind the Black Veil, was released in 2014. This was followed by The Puzzle (released 2016), and The Golden Moth (released 2018). The Violent Roses EP was released in 2014.<ref name=\"Dark Sarah\"/>\n\nIn 2020 the band announced their signing to Napalm Records and a new studio album called \"Grim\".\n\n===Other works===\nParviainen has performed with a few other bands in studio, with [[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]] on the song \"Tears of Autumn Rain\" from the album [[Children of the Dark Waters]] in 2009, and with [[Ensiferum]] on their album [[Unsung Heroes (Ensiferum album)|Unsung Heroes]], providing the choir vocals. \n\n== Discography ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Dark Sarah ===\n;Studio albums'\n* ''Behind the Black Veil'' (2015)\n* ''The Puzzle'' (2016)\n* ''The Golden Moth'' (2018)\n* ''Grim'' (2020)\n;EP's\n* ''Violent Roses'' (2014)\n\n;Music videos\n* ''Save Me'' (2013)\n* ''Memories Fall'' (2014) <small>(feat. [[Manuela Kraller]])</small>\n* ''Hunting The Dreamer'' (2014)\n* ''Light In You'' (2015) <small>(feat. [[Tony Kakko]])</small>\n* ''Little Men'' (2016)\n* ''Aquarium'' (2016) <small>(feat. [[Charlotte Wessels]] - lyric video)</small>\n* ''Dance With the Dragon'' (2016) <small>(feat. [[Juha-Pekka Lepp\u00e4luoto]])</small>\n* ''Trespasser'' (2017)\n\n=== Amberian Dawn ===\n;Demos\n* ''[[Amberian Dawn (demo)]]'' (2006)\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[River of Tuoni]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Clouds of Northland Thunder]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[End of Eden]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Circus Black]]'' (2012)\n\n;Singles\n* \"He Sleeps in a Grove\" (2009)\n* \"[[Arctica (song)|Arctica]]\" (2010)\n* \"Cold Kiss\" (2012)\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Iconofear ===\n;EPs\n* ''Dark (EP)'' (2003)\n* ''The 13th Circle'' (2005)\n* ''The Unbreathing'' (2006)\n\n=== Agonia ===\n;Demos\n* ''Demo I'' (1997)\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n*'''2009:''' ''[[Children of the Dark Waters]]'' ([[Eternal Tears of Sorrow]]) (vocals on \"Tears of Autumn Rain\")\n*'''2012:''' ''[[Unsung Heroes (Ensiferum album)|Unsung Heroes]]'' ([[Ensiferum]]) (choir vocals)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.darksarah.com Dark Sarah Official Website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/HeidiParviainenOfficial Heidi Parviainen Official Facebook]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/darksarahofficial Dark Sarah Official Facebook]\n*[https://twitter.com/DarkSarahHQ Dark Sarah Official Twitter]\n*[https://myspace.com/heidi_darksarah Dark Sarah Official Myspace]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/darksarahofficial Dark Sarah Official YouTube]\n\n{{amberian Dawn}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parviainen, Heidi}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Espoo]]\n[[Category:Finnish heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish sopranos]]\n[[Category:Amberian Dawn members]]\n", "name_user": "Dchaikelsonmusiclove", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heidi_Parviainen"}
{"title_page": "List of Horrid Henry characters", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=November 2011}}\n{{in-universe|date=November 2011}}\n{{cleanup|date=November 2011}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Horrid Henry'' characters}}\nThe following is a list of characters that appear in the [[United Kingdom|British]] series of children's books, ''[[Horrid Henry]]'', written by [[Francesca Simon]]. It also includes names from the [[CITV]] and [[Nicktoons]] [[Horrid Henry (TV series)|TV series of the same name]].\n{{Horizontal TOC|limit=2|nonum=y}}\n\n== A ==\n\n===Aerobic Al===\n\nAerobic Al is an extremely athletic boy, who is often displayed engaging in various athletic endeavours. He has blond hair and is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. He is often seen with Rude Ralph, Beefy Bert and Gorgeous Gurinder. He wears a white shirt with a blue collar, blue shorts and teal keds. In some episodes, he is shown to have a crush on Moody Margaret. \n\nIn the TV series, he speaks with a [[Brummie]] accent and is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Al\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sports Day (Books)<br>Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Aerobic Al\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Dad\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Wayne Forester\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\n\n===Aerobic Al's dad===\nAerobic Al's dad comes to some school events, mostly to see his son end up winning. In the TV series, he appeared in \"''[[Horrid Henry's Fun Run]]''\", where he had brown hair and was a referee. he docent want his son to be eating sweets in horrid henrys sports day. \n\n===Anxious Andrew===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Andrew\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Injection\n| last               = TBA\n| voice              = Sue Elliott-Nichols\n| nickname           = Anxious Andrew\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Tidy Ted\n}}\n\nAnxious Andrew is one of Henry's classmates; a nervous and meek boy, who always worries about unnecessary things. He is best friends with Weepy William and attends Ashton Primary School. He has ginger hair and wears a dark green tanktop with a green shirt and blue-grey trousers \n\nIn the TV series, he is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Allergic Alice===\nA minor character who appears in the book ''Horrid Henry's Cannibal Curse'' in which she is revealed to be allergic to [[gluten]], nuts, sugar, flour ''and'' dairy.\n\n==B==\n\n===Bald man===\nA bald man appears as a minor character in 'Horrid Henry's New Shoes' when Mum opens his changing room door when trying to look for Henry.\n\n=== Basher ===\nA Dog who appears in Horrid Henry and The Lost Dog, who Henry finds and part-time owns for a while. It was then revealed he was missing, after an advert passes through Henry's house door. His name appears to have been inspired by Gnasher from the ''[[Dennis the Menace and Gnasher|Dennis the Menace]]'' stories.\n\n===Beefy Bert===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Bert\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's New Teacher (Books)<br>Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Beefy Bert\n| gender             = Male\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Wayne Forester\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nBeefy Bert is usually seen in the crowds of children at Henry and Peter's school, and is normally seen with Ralph and Al. Whenever anyone asks him a question, his immediate answer is \"I dunno\", which is actually the only line Bert ever says throughout the entire book series. He is the biggest boy in Henry's class. Both his parents and his brother also say \"I dunno\" as revealed when he films them for a school project in the story ''Horrid Henry Tells it Like it Is'' in the book ''Horrid Henry's Krazy Ketchup''.\n\nIn the TV series, Bert is voiced by Wayne Forester, and his voice was originally low-pitched and deep, but from the second season onwards, it was changed to a higher-pitched, squeakier one. Like with his book counterpart, the only word he says is \"I dunno\" but however in the Series 1 TV episode ''Horrid Henry Gets Rich Quick'', he says \"Have you got any food?\" and in the Series 4 episode ''Horrid Henry Who's Who?'', after switching personalities with Brainy Brian, he gives his answers in full sentences.\n\n===Beefy Bert's dad===\nBeefy Bert's dad is a bus driver who appears in ''Horrid Henry Takes a Shortcut'', ''Horrid Henry And The Purple Pass'', ''Horrid Henry and the Perfect Parents'' and ''Horrid Henry Alone at Home''. Like with his Son, Whenever anyone asks him a question, his immediate answer is \"I dunno\".\n\n===Beefy Bert's mum===\nBeefy Bert's mum is briefly seen in the TV adaption of ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover'', calling Henry's Dad. She is voiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]].\n\nIn the books, she appears in ''Horrid Henry Tells it Like it Is'', where with the rest of Bert's family, she says \"I dunno\".\n\n===Bob===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Bob\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Goes to Work\n| last               = Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| nickname           = Bob Sir, Big Boss\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Bill (son)\n| children           = Bossy Bill\n}}\nBob (also known as Big Boss or \"Bob Sir\") is Dad's work boss. He is very strict, and is extremely proud of his son, Bill, whom he believes is perfect. However, he discovers that this is not the case after catching Bill photocopying his bottom. He grounds Bill for a month and sends him home. His book appearance was in ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'' and he is mentioned in \"Horrid Henry's Arch Enemy\". \n\nIn the TV series, he is referred to as Bob or Bob Sir, and the job he runs is Tingly Toothbrushes who make toothbrushes and toothpaste just for Dogs. He appeared in the adaptation of ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'', and has  also appeared in \"Horrid Henry's Heist\" as the school inspector at the fancy dress party (where his character design looks like an older version of his son, Bossy Bill),  ''Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson'' when he was in the park on his way to an appointment with Bill's headmaster and in ''Horrid Henry Helps Out''.\n\n===Massive Mozz===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mozz\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Goes to Work (Books and TV series)\n| last               =\n| portrayer          = \n| nickname           = Massive Mozz\n| species            = TBH lad completely unknown\n| gender             = Unknown\n| family             = Naomi\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| voice              = [[Murad Ahmed]]\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nThe guy no-one wants in the party because he doesn't listen speak a word of English.\n\n===Brainy Brian===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Brian\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb (Books)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Brainy Brian\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Brother of Gordon\n| family             = Goody Gordon\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Aidan Cook\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nThe smartest boy in Horrid Henry's class. He appears to be of Black descent. He has brown skin and black hair and wears a pink shirt with pens tucked into his pocket and green floral shorts along with baby-blue shoes. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n=== Bunny ===\nBunny is Peter's adorable toy [[rabbit]]. It is Peter's version of Mr. Kill. His most major roles in the TV series are in ''Horrid Henry and the Time Capsule'', in which Henry gives Bunny to the capsule and rescues him, ''Horrid Henry Trapped'', in which Henry has Bunny in the hospital after he was injured whilst saving Peter from a falling shelf in the cellar and ''Perfect Peter Pumps Up'', in which Henry realises that the only way to turn Peter aggressive is to steal Bunny and make fun of him.\n\n==C==\n\n===Captain Push-Me Button===\nCaptain Push-Me Button is a robot that appeared in ''Horrid Henry's Aquarium''. He gives tickets to the Dingy Dungeon. It is thought that he wasn't put together properly as he has some technical malfunctions. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Caring Chris===\nCaring Chris works at the old people's home. She has a good friendship with Miss Oddbod. She only appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Walking Stick Gang''. She is voiced by Sue Eliott Nichols in the TV series.\n\n===Cherry Berry===\nCherry Berry is a famous pastry chef based on ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'' judge, [[Mary Berry]]. Cherry was a judge in the street party in ''Horrid Henry's Bake-Off''.\n\n===Clever Clare===\nClever Clare is the smartest girl in Horrid Henry's class. But only appears as a minor character in an Ashton Primary school photo in Horrid Henry, Nothing But The Truth in the TV series as a member of Perfect Peter's class. In ''[[Horrid Henry's Double Dare]]'', she has to get all her spellings wrong. She also appeared in Horrid Henry, ''It\u2019s All Your Fault'' when she was singing with Sour Susan, Gorgeous Gurinder and Singing Soraya in the musical number, Born To Be Rude. She also appears on the cover of Horrid Henry's Nits, appearing as the one who Henry is flicking nits to.\n\n===Colin the Clown===\nColin the [[Clown]] appears in ''Happy Birthday Peter!'', where he appears as the clown and entertainer of Peter's [[birthday party]] and is scared of lions, whom he had a bad [[circus]] experience with. He is able to blow [[handkerchiefs]] out of his nose, make [[milk]] disappear and make a [[banana]] disappear. He has a '[[Box]] of Bewilderment'. He also appears in the Season 3 episode, Horrid Henry Goes To The Theatre when he was helping the Penelope family find their way to the show. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Crabby Chris===\nCrabby Chris once babysat Horrid Henry but never came back after Henry hid her homework and spilt grapefruit juice on her jeans. She is only seen on a flashback in ''Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter''. She was voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Cross Colin===\nCross Colin appears in ''Horrid Henry's Wedding'' as the best man and one of Pimply Paul's friends.\n\nCrazy Cath\nHenry\u2019s grandma whom appears in multiple episodes for example: \u2018trip to Portugal\u2019, \u2018ONIONS\u2019 and \u2018Cath V Cath\u2019\n\n==D==\n\n===Dad===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Dad\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Trapped\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Wayne Forester]]\n| full_name          = Simon Daniels\n| nickname           = Silly Simon\n| occupation         = Works for Tingly Toothbrushes\n| spouse             = Mum\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Mum, Henry, Peter, Francis\n| children           = Henry, Peter\n| relatives          = Fussy Francis\n}}\n'''Dad''' is the father of Henry and Peter. He is always yelling at Henry, but very rarely at Peter. He often shouts \"Go to your room, now!\" Like Mum, he has never trusted Henry to be well behaved. He agrees with his wife almost all the time. He is also extremely healthy, making Henry and Peter very healthy packed lunches and cooking healthy dinners, much to Henry's disgust. Peter often shows off to Dad by being well behaved while Henry misbehaves. He punishes Henry by banning the TV and/or the computer, but mostly resorts to cancellation or reduction of pocket money, for example when Henry refuses not to come on a hike he starts deducting pocket money. He shows favouritism when it comes to Henry and Peter. He tends to believe the best of Peter and the worst of Henry as even if Henry was telling the truth, he will still dismiss it as \"rubbish\". When Peter was horrid, he will find excuses for him. A good example was that Peter sprayed Henry with a hose deliberately, even chasing him around the garden, but he ended up telling Henry that he should have got out of the way when Peter was \"watering the flowers\".  Although strict he appears to be more tolerant of Henry by giving him second chances. Also, he is often shown to be capable of distracting Henry enough that he behaves. He has curly brown hair and wears an orange sweater and a blue jacket. It is revealed that ''Gross Class Zero'' was his favourite show when he was a boy. At the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings'' it is revealed that his nickname is \"Silly Simon\". At the end of this episode it is also implied that Henry gets his horrid streak from him, while Peter gets his goody-goody streak from Fussy Uncle Francis. He is always on Mum's side and rarely lets Henry get his own way, however he sometimes agrees with Henry's point of view. He is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Dirty Dirk===\nHe is the Judge of the TV programme \"Hog House\".\n\n===Dizzy Dave===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Dave\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Dizzy Dave\n| species            = Human\n}}\nDizzy Dave is a boy in Henry's class who is always spinning around and knocking things over. He is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. His name was replaced with Rude Ralph's in Horrid Henry's Birthday Party, when Henry talks about a previous party at laser zap. A boy with brown hair, white skin, purple-ish top with orange shorts and a gleen bowl of green liquid may be him because of his sleepy face but this has not been confirmed yet.\n\n===Dr. Dettoll===\nDr. Dettoll is a doctor who gives injections. She only appears at the end of ''Horrid Henry's Injection''.\n\n=== Doddery Donald ===\nGreat Aunt Greta's brother. He mostly says \"Donald\". He only appears in ''Horrid Henry Plays Air Guitar''.\n\n==E==\n\n===Ed Banger===\nEd Banger is a [[Magic (illusion)|magician]], [[dancer]], [[ringmaster (circus)|ringmaster]], [[musician]] and the lead singer in the Killer Boy Rats. In the episode ''Horrid Henry and the Killer Boy Rats'' Ed Banger leaves the Killer Boy Rats and begins writing and singing \"nice songs\", much to Henry's ire and Peter's delight. After Henry gets up on stage during a concert and sings (loud and off-key) one of his Killer Boys Rats songs, his manager phones Henry and congratulates him. Henry is then given tickets to the next Killer Boy Rats concert. While on TV Ed says he is going back to being a Killer Boy Rats member and his manager explains that it was Henry inspired him to return to the music group. Henry and his family then go to the concert where the Killer Boy Rats sing a song (\"Gonna Be A Rock Star\") as a token of thanks and appreciation to Henry who is on stage with them as a drummer.\n\n===Evil Eddy Edwards===\nEvil Eddy Edwards is a milkman who has a rivalry with Pimply Paul as seen in Horrid Henry Delivers The Milk.\n\n==F==\n\n===Fang the Hamster===\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Fang\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Horrid Hamster\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| family             = Henry,Peter,Mum,Dad\n| relatives          = None\n}}\n\nFang is Henry's loyal, vicious [[hamster]]. He often feuds with Fluffy the Cat, and has a helpful ear when Henry needs someone to talk to. He is an unusual hamster in which he is up in the day, he sleeps in a bed and is able to say \"Yeah, yeah, yeah!\". He is also useful to Henry for when he plots revenge against an enemy. Fang acts like a [[dog]] and sniffs out missing Fluffy in one episode. In another episode, Fang had a major role, when he went missing. The family presumed him as dead, and when Henry found him a day later, he dressed Fang up as a [[poodle]], as a pose for the replacement pet for Peter. Sometimes he is mistaken for a rat which is what Moody Margaret calls him. His vocal effects are provided by [[Tamsin Heatley]].\n\n===Fearless Phantom===\nFearless Phantom is a TV superhero who Horrid Henry loves but he is scared of spiders.\n\n===Fiery Fiona===\nFiery Fiona is a girl in Henry's class, who appears a few times in the books but never in the TV series. She is shown to have a fiery temper.\n\n===Filthy Phil===\nHe is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Fluffy the Cat===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Fluffy\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| alias              = Fluffy the Cat.\n| species            = Cat\n| occupation         = Pet\n}}\nFluffy is the family's grey [[cat]], who feuds with Henry's [[hamster]], Fang. Fluffy is shown in most episodes sitting by the sitting room window sill at night and as she clicks the TV remote control button next to her in the first three series and swipes the tablet computer in the fourth series the scene changes to sunrise. Fluffy also gets dressed up as a mummy in the tale ''Horrid Henry and the Mummy''. Like Peter, she seems to have a vindictive streak towards Henry as she once framed him for eating several packets of a snack that Mum likes. Despite being female she is sometimes referred to as a \"he\". Peter is completely devoted to her, and never believes she does anything wrong, even though she started chasing Fang in one episode, and Peter said Fang started the fight.\n\n===Frosty Freeze Man===\nHe works at Frosty Freeze. He appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Abominable Snowman'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Big Freeze Wheeze''.\n\n===Frosty Steve===\nFrosty Steve works at Frosty Freeze. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Ice Cream Dream''.\n\n===Fussy Uncle Francis===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Francis\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings (only appearance)\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Fussy Uncle Francis\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Brother of Silly Simon\n| relatives          = Mum (sister), Dad (older brother), Henry (nephew), Peter (nephew)\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Aidan Cook\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nHenry's uncle and Dad's younger brother. Voiced by [[Aidan Cook]]. He has curly blonde hair which is similar to Peter's, just as Dad's hair is brown, like Henry's, although Dad also has curly hair. He wears a green jacket and orange tie and he only appears so far in ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings''. He is shown not to get on with Dad, as they argue often and this is also where a slightly childish aspect of Dad's personality is revealed. He is said to be fussy, as when he visits he inspects the staircase for dust when he comes in. At the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings'', he calls Dad \"Silly Simon\", which is presumably what he was called when he was a kid. At the end of this episode it is also implied that Peter gets his goody-goody streak from him, while Henry gets his horrid streak from Dad.\n\n==G==\n\n===Goody-Goody Gordon===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Gordon\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Fangmangler\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Goody-Goody Gordon\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Brainy Brian\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nGordon is one of Peter's best friends. He is a member of the Best Boys Club and is friends with Tidy Ted and Spotless Sam. He often speaks with a lisp. He is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]]. Gordon has black hair and dark skin. He wears a mustard-yellow jumper, white undershirt, and blue grey pants.\n\n===Gorgeous Gurinder===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Gurinder\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Secret Club\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Gorgeous Gurinder\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Gorgeous\n}}\nGorgeous Gurinder is a beautiful and gorgeous girl who appears to be best friends with Singing Soraya and Lazy Linda. They are both members of the Secret Club. She has brown skin, purple-black hair, and wears a white shirt with periwinkle flower prints, pink trousers, and beautiful white ballet pumps. In the later episodes, She also good knowledge of makeup products as she is seen teaching Henry how to put on handcream.\n\n===Grandma===\nShe is Henry and Peter's grandmother, and Mum's mother. She always gives nice presents to Henry and Peter. She only appears in the books.\n\n===Granny===\nShe is Henry and Peter's grandmother, and Dad's mother. She only appears in Horrid Henry's Christmas Lunch, and she is shown to be quite bossy.\n\n===Grandpa===\nHe is Henry and Peter's grandfather, and Dad's father. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Christmas Cracker'' when he visits Henry's family for Christmas lunch on Christmas Day.\n\n===Greasy Greta===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Greta\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Demon Dinner Lady\n| last               = Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady\n| portrayer          = Sue Elliot-Nichols\n| nickname           = Demon Dinner Lady\n| alias              = Greasy Greta\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| children           = Pasty Patsy\n}} \nGreasy Greta is the lady from the counter in the school cafeteria who was in charge of the packed lunch room. She first appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Demon Dinner Lady''. She was sent to look after the kids in the lunch room because they were always playing with their food. She always took the children's treats and ate them, but she ran away after she ate hot chili biscuits Henry brought in. However, in the TV series, she ate far too many treats and was wheeled out of the school on a trolley, by Soggy Sid. She is voiced by [[Sue Elliot Nicholls|Sue Elliot-Nichols]]. She returns in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the Book, Horrid Henry's Nightmare. This time she inspects lunch boxes to promote healthy eating. She has maroon-colored hair and crimson-pink skin. She is fired on the spot when Miss Oddbod catches her in the cupboard eating the confiscated sweets that were supposed to be donated to charity.\n\n===Great Aunt Greta===\nVoiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]], Great Aunt Greta is the great aunt of Horrid Henry. She thinks that Henry is a little girl called Henrietta (or Henny in ''Horrid Henry's Underpants''), and that Peter is a teenager. This is reflected in the presents that she sends to the boys. Although Henry's Mum and Dad have told her countless times that Henry is a boy and that Peter is six, Greta refuses to believe this, and usually doesn't hear, most likely due to her senility. Her senility is such that she once cooked cat food for the boys and believed that Fluffy is a dog named Fido. She also mistook it to be the middle of the night when in fact it was only half past five in the afternoon. She wears a light pink sweater, a gold button studded in her white blouse, dark pink skirt, lavender shoes and a walking stick.\n\n===Greedy Graham===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Graham\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = Wayne Forester\n| nickname           = Greedy Graham\n| gender             = Male\n}}\nGreedy Graham is a brown-haired obese boy who is always hungry and is often seen eating carrots and junk food in the earlier episodes. He is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. Voiced by Wayne Forester. He wears an orange shirt with blue outlines, blue sweatpants and red sneakers. He has a Cockney accent in some early episodes and a Cornish accent for the majority of his appearances. It is stated by Aerobic Al that he ate his gloss class zero comic in Horrid Henry's Unhappy Day.\n\n==H==\n===Horrid Henry===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Henry\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Tricks or Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| nickname           = Horrid Henry\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Peter (brother), Mum and Dad\n| children           = none\n| relatives          = Steve (cousin) Ruby (aunt) Great Aunt Greta (great aunt)\n}}\n\nHenry is the main character of the series and is portrayed as a determined and relentless young boy. He believes that life is unfair as the rest of the world is against him, so he fights \"against the tyranny of adults\". He is resistant to defeat as teachers, relatives and babysitters in the series try their best to avoid him. Even his parents argue over whose turn it is to look after him.\n\nHenry is very selfish, inconsiderate, stubborn, and rarely learns from his mistakes. He can also be bluntly honest, as seen when he tells his mother's boss what she calls her at work behind her back and is unafraid of telling people how much he hates them right to their faces. However, he is willing to act nice and collude with Margaret and even Peter, but only if it means he will get to have his own way. Most likely because of his young age, Henry can get frightened by talk of ghosts or monsters, and in one episode, is revealed to have a [[fear of needles]]. He is very imaginative, as he indulges in fantasies, usually transforming into terrifying creatures and attacking the source of his frustrations, and often has \"Eureka moments\" when the stories mention what he thinks is a \"spectacularly wonderful idea\". In every story, there is something Henry has to get or do (or occasionally avoid doing) and the ensuing chaos is the consequence of this overriding desire.\n\nWhenever Henry thinks of a plan it is simply to get his own way, never to make trouble purely for its own sake. He is more often than not seen taking life very seriously and he sincerely believes in what he is doing, making him something of a complex character as well. It has also been further hinted that deep down, Henry never really means to be horrid, and only acts that way as a wanting to get attention and needing to feel important, especially when dealing with his younger brother Peter, implying he has low self-esteem.\n\n===Helpful Hari===\nShe is invited to Peter's party in ''Perfect Peter's Pirate Party'' and is in Peter's class.\n\n==I==\n\n===Inky Ian===\n\nInky Ian is a pupil who isn't very much in Henry's [[classroom]] who is only seen in the book version ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend''.\n\n==J==\n\n===Jazzy Jim===\nJazzy Jim is a minor character in Henry's class who likes music. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Arch Enemy'', ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend'' and ''Horrid Henry's Bake Off''.\n\n===Jolly Josh===\n\nJolly Josh is a boy in Henry's class who is always playing and joking. He's shown to be friends with Henry in ''Horrid Henry Tidies Up''. he has a darker skin tone but still lighter than goody-goody gorden,brainy brian and the mossies.\n\n===Jolly Josh's father===\nJolly Josh's father only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Nits'' when he complains about the letter sent home.\n\n===Jumping Jeffrey===\nJeffrey is a boy who loves jumping like a [[kangaroo]] at Henry's karate class.\n\n==K==\n\n===Killer Boy Rats===\nHorrid Henry's favourite band. The lead singer is Ed Banger, Henry's idol.\n\n===Kind Kasim===\nKind Kasim is a minor character in Henry's class. He doesn't appear in the picture of Henry's class.\n\n===Kind Kelly===\nKind Kelly is a girl in Peter's class who once let Henry borrow her mobile phone and is so kind. She is mentioned in ''Horrid Henry and the King Of Bling'' and appears in a photo in ''Horrid Henry, Nothing But the Truth''. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Kung-Fu Kate===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Kate\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Thank You Letter\n| nickname           = Kung-Fu Kate\n}}\nKung-Fu Kate is a girl in Henry's class who is always doing Kung-Fu. She is also friends with Margaret.\n\n==L==\n\n===Lazy Linda===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Linda\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| nickname           = Lazy Linda\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n}}\nThe laziest girl in Henry's class. She is often seen sleeping. She doesn't talk very often, but when she does, she uses the word \"like\" quite a lot and has a [[cockney accent]]. She is a member of the Secret Club, which she initially joined as a replacement for Susan. At some point, Margaret fired her and Susan returned, however at some point Linda returned as well. She and Susan are foes and sometimes friends. Linda wears a light green shirt, red overall dress and green sneakers. She is voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Lisping Lily===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Lily\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sleepover\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Lisping Lily\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Sister of Nick & Mike\n| family             = Nick (brother), Parents, Mike (brother)\n}}\nLisping Lily is New Nick's younger sister; a toddler, who is largely infatuated with Henry (pronouncing his name \"Henwy\") and is known for her noticeable lisp. Her common catchphrases in the book are \"I love you, Henwy.\" and \"Will you mawwy with me, Henwy?\". She wears a blue tunic with a ribbon, and dark blue overalls and she also has a doll that squirts Henry in the face from its mouth/nose.\n\n===Little girl===\nA little girl appears as a minor character in ''Horrid Henry's New Shoes'' when she is buying trousers at the same time as Henry and Mum.\n\n==M==\n\n===Mad Martin===\nMartin is a teenager who babysat henry once.it is currently unknown who he is voiced by.\n\n===Maggie===\nThe presenter of one of Peter's favourite TV programmes, \"Manners with Maggie\" which was one of Henry's least favourite programmes. The show stopped airing after Maggie was dragged off the set screaming following her reaction to Henry's terrible manners.\n\n===Marvin the Maniac===\nThe presenter of one of Henry's favourite TV programmes, Gross-Out. He invites Henry to appear on the show after he wrote to him. He eventually appeared on underpants separate to Henry's old Gross-Out pants.\n\n===Magic Rabbit===\nThe rabbit appears in ''Happy Birthday Peter''.\n\n===Magic Martha===\nMartha is a girl who does magic tricks In Henry's class.\n\n===Milksop Miles===\nThe author of Peter's favourite book, \"The Happy Nappy\". He is Henry's least favourite writer and only appears in \"Horrid Henry's Author Visit\".\n\n===Mini Minnie===\nShe is invited to Peter's party in ''Perfect Peter's Pirate Party'' and is in Peter's class.\n\n===Mischievous Mike===\nHe is one of Horrid Henry's friends who loves [[Airplane|planes]]. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Miss Battle-Axe===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Boudicca Battle-Axe\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = [[Aidan Cook]]<br>[[Anjelica Huston]]\n| nickname           = Miss Battle-Axe\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Teacher]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Miss Battle-Axe, Henry's teacher\n| family             = Mrs. Alicia Battle-Axe (mother) &  Our Lady Giddyantus School Headmistress Battle-Axe (twin sister)\n}}\n\n'''Miss Boudicca Battle-Axe''' is a strict, sadistic schoolteacher who talks with a Scottish accent. She teaches [[Horrid Henry (Character)|Horrid Henry]], and many of his classmates such as [[Rude Ralph]], [[Moody Margaret]] and [[Sour Susan]]. She seems to have a particular disliking towards Henry, which would be because it is usually his horrid behaviour which disrupts her class. She once said that Henry's class was the worst she ever taught. In very few episodes, her mother, Mrs Battle-Axe, has appeared, who appears to discipline her daughter greatly. She wears pointy glasses and has gray hair. She also wears a green cardigan, pale chartreuse top, brown skirt, and brownish stockings. In ''Horrid Henry Delivers a Message'', it is shown that Miss Battle-Axe secretly has a crush on [[Soggy Sid]]. Miss Battle-Axe is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]] ( wayne forester in an interview with BFI ) and portrayed by [[Anjelica Huston]].\n\nDespite hating Henry's class it is apparent that Miss Battle-Axe is tough enough to survive teaching it, as it has been mentioned that all of Henry's teachers prior to her had quit because of him.\n\nIn the season 4 episode ''Horrid Henry's Movie Moments'' it is revealed she has an identical twin sister who is also called ''Miss Battle-Axe'' but is Headmistress of Our Lady Giddiantus and talks with a [[Received pronunciation|posh voice]]. However in the film the Headmistress of Our Lady Giddiantus is named as \"Miss Dinesta Clutterbuck\" on the sign outside.\n\n===Miss Impatience Tutu===\nMiss Impatience Tutu is a dance teacher who first appeared in ''Horrid Henry's Dance Class''. In the TV series, she is referred to as Madame Tutu and speaks with a French accent when talking to her class, but speaks with an English accent when talking to Henry individually. She seems to be a lot nicer in the TV series than in the books. She has blonde hair in a bun and wears a black leotard over a pale pink jumpsuit .she organised the show \"I hear thunder\" in the episode horrid henrys dance class. she is Voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Miss Lovely===\n\n'''Miss Lydia Lovely''' is Peter's teacher. As her name suggests, she has a gentle nature. She is very proud of Peter's progress and behaviour and is always saying nice things about him to his parents. However, on odd occasions (such as when Peter hands in a \"Why I Hate My Teacher\" essay, which he wrote as \"Why I Love My Teacher\", which Henry edited the night before) she had lost her temper. She is often seen in the library, on library duty when she's in the reading area. During early seasons, she spoke with an Indian accent, which fitted considering she appears to be Asian, however, later on in the series, she speaks with a Welsh accent. She is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Miss Thumper===\nMiss Thumper only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Dance Class'', where she works.\n\n===Moody Margaret===\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #800080\n| name               = Moody Margaret\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| franchise          = \n| image              = Moody Margaret.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Moody Margaret, as she appears in the book series (With an edit done by Horrid Henry)\n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = ''[[Horrid Henry (book)|Horrid Henry]]'' (''Horrid Henry and Moody Margaret'')\n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = Scarlet Stitt\n| voice              = Sue Elliot-Nichols\n| full_name          = Margaret Millicent Mordeates Smythe\n| nickname           = Moody<br>Frogface<br>Bogey Brain\n| alias              = \"The Fangmangler\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Simon|first=Francesca|title=Horrid Henry and the Fangmangler|year=1997|publisher=Orion Children's Books|location=UK|isbn=978-1-85881-353-0|pages=22}}</ref>\n| species            = [[Human]]\n| gender             = [[Female]]\n| occupation         = [[Student]]\n| family             = '''Mother''': Unnamed<br>'''Father''': Unnamed\n| spouse             = \n| significant_other   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| religion           = [[Europe]]an\n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| nationality        = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\nMoody Margaret is a moody girl who is always fussing and wanting to get her own way. She is a spoilt brat. She is portrayed as the secondary main antagonist in the series and serves as Horrid Henry's archenemy. She lives next door to Horrid Henry and her best friend is Sour Susan. She has magenta hair in a spiky ponytail.\nHenry and Margaret are enemies; Margaret has a secret club and Henry has the Purple Hand Gang. She has an ability of screaming and always competes with Henry. She might have a crush on Henry, because in ''Perfect Peter's Revenge'', she is happy when Peter sends her a forged letter that said Henry loves and wants to marry Margaret. This is also seen in other episodes. She wears a violet [[tank top]] with white stripes, green [[cardigan (sweater)|cardigan]] and a bottle-green skirt. Margaret, however, occasionally assists Henry in his plans, as seen in ''Horrid Henry's Horrid Revenge'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Big Dig'', though under the word of being the leader of the Purple Hand Gang for a day or a month or even a whole year you will never know how long it will be maybe a week or even every month/year/day/second/minute. She is voiced by Sue Elliot-Nichols. In the episode ''Horrid Henry Rockstar'' it is suggested that her full name is Margaret Millicent Maudita Smythe which she also uses in subsequent episodes. However she denies this when Rude Ralph asks her if this is true.\n\nAs the primary antagonist of the series, Moody Margaret is the most prominent arch-enemy of the series' protagonist, [[Horrid Henry]]. When Francesca Simon was in the process of creating this character, she suggested a boy called Moody Martin. However, her husband did not approve of the idea as it would be too much like Horrid Henry the main character. Thus, Martin became a female called Margaret. Margaret is depicted as being a self-absorbed, grumpy, spiteful, and cantankerous girl who shares an intense rivalry with Henry, and their opposing neighborhood clubs continuously develop practical jokes or conspiracies against one another. They have resorted to each other's companionship when left with no other options, but nonetheless detest one another and continuously plot against one another, especially in an attempt to soil each other's reputations. Margaret has a tendency to gloat about her various accomplishments in a ridiculously [[narcissistic]] fashion, looking down on others and domineering her friends and peers. True to this, she is resented by her best friend Sour Susan because of her rudeness, but Susan seems to have no other choice than to reluctantly obey Margaret's constant commands. Margaret viciously domineers the Secret Club in various plots formulated against Henry's corresponding Purple Hang Gang, and the two opposing sides share a mutual animosity. She is used to having her own way and is capable of releasing violent, piercing screeches when her demands remain unfulfilled.\n\n====Live-action====\n\n[[File:Scarlet Stitt Moody Margaret.jpg|150px|thumb|Movie poster for ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]'' featuring Scarlet Stitt as Moody Margaret.]]\n* Scarlet Stitt portrays Moody Margaret in the 2011 movie, ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]''. At the beginning of the movie, She, Sour Susan and [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Singing Soroya|Singing Soroya]] are in the Secret Club treehouse eating biscuits and arguing. Henry disguises himself as a spy, steals the biscuits and runs away but Margaret has also stolen his mighty magnet yoyo. Later, on his way home from school, Henry dodges a water balloon thrown by Margaret. He ducks behind a lamppost, waits for Margaret to walk past, throws a balloon filled with water that hovers over her head and finally, flicks a yoyo at the balloon which bursts and soaks Margaret. Margaret shrieks and throws another balloon at Henry but he ducks and it hits [[Perfect Peter]] instead.<br>The next day at school, Margaret hangs a pail filled with purple paint over the door, ties one end of a rope to it and the other end to the door's handle. Instead of Henry who gets painted, it is their teacher [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Battle-Axe|Miss Battle-Axe]] who falls for the trick. Battle-Axe blames it on Henry, giving Margaret a lucky escape. The next day, Miss Battle Axe's class is moved to [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Lovely|Miss Lovely]]'s class after the head sacks Miss Battle-Axe for not controlling the pupils. Margaret snatches Henry's bag and Henry tries to pull it back, resulting in a pot of \"Exploding Gross-Glue\" placed by the school inspectors to fly out. The glue bursts and hits Miss Lovely in the face. She too gets sacked and the head, and [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Oddbod|Miss Oddbod]] bans Henry from entering the school's talent contest. As the school is going bankrupt, many children transfer to another school. Margaret and Henry both get transferred to a girls' school (Henry's Great-Aunt Greta transferred him there as she thinks he is a girl).<br>The girls in the school attack Henry for being a boy and try to attack Margaret too for being with Henry. The two of them escape and form an alliance to save their school. They do this by making Henry sneak into the talent contest and win it so he would be so famous but the plan fails. They try another plan which involves Henry going onto a game show to win the big cash prize so he can give it to Miss Oddbod so she can give it to the school inspectors to bribe them away as they were the ones trying to get the school closed down under the order of the head of a boys' school called [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Vic Van Wrinkle|Vic Van Wrinkle]]. However, although Henry wins, the Best Boy's Club, Miss Lovely and Miss Oddbod had got Vic and the inspectors arrested so she lets Henry keep the money. At the very end, Margaret is seen in a fairy costume at Henry's party.\n\n====Animation====\n\n* In 2006's ''[[Horrid Henry (TV series)|Horrid Henry]]'' TV series, Moody Margaret is voiced by Sue Elliot-Nichols and is the series' most recurring villain. Margaret is represented just like she is in the books and seen as Henry's rival. However she is shown to be smarter. It has been hinted in some episodes, especially in series 4, that she may in fact admire Henry and wants to be his friend. She has shown a very keen interest in wanting to join The Purple Hand Gang. She might have a crush on Henry, e.g. in \"Perfect Peter's Revenge\", she was happy when Peter send her a forged letter that said Henry loves and wants to marry Margaret. On Henry's side he pictures himself marrying Margaret when he imagines himself in the future in the episodes ''Horrid Henry Gets Married'' and ''Horrid Henry's Birthday Bonanza'' although he does not know why this is. From the Series 3 episode ''Horrid Henry Rockstar'' she names herself as Margaret Millicent Maudita Smythe. However she denies this when Rude Ralph asks her if this is true in the first instance. her shouting is able to crack glass as seen in moody Margaret moves in.\n\n===Moody Margaret's parents===\nMoody Margaret's parents give her everything her heart desires.\nMargaret's mum is voiced by Joanna Ruiz and has dark magenta hair while her dad is voiced by Aidan Cook and has grey hair. In Horrid Henry on TV Henry gets these parents but then gets kicked out because he sat on Margaret's Dad's Chair.\n\n===Mouldy Myra===\nShe is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Mr and Mrs Mossy===\nMr and Mrs Mossy are characters who first appeared in ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests''.\nMr Mossy is Mum's boss, although sometimes Mrs Mossy is shown to be Mum's boss. Mr Mossy also appears in TV series ''Horrid Henry Changes a Nappy''. At the start of ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests'' Mr Mossy sabotages all of the tricks of Henry. The Mossys appear to be of black descent and it is revealed at the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests'' that Mr Mossy's first name is Timothy in the TV series, although it is given as Reginald in the book. When Mr Mossy was a child he was called \"Terrible Timothy\". Mr. Mossy is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]] and Mrs. Mossy is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Mrs Battle-Axe===\nMrs Battle-Axe is Miss Boudicca Battle Axe's mother. She disciplines her daughter greatly and is a nice, old woman who likes Henry, in a sharp contrast to her daughter's meanness and dislike of Henry.\n\n===Mrs Crunch===\nMrs Crunch is the guide at Our Town Museum, runs Camp Sunshine and the Happiest Family competition. she has an upper-class English accent.\n\n===Mrs/Miss Oddbod===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Cynthia Oddbod\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's School Fair\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| nickname           = Mrs Oddbod (book)<br />Miss Oddbod (TV series)\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Head Teacher]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Miss\n}}\nThe head teacher/principal of Ashton Primary School. Her name is revealed as Mrs Oddbod in the story ''Horrid Henry's School Project'' in the book ''Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb''. However she is addressed as \"Miss\" rather than \"Mrs\" Oddbod in the TV series and the film. Despite her title as head teacher, she is somewhat kinder to Henry than Miss Battle-Axe. She is generally good-natured but can act strange at times, for example, she was the \"time capsule thief\" who dug up time capsules from the school grounds at night. Her first name is Cynthia. This was revealed in the episode ''Horrid Henry, Horrid Headmaster''. She and Chris, the woman who works at the old people's home, have a good friendship, as seen in ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Walking Stick Gang''. She is voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]] in the series. She has ginger hair in a ponytail and wears round glasses, a lavender dress, with a beige collar and button, and a violet hairband in the TV series.\n\n===Mum===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mum\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'' (Books)<br>''Horrid Henry Tricks And Treats'' (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = Bookshop worker\n| spouse             = Dad (aka \"Silly Simon\") (husband)\n| gender             = Female\n| family             = Henry, Peter, Dad\n| children           = Henry, Peter\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = \n<!--| full_name      = Elizabeth Daniels-->\n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\n\n'''Mum''' is the mother of Henry and Peter, the wife of Dad (\"Silly Simon\") and the younger sister of Rich Aunt Ruby. Mum is usually almost never angry with Peter usually referring to him as \"Sweetie Pie\" and \"Bunny Hop\" etc. Henry on the other hand is usually getting yelled at by his parents, and when he does something horrid, Mum will say \"Go to your room now, Henry!\" or \"No TV, sweets or pocket money for a week!\" or simply \"Don't be horrid, Henry!\" Despite the fact that Peter's perfect behavior leads to Mum being proud of him in the episode \"The Fairy Dance\" Mum finally yells at Peter which of course makes Henry happy. Mum also yells at Peter, for being horrid and chucking food at her, in ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day''. She wears a purple cardigan with a pinkish shirt under. She has blonde hair and wears glasses. Mum also wears blue jeans and pink ballet shoes. It is known that she has a sister named Ruby, a brother-in-law named Fussy Francis. Her mother is Henry and Peter's grandmother, but it's unknown who her father is. She is currently voiced by Tamsin Heatley, and Siobhan Hayes played her role in the ''Horrid Henry Movie'' as well.\n\n==N==\n\n===Nasty Nicola===\nNasty Nicola joins Henry's class in ''Horrid Henry and the New Best Friend'' and appears nice to begin with but turns out to be nasty and vicious. She has light red hair in braided pigtails and wears a teal sweatshirt. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Needy Neil===\nNeedy Neil is Weepy William's younger brother. He is in Miss Lovely's class.\n\n===New Nick===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Nick\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sleepover\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = New Nick\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Parents, Lily (sister), Mike (brother)\n}}\n\nNick is a boy who joined Henry's class as a \"new\" boy. He makes friends with Henry soon after he joins Henry's class and invites him to stay all night at his house. When Henry arrives, he has a thoroughly miserable evening. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===New Nick's parents===\nThey have two dogs and run a karaoke club of Scandinavian folk songs. They're very loud and only appear in ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover'' and ''Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson''. They are voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]] and [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Ninius Nerdon===\nMr Nerdon was a teacher first featured in the story ''Horrid Henry's New Teacher''. After a prank pulled by Henry involving Peter, he collapsed and Miss Battle-Axe took over the class. \n\nIn the TV series, he was the substitute teacher for Henry's class when Miss Battle-Axe got the flu, although a prank involving frogs made him run away screaming from the class. He is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]]. He appears in the adaptation of ''Horrid Henry's New Teacher'' and later appears in Season 5 for the Brainbox of the Year contest.\n\n===Norwegian Norris===\nNorris is a Norwegian boy in Henry's class making his first appearance in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the book Horrid Henry's Nightmare. When there is a practice in the school he does not like, such as the lunchbox inspections and taking names out of the hat to see who should look after the class chicken, he wails that it wouldn't happen in Norway.\n\n===Nudie Foodie===\nMr Nudie Foodie is a celebrity chef based on [[Jamie Oliver]]. In ''Horrid Henry and the Nudie Foodie'', he visits the school to improve school dinners. He is sent away after Henry adds extra ingredients to his pasta sauce to make it taste bad. His name is a parody on the BBC programme ''[[The Naked Chef]]''.\n\n===Nurse Needle===\nNurse Needle is a nurse who appears in ''Horrid Henry's Injection''. She tried to give Henry an injection, but Henry pretended to be sick and was sent home.\n\n==P==\n\n===Park keeper===\nHe works in the park and employs Henry in ''Horrid Henry Gets A Job''. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Pasty Patsy===\nPasty Patsy is the daughter of Greasy Greta and appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the book ''Horrid Henry's Nightmare''. When Henry asked her why she didn't get her lunchbox inspected, she replied that she is Greta's daughter and she could have what she wanted, much to Henry's surprise. She then opened her lunchbox and ate a handful of sweets and treats, while Henry's mouth watered.\n\n===Patrolling Patrick and Vigilant Vincent===\nIn some stories and episodes of Horrid Henry, there are some security guards that appear. Their names are Patrolling Patrick and Vigilant Vincent. They are voiced by Wayne Forester and Aidan Cook.\n\n===Perfect Peter===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Perfect Peter\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| franchise          = \n| image              = [https://hhenrystories.files.wordpress.com/2011/11/peter.jpg]\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'' (Books)<br>''Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats'' (TV series)\n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = Ross Marron\n| voice              = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Perfect<br>Worm (as [[Horrid Henry|Henry]] and his friends call him)\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Human]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| occupation         = [[Student]]\n| family             = '''Brother''': [[Horrid Henry]]<br>'''Mother''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Mum|Mum]]<br>'''Father''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Dad|Dad ('Silly Simon')]]\n| spouse             = \n| significant_other   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = '''Cousins''': [[Stuck-up Steve]], [[Prissy Polly]], [[Vomiting Vera]] and [[Pimply Paul]] <br>'''Aunt''': [[Rich Aunt Ruby]]<br>'''Great aunt''': [[Great aunt Greta]]<br>'''Grandmother''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Grandma|Grandma]]<br>'''Uncle''': Fussy Francis\n| religion           = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| nationality        = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\n'''[[Perfect Peter]]''' is Henry's perfect younger brother. He is often referred to as a \"worm\" by Henry. Peter has a very effeminate attitude, liking flowers much like [[Walter the Softy]] in the [[Dennis the Menace (UK comics)|Dennis the Menace]] comic strips and [[Dennis the Menace (1996 TV series)|cartoon series]], believes in fairy tales, and is known to always do as he is told and treat others with respect. On several occasions, however, he has revealed that he is in reality, very whiny and spoiled. It is obvious that Peter likes to get back at Henry with the help of his parents, and he always [[Emotional blackmail|emotionally bribes]] them (e.g.: \"You're the best mum in the world! So Henry won't be getting any biscuits will he?\"), resulting in his parents favouring him. Aside from being spoiled, he shows aspects of being sort of like Moody Margaret, except that instead of using a bossy tone, he adopts a crying and sorrowful look to get what he wants.\n\nOften, Henry gets into trouble as a result of Peter telling Mum or Dad when he has done something wrong, usually with the phrases \"Mum/Dad! Henry's being horrid/mean!\" or \"Mum/Dad! Henry called me a [[worm]]/a toad/told me to shut up!\", and he even blames Henry for the most minor offences. He has been known to blame Henry for things Henry doesn't do. He is also similar to his friends as he hates dirt, is always tidy and always does as he is told, unlike Henry. He also expects praise for even the most minor things, such as \"being normal\", using his fork and knife, and also shows off how good he is, especially when Henry is being reprimanded. This, and the fact that he always asks them politely.\n\nAt times, Peter can be desperate for praise and attention; he gets his toys out just to tidy them again in the episode \"Horrid Henry And The Best Boys Club\". In the same episode, it is hinted he sees the other members of \"The Best Boys Club\" as underlings rather than actual friends as he immediately refuses Gordon's suggestion of taking turns to decide things. This suggests that he only acts perfect because he gets praised. At times, he tries to take credit for Henry's rare good deeds, as shown in ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'', and in ''Horrid Henry Horrid Headmaster'', when he recorded what Henry said when Henry discovered he had to fill end of term reports (\"No holiday for me, then.\"), then modified it into \"No holiday!\", causing the students to rebel. He seldom defies orders or complains about said orders, though it has been revealed that his sweet-natured personality is soiled with narcissism; he has indeed defied adults or rules in revenge against Henry or while attempting to frame him, and he derives pleasure from Henry's suffering and punishments for poor behavior, implying that he may actually not be much better than his brother. Despite all this, Henry will still help Peter out on occasion, such as rescuing him from a falling shelf in the cellar in ''Horrid Henry Trapped''.\n\n====Live-action====\n* In 2011's ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]'', Perfect Peter is shown as a pure goody-goody and never shows his bad side. He is one of the very few people who help save the school from [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Vic Van Wrinkle|Vic Van Wrinkle]].\n\n====Animation====\n* In 2006's ''[[Horrid Henry (TV series)|Horrid Henry]]'' TV series, Perfect Peter is the most recurring character apart from Henry.\n\n===Perky Parveen===\nShe is in Peter's class and is invited to Peter's birthday party. She is mentioned in ''Perfect Peter's Birthday Party''.\n\n===Pimply Paul===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Paul Peregrine\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Pimply Paul\n| species            = Human\n| spouse             = Polly\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Polly, Vera\n| children           = Vomiting Vera\n| relatives          = Mum, Dad, Henry, Peter\n}}\n\nThe husband of Prissy Polly, who is a milkman and lives in a world of self pity and misery. He and Henry have a mutual hatred for each other, because Henry\u2019s a brat and Paul\u2019s a sour puss. He is a fan of [[rugby football|Rugby]], as revealed in Horrid Henry Cooks a Meal. He and Henry eventually develop a father-son relationship and start seeing each other eye-to-eye when Henry helps him with his route. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Prissy Polly===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Polly Penelope\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Prissy Polly\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| children           = Vera\n| relatives          = Henry, Peter, Mum, Dad, Ruby, Steve, Greta, Francis\n}}\n\nHenry's fussy, childish, ditzy, and uptight cousin who is usually seen smiling, until she reaches her breaking point. She marries Pimply Paul in Horrid Henry's Wedding and together, they had a daughter, Vera. Polly and Henry hate each other, and she wants everything to be her way, all the time (even to the discomfort of others, including her own family). She is voiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]]. She mostly wears a pink top, blue jeans, with a cyan blue sash-belt has curly blonde hair and wears beautiful pink high heel pumps. But in the film, she had her in a side braid with a yellow ribbon on the top of her head and she wore a cream dress with yellow and gold roses on it and a gold bracelet.\n\n==R==\n\n===Rabid Rebecca===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Rebecca Rancid\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter (Books and TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Rabid Rebecca, Miss Rancid\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = Babysitter\n| gender             = Female\n}}\n'''Rabid Rebecca''' is the toughest [[teenager]] in town, and is very strict. She once babysat Henry and Peter. Henry had a tough job getting rid of her, eventually succeeding after discovering that she was [[arachnophobia|scared of spiders]]. She has very large teeth and these are always visible even when her mouth is shut. She is introduced in [[Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter]] and makes a reappearance in ''Revenge of the Bogey Babysitter'' in the books. In the TV series she also appears in ''Horrid Henry's Smelly Stuff'', ''Horrid Henry's Haircut'', ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher'', and ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend'' in the audience at the match. She makes a cameo appearance in ''Horrid Henry and the Killer Boy Rats'', when she is shocked and is seen when Henry sings, \"Slimy, slimy, slimy!\" and Dad says, \"Don't be horrid, Henry!\" in the audience. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols. She appears as Miss Rancid, the substitute teacher in ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher'' and she is fired when Miss Oddbod sees her chasing Peter. She is training to become a hairdresser.\n\n===Razor Ron===\nRazor Ron is a barber who hates children. He cuts Henry's hair in ''Horrid Henry's Haircut''.\n\n===Rich Aunt Ruby===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ruby\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Christmas (Books and TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Rich Aunt Ruby\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Mother of Stuck-up Steve\n| family             = Steve\n| children           = [[#Stuck-up Steve|Steve]]\n| relatives          = Mum (sister), Dad, Henry, Peter, Paul, Polly, Vera, Greta, Grandma\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = \n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nHenry's wealthy aunt, Mum's sister and Stuck-Up Steve's mother. She is shown to be a very posh lady and she's dressed very fashionable, and she speaks with a posh-sounding accent and she was first seen in Horrid Henry's Christmas, where she buys Steve loads of great presents and Henry \"somehow\" managed to help himself to a few of them by switching the labels, she was next seen in the episode [[Horrid Henry's Haunted House]], where Henry scares her and Steve away from their house and gets to play with all Steve's toys. She has previously been seen in ''Horrid Henry Dines at Restaurant Le Posh'', where she took Steve and Henry's family to a fancy French restaurant, and orders Mum, Dad and Peter the things they don't want. She also spoils Steve greatly and buys him anything and everything he wants and she and Steve live in a very large house. She has burgundy-purple hair, like Steve. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Rude Ralph===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ralph\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Tricks and Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Aidan Cook]]\n| nickname           = Rude Ralph\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n}}\n'''Rude Ralph''' is Horrid Henry's best friend, who lives the life of luxury that Henry dreams of having. He gladly assists Henry in many of his plans, including plots to raid [[Moody Margaret]]'s Secret Club, with him being a member of Henry's \"Purple Hand Gang\". Contrary to his alliterative nickname, he is actually much more friendly, laid-back, and sensible than Henry. Unlike Henry, he doesn\u2019t mind eating healthy food or hanging out with girls, and he even befriends Peter in a few episodes. He wears a red hoodie and white capri pants. Besides Henry, he is often seen with Al and Bert. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Rude Ralph's dad===\nRude Ralph's dad cheers Ralph on in ''Horrid Henry's Sports Day'' and also appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Go Kart''.\n\n===Rude Ralph's mum===\nRude Ralph's mum picks Ralph up from Henry's in ''Horrid Henry's Fairy Dance'' and is seen calling Henry's Dad on ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover''. She was also seen in ''Horrid Henry Gets The Message'', ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Pass'' and ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Panto'' where she was seeing her son performing in the school panto. She is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n==S==\n\n===Singing Soraya===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Soraya\n| nickname           = Singing Soraya\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n}}\nAn Indian girl in Henry's class who loves singing. She even sounds like she's singing when she's talking normally. Soraya wears a yellow blouse with blue pants and orange [[keds]]. Voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Slimy Sammy===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Sammy\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Perfect Peter's Pen Pal\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Slimy Sammy, Super Sammy\n| species            = Human\n}}\nSammy first appeared in the episode Perfect Peter's Pen Pal. He stays at Peter's house and attempts to steal his stamp collection, as well as getting Henry into trouble. Despite the fact he appears to be French and speaks French, he talks with a German-sounding accent. Peter first calls him Super Sammy. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Snappy Croc===\nSnappy Croc is a [[crocodile|toy crocodile]] who was first seen in ''Horrid Henry's Bathtime''.\n\n===Soggy Sid===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Sidmouth Soggington\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = Aidan Cook\n| nickname           = Soggy Sid, Mr. Soggington, Sidmouth\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = \n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = \n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| voice              = \n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| occupation         = PE teacher\n}}\nSoggy Sid is Horrid Henry's swimming teacher and the school's sport coach. He also appears in some episodes as the caretaker of the school. In one episode, his name is revealed to be Sidmouth Soggington. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Sour Susan===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Susan\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Tricks or Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]<br />[[Helena Barlow]]\n| nickname           = Sour Susan\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| family             = Vicious Vicky (younger sister)\n}}\n\nSour Susan is the best friend of Moody Margaret. She always has a sour look on her face and often says \"Yeah, Henry.\" when Margaret offends or annoys him. She acts as a budgie and sidekick to Moody Margaret, but often has fallouts with her. She has a baby sister called Vicious Vicky. In TV Series, she has orange hair and wears a lime dress with dark green effects. In ''Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb'', she joins the Purple Hand Gang, and warns Henry about Margaret's stinkbomb. She is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]] and portrayed by [[Helena Barlow]].\n\n===Spotless Sam===\nSpotless Sam is one of Peter's friends and a member of the Best Boys Club. He is voiced by Emma Tate. He has black hair and wears a white shirt with blue stripes, and blue [[capri pants]].\n\n===Stone-Age Steven===\nStone-Age Steven is a minor character in Henry's class. He likes pretending to be a caveman.\n\n===Stuck-Up Steve===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Steve\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| last               = Ongoing\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Stuck-up Steve\n| species            = Human\n| spouse             = Unknown\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Son of Rich Aunt Ruby\n| family             = [[#Rich Aunt Ruby|Ruby]]\n| children           = none\n| relatives          = [[#Horrid Henry|Henry]], [[#Perfect Peter|Peter]], [[#Dad|Dad]], Mum, Grandma, Grandpa, Paul, Polly, Vera, Greta\n}}\n\nSteve is Henry's Stuck up Cousin. Henry calls him \"Stuck-Up\" because of how rich, greedy and spoiled he is compared to him. Once Steve got a taste of his own medicine in Horrid Henry and The Perfect Plane when the park keeper caught him flying his toy plane in the park and he takes it away from Steve and gives it to Mike. In the series 5 episode ''Horrid Henry\u2019s Class Action,'' he faces Henry in the School Council election'','' also In ''Horrid Henry Eats Out'', Henry wins by eating all his snails. Steve is hated by Henry for a particular reason - because he is spoiled and refuses to share with his cousin, Henry. Henry always knows that Steve does not look forward to seeing him, as in ''Horrid Henry's Christmas'', he switched the labels on his and Steve's presents, allowing him to help himself to some presents intended for Steve while Steve gets presents, such as socks, intended for Henry, and in ''Horrid Henry's Haunted House'', he convinced Steve that there was a monster under his bed. In the television series, he speaks with what is seemingly an upper class London accent and has reddish-purple hair. The turtleneck jumper he wears also appears to change colour between episodes - it is light green in most episodes, but is purple in ''Horrid Henry's Haunted House''. He is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]] in the TV series.\n\n===Super Sally===\n\nSuper Sally is a character in ''Manners with Maggie'' in \"''Horrid Henry Minds His Manners''\". She works at the TV station.\n\n==T==\n\n===T.J. Fizz===\nShe is Henry's favourite author and Peter's least favourite, because he says \"her books are too scary\". She has only been seen in ''Horrid Henry's Author Visit''. Miss Battle-axe sent him off from his to Peter's class because of his horridness and was stuck with Peter's favourite author. In the TV Series, she is known as \"B.B. Silver\".\n\n===Tell-Tale Tim===\nHe is one of Peter's friends.\n\n===Tetchy Tess===\nTetchy Tess is one of Horrid Henry's babysitters. After Henry floods the bathroom, she refuses to come back. She appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter'' and ''Horrid Henry Goes to the Park''. She is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Tidy Ted===\nTidy Ted is one of Peter's friends and is a member of the Best Boys Club. He is always tidy, hence his name. He is voiced by Tamsin Heatley. He has ginger-colored hair, wears a [[Periwinkle (color)|periwinkle]] sweater, cyan neck-tie, white shirt, with blue trousers, and brown shoes. His hairstyle and voice often mistake some for thinking he is a girl.\n\n===Tiddles===\nTiddles is Mrs (Miss) Oddbod's cat. It appeared in ''Horrid Henry on Trial'', ''Horrid Henry:'' ''It's All Your Fault!'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher''.\n\n===Toddler Tom===\nHe is a toddler who is mentioned in several episodes.\n\n===Tornado Tariq===\nHe is mentioned in ''Horrid Henry's household chores'' and is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Tough Toby===\nTough Toby is a boy in Henry's class who is tough. He invited Henry to his party at Lazer Zap in ''Horrid Henry's Birthday Party''.\n\n==V==\n\n===Vain Violet===\nShe appears in several of the books and is friends with Margaret. She takes a lot of pride in her appearance, and she enjoys makeovers. She never appeared in the TV series.\n\n===Vicious Vicky===\nVicious Vicky first appears in ''Horrid Henry The Movie'' and in the TV Series 3 episode ''Horrid Henry Bogus Babysitter''. She is Sour Susan's younger sister. In the Series 2 episode ''Horrid Henry Changes a Nappy'' Susan mentions a baby sister whom she has to change her nappies explaining her experience. However, Vicky is seen as a toddler or possibly an infant at Ashton Primary.\nVicious Vicky is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols and played by [[Kia Pegg]]. In ''The Movie'' she bites people. In the TV series after being thrown out by Moody Margaret, Vicky finds her way into Henry's house and raids the kitchen. She then steals Margaret's cutlass and uses it to frame her. Henry is impressed by this after initially being afraid of her. However in her next appearance in ''It's All Your Fault'' she scares Henry away from the climbing frame in the school playground and also intimidates Wheely Walter.\n\n===Vic Van Wrinkle===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Vicent Van Wrinkle\n| first              = Horrid Henry The Movie (only appearance)\n| nickname           = Vic Van Wrinkle\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Headmaster of Brickhouse School\n}}\n\nVic Van Wrinkle is the strict, fiery-tempered headmaster of \"Brickhouse School\" and the main antagonist in ''Horrid Henry The Movie''. He tries to shut down Ashton Primary school and send all the students to Brickhouse School so he can make lots of money to shut down all the schools in Ashton.\n\n===Vomiting Vera===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Vera Venetia Verocula\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Changes A Nappy\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = '''Voice'''<br>[[Tamsin Heatley]]\n| nickname           = Vomiting Vera\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Daughter of Prissy Polly & Pimply Paul\n| family             = [[#Pimply Paul|Paul]], [[#Prissy Polly|Polly]]\n| relatives          = [[#Mum|Mum]], [[Perfect Peter|Peter]], [[#Horrid Henry|Henry]], Dad\n}}\nHenry and Peter's baby first cousin once removed who is always vomiting, much to the annoyance of others. Henry will refuse to see her unless she is older and behind bars. She has blonde hair, wears a pink long-sleeved undershirt, light pink tank top with vertical magenta stripes, pink skirt, an orange hair ribbon, and dark pink stockings. She likes to watch Happy Hippos.\n\n==W==\n\n===Weepy William===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = William\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Unknown\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = Sue Elliott-Nichols\n| nickname           = Weepy William\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Son of his mum and dad\n| family             = Dad, Mum, [[Needy Neil]] (brother)\n}}\nA boy in Henry's class who is often seen crying at the slightest things. His best friend is Anxious Andrew. William has a younger brother called Needy Neil.\n\nNeedy Neil is in Miss Lovely's class. He wears a [[purple]] [[sweatshirt]], pale green undershirt with [[beige]]-trousers and brown shoes. He is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Weepy William's Dad===\nWeepy William's dad is a newspaper reporter and appears in ''Horrid Henry Ace Reporter'' and ''Horrid Henry on TV''.\n\n===Weepy William's Mum===\nWeepy William's mum only appears in ''Horrid Henry on TV'' when her and her husband have Margaret round.\n\n===Wheely Walter===\nWheely Walter is a teacher at Ashton Primary who is disabled and uses a wheelchair. He is introduced in the third series episode ''Horrid Henry and the Climbing Frame Clincher'', teaching science, and his name is revealed in the episode ''Horrid Henry and the Movie Star'' when he auditions for the part of a dead ringer for Lose Laser Larry but is fired for being \"too wheely\". He appears to get along with Henry, unlike the other teachers, but still sends him along with Moody Margaret to Miss Oddbod's office when they argue in his class during his first appearance. In the episode ''Horrid Henry's Teacher Talk'', he claims that once Horrid Henry once turned the ceiling blue in his class while he was making a cup of tea.\n\n==Z==\n\n===Zippy Zoe===\nZippy Zoe is a girl who is very fast and only appears in the books. She is in Henry's class.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Horrid Henry]]\n*[[Horrid Henry (TV series)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Horrid Henry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horrid Henry Characters}}\n[[Category:Horrid Henry characters| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of characters in British television animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=November 2011}}\n{{in-universe|date=November 2011}}\n{{cleanup|date=November 2011}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Horrid Henry'' characters}}\nThe following is a list of characters that appear in the [[United Kingdom|British]] series of children's books, ''[[Horrid Henry]]'', written by [[Francesca Simon]]. It also includes names from the [[CITV]] and [[Nicktoons]] [[Horrid Henry (TV series)|TV series of the same name]].\n{{Horizontal TOC|limit=2|nonum=y}}\n\n== A ==\n\n===Aerobic Al===\n\nAerobic Al is an extremely athletic boy, who is often displayed engaging in various athletic endeavours. He has blond hair and is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. He is often seen with Rude Ralph, Beefy Bert and Gorgeous Gurinder. He wears a white shirt with a blue collar, blue shorts and teal keds. In some episodes, he is shown to have a crush on Moody Margaret. \n\nIn the TV series, he speaks with a [[Brummie]] accent and is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Al\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sports Day (Books)<br>Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Aerobic Al\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Dad\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Wayne Forester\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\n\n===Aerobic Al's dad===\nAerobic Al's dad comes to some school events, mostly to see his son end up winning. In the TV series, he appeared in \"''[[Horrid Henry's Fun Run]]''\", where he had brown hair and was a referee. he docent want his son to be eating sweets in horrid henrys sports day. \n\n===Anxious Andrew===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Andrew\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Injection\n| last               = TBA\n| voice              = Sue Elliott-Nichols\n| nickname           = Anxious Andrew\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Tidy Ted\n}}\n\nAnxious Andrew is one of Henry's classmates; a nervous and meek boy, who always worries about unnecessary things. He is best friends with Weepy William and attends Ashton Primary School. He has ginger hair and wears a dark green tanktop with a green shirt and blue-grey trousers \n\nIn the TV series, he is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Allergic Alice===\nA minor character who appears in the book ''Horrid Henry's Cannibal Curse'' in which she is revealed to be allergic to [[gluten]], nuts, sugar, flour ''and'' dairy.\n\n==B==\n\n===Bald man===\nA bald man appears as a minor character in 'Horrid Henry's New Shoes' when Mum opens his changing room door when trying to look for Henry.\n\n=== Basher ===\nA Dog who appears in Horrid Henry and The Lost Dog, who Henry finds and part-time owns for a while. It was then revealed he was missing, after an advert passes through Henry's house door. His name appears to have been inspired by Gnasher from the ''[[Dennis the Menace and Gnasher|Dennis the Menace]]'' stories.\n\n===Beefy Bert===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Bert\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's New Teacher (Books)<br>Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Beefy Bert\n| gender             = Male\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Wayne Forester\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nBeefy Bert is usually seen in the crowds of children at Henry and Peter's school, and is normally seen with Ralph and Al. Whenever anyone asks him a question, his immediate answer is \"I dunno\", which is actually the only line Bert ever says throughout the entire book series. He is the biggest boy in Henry's class. Both his parents and his brother also say \"I dunno\" as revealed when he films them for a school project in the story ''Horrid Henry Tells it Like it Is'' in the book ''Horrid Henry's Krazy Ketchup''.\n\nIn the TV series, Bert is voiced by Wayne Forester, and his voice was originally low-pitched and deep, but from the second season onwards, it was changed to a higher-pitched, squeakier one. Like with his book counterpart, the only word he says is \"I dunno\" but however in the Series 1 TV episode ''Horrid Henry Gets Rich Quick'', he says \"Have you got any food?\" and in the Series 4 episode ''Horrid Henry Who's Who?'', after switching personalities with Brainy Brian, he gives his answers in full sentences.\n\n===Beefy Bert's dad===\nBeefy Bert's dad is a bus driver who appears in ''Horrid Henry Takes a Shortcut'', ''Horrid Henry And The Purple Pass'', ''Horrid Henry and the Perfect Parents'' and ''Horrid Henry Alone at Home''. Like with his Son, Whenever anyone asks him a question, his immediate answer is \"I dunno\".\n\n===Beefy Bert's mum===\nBeefy Bert's mum is briefly seen in the TV adaption of ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover'', calling Henry's Dad. She is voiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]].\n\nIn the books, she appears in ''Horrid Henry Tells it Like it Is'', where with the rest of Bert's family, she says \"I dunno\".\n\n===Bob===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Bob\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Goes to Work\n| last               = Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| nickname           = Bob Sir, Big Boss\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Bill (son)\n| children           = Bossy Bill\n}}\nBob (also known as Big Boss or \"Bob Sir\") is Dad's work boss. He is very strict, and is extremely proud of his son, Bill, whom he believes is perfect. However, he discovers that this is not the case after catching Bill photocopying his bottom. He grounds Bill for a month and sends him home. His book appearance was in ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'' and he is mentioned in \"Horrid Henry's Arch Enemy\". \n\nIn the TV series, he is referred to as Bob or Bob Sir, and the job he runs is Tingly Toothbrushes who make toothbrushes and toothpaste just for Dogs. He appeared in the adaptation of ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'', and has  also appeared in \"Horrid Henry's Heist\" as the school inspector at the fancy dress party (where his character design looks like an older version of his son, Bossy Bill),  ''Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson'' when he was in the park on his way to an appointment with Bill's headmaster and in ''Horrid Henry Helps Out''.\n\n===Bossy Bill===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Bill\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Goes to Work (Books and TV series)\n| last               =\n| portrayer          = \n| nickname           = Bossy Bill\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Bob (Father)\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| voice              = [[Murad Ahmed]]\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nBossy Bill is the horrible, stuck-up son of Dad's boss. His father thought he was perfect until Henry tricked him into photocopying his bottom at the office, but he still is a mischievous boy, as is evident from when he made tea, but added salt instead of sugar. In the Books, he appears in ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'', ''Horrid Henry's Arch Enemy'' and ''Horrid Henry's Horrid Weekend''. In the audiobook editions read by Miranda Richardson, both Bill and his father have American accents.\n\nIn the TV series, he is voiced by [[Murad Ahmed]] and has a [[Scouse|Scouse accent]]. He wears the same clothes and has the same hairstyle as his father. He has appeared in the adaptation of ''Horrid Henry Goes to Work'', ''Perfect Peter Pumps Up'', ''Horrid Henry Says Goodbye'', ''Perfect Peter\u2019s Perfect Day'', ''Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson'' and ''Horrid Henry Helps Out''.\n\n===Brainy Brian===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Brian\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb (Books)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Brainy Brian\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Brother of Gordon\n| family             = Goody Gordon\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Aidan Cook\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nThe smartest boy in Horrid Henry's class. He appears to be of Black descent. He has brown skin and black hair and wears a pink shirt with pens tucked into his pocket and green floral shorts along with baby-blue shoes. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n=== Bunny ===\nBunny is Peter's adorable toy [[rabbit]]. It is Peter's version of Mr. Kill. His most major roles in the TV series are in ''Horrid Henry and the Time Capsule'', in which Henry gives Bunny to the capsule and rescues him, ''Horrid Henry Trapped'', in which Henry has Bunny in the hospital after he was injured whilst saving Peter from a falling shelf in the cellar and ''Perfect Peter Pumps Up'', in which Henry realises that the only way to turn Peter aggressive is to steal Bunny and make fun of him.\n\n==C==\n\n===Captain Push-Me Button===\nCaptain Push-Me Button is a robot that appeared in ''Horrid Henry's Aquarium''. He gives tickets to the Dingy Dungeon. It is thought that he wasn't put together properly as he has some technical malfunctions. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Caring Chris===\nCaring Chris works at the old people's home. She has a good friendship with Miss Oddbod. She only appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Walking Stick Gang''. She is voiced by Sue Eliott Nichols in the TV series.\n\n===Cherry Berry===\nCherry Berry is a famous pastry chef based on ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'' judge, [[Mary Berry]]. Cherry was a judge in the street party in ''Horrid Henry's Bake-Off''.\n\n===Clever Clare===\nClever Clare is the smartest girl in Horrid Henry's class. But only appears as a minor character in an Ashton Primary school photo in Horrid Henry, Nothing But The Truth in the TV series as a member of Perfect Peter's class. In ''[[Horrid Henry's Double Dare]]'', she has to get all her spellings wrong. She also appeared in Horrid Henry, ''It\u2019s All Your Fault'' when she was singing with Sour Susan, Gorgeous Gurinder and Singing Soraya in the musical number, Born To Be Rude. She also appears on the cover of Horrid Henry's Nits, appearing as the one who Henry is flicking nits to.\n\n===Colin the Clown===\nColin the [[Clown]] appears in ''Happy Birthday Peter!'', where he appears as the clown and entertainer of Peter's [[birthday party]] and is scared of lions, whom he had a bad [[circus]] experience with. He is able to blow [[handkerchiefs]] out of his nose, make [[milk]] disappear and make a [[banana]] disappear. He has a '[[Box]] of Bewilderment'. He also appears in the Season 3 episode, Horrid Henry Goes To The Theatre when he was helping the Penelope family find their way to the show. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Crabby Chris===\nCrabby Chris once babysat Horrid Henry but never came back after Henry hid her homework and spilt grapefruit juice on her jeans. She is only seen on a flashback in ''Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter''. She was voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Cross Colin===\nCross Colin appears in ''Horrid Henry's Wedding'' as the best man and one of Pimply Paul's friends.\n\nCrazy Cath\nHenry\u2019s grandma whom appears in multiple episodes for example: \u2018trip to Portugal\u2019, \u2018ONIONS\u2019 and \u2018Cath V Cath\u2019\n\n==D==\n\n===Dad===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Dad\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Trapped\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Wayne Forester]]\n| full_name          = Simon Daniels\n| nickname           = Silly Simon\n| occupation         = Works for Tingly Toothbrushes\n| spouse             = Mum\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Mum, Henry, Peter, Francis\n| children           = Henry, Peter\n| relatives          = Fussy Francis\n}}\n'''Dad''' is the father of Henry and Peter. He is always yelling at Henry, but very rarely at Peter. He often shouts \"Go to your room, now!\" Like Mum, he has never trusted Henry to be well behaved. He agrees with his wife almost all the time. He is also extremely healthy, making Henry and Peter very healthy packed lunches and cooking healthy dinners, much to Henry's disgust. Peter often shows off to Dad by being well behaved while Henry misbehaves. He punishes Henry by banning the TV and/or the computer, but mostly resorts to cancellation or reduction of pocket money, for example when Henry refuses not to come on a hike he starts deducting pocket money. He shows favouritism when it comes to Henry and Peter. He tends to believe the best of Peter and the worst of Henry as even if Henry was telling the truth, he will still dismiss it as \"rubbish\". When Peter was horrid, he will find excuses for him. A good example was that Peter sprayed Henry with a hose deliberately, even chasing him around the garden, but he ended up telling Henry that he should have got out of the way when Peter was \"watering the flowers\".  Although strict he appears to be more tolerant of Henry by giving him second chances. Also, he is often shown to be capable of distracting Henry enough that he behaves. He has curly brown hair and wears an orange sweater and a blue jacket. It is revealed that ''Gross Class Zero'' was his favourite show when he was a boy. At the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings'' it is revealed that his nickname is \"Silly Simon\". At the end of this episode it is also implied that Henry gets his horrid streak from him, while Peter gets his goody-goody streak from Fussy Uncle Francis. He is always on Mum's side and rarely lets Henry get his own way, however he sometimes agrees with Henry's point of view. He is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Dirty Dirk===\nHe is the Judge of the TV programme \"Hog House\".\n\n===Dizzy Dave===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Dave\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Dizzy Dave\n| species            = Human\n}}\nDizzy Dave is a boy in Henry's class who is always spinning around and knocking things over. He is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. His name was replaced with Rude Ralph's in Horrid Henry's Birthday Party, when Henry talks about a previous party at laser zap. A boy with brown hair, white skin, purple-ish top with orange shorts and a gleen bowl of green liquid may be him because of his sleepy face but this has not been confirmed yet.\n\n===Dr. Dettoll===\nDr. Dettoll is a doctor who gives injections. She only appears at the end of ''Horrid Henry's Injection''.\n\n=== Doddery Donald ===\nGreat Aunt Greta's brother. He mostly says \"Donald\". He only appears in ''Horrid Henry Plays Air Guitar''.\n\n==E==\n\n===Ed Banger===\nEd Banger is a [[Magic (illusion)|magician]], [[dancer]], [[ringmaster (circus)|ringmaster]], [[musician]] and the lead singer in the Killer Boy Rats. In the episode ''Horrid Henry and the Killer Boy Rats'' Ed Banger leaves the Killer Boy Rats and begins writing and singing \"nice songs\", much to Henry's ire and Peter's delight. After Henry gets up on stage during a concert and sings (loud and off-key) one of his Killer Boys Rats songs, his manager phones Henry and congratulates him. Henry is then given tickets to the next Killer Boy Rats concert. While on TV Ed says he is going back to being a Killer Boy Rats member and his manager explains that it was Henry inspired him to return to the music group. Henry and his family then go to the concert where the Killer Boy Rats sing a song (\"Gonna Be A Rock Star\") as a token of thanks and appreciation to Henry who is on stage with them as a drummer.\n\n===Evil Eddy Edwards===\nEvil Eddy Edwards is a milkman who has a rivalry with Pimply Paul as seen in Horrid Henry Delivers The Milk.\n\n==F==\n\n===Fang the Hamster===\n\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Fang\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Horrid Hamster\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| family             = Henry,Peter,Mum,Dad\n| relatives          = None\n}}\n\nFang is Henry's loyal, vicious [[hamster]]. He often feuds with Fluffy the Cat, and has a helpful ear when Henry needs someone to talk to. He is an unusual hamster in which he is up in the day, he sleeps in a bed and is able to say \"Yeah, yeah, yeah!\". He is also useful to Henry for when he plots revenge against an enemy. Fang acts like a [[dog]] and sniffs out missing Fluffy in one episode. In another episode, Fang had a major role, when he went missing. The family presumed him as dead, and when Henry found him a day later, he dressed Fang up as a [[poodle]], as a pose for the replacement pet for Peter. Sometimes he is mistaken for a rat which is what Moody Margaret calls him. His vocal effects are provided by [[Tamsin Heatley]].\n\n===Fearless Phantom===\nFearless Phantom is a TV superhero who Horrid Henry loves but he is scared of spiders.\n\n===Fiery Fiona===\nFiery Fiona is a girl in Henry's class, who appears a few times in the books but never in the TV series. She is shown to have a fiery temper.\n\n===Filthy Phil===\nHe is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Fluffy the Cat===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Fluffy\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| alias              = Fluffy the Cat.\n| species            = Cat\n| occupation         = Pet\n}}\nFluffy is the family's grey [[cat]], who feuds with Henry's [[hamster]], Fang. Fluffy is shown in most episodes sitting by the sitting room window sill at night and as she clicks the TV remote control button next to her in the first three series and swipes the tablet computer in the fourth series the scene changes to sunrise. Fluffy also gets dressed up as a mummy in the tale ''Horrid Henry and the Mummy''. Like Peter, she seems to have a vindictive streak towards Henry as she once framed him for eating several packets of a snack that Mum likes. Despite being female she is sometimes referred to as a \"he\". Peter is completely devoted to her, and never believes she does anything wrong, even though she started chasing Fang in one episode, and Peter said Fang started the fight.\n\n===Frosty Freeze Man===\nHe works at Frosty Freeze. He appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Abominable Snowman'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Big Freeze Wheeze''.\n\n===Frosty Steve===\nFrosty Steve works at Frosty Freeze. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Ice Cream Dream''.\n\n===Fussy Uncle Francis===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Francis\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings (only appearance)\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Fussy Uncle Francis\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Brother of Silly Simon\n| relatives          = Mum (sister), Dad (older brother), Henry (nephew), Peter (nephew)\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = Aidan Cook\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nHenry's uncle and Dad's younger brother. Voiced by [[Aidan Cook]]. He has curly blonde hair which is similar to Peter's, just as Dad's hair is brown, like Henry's, although Dad also has curly hair. He wears a green jacket and orange tie and he only appears so far in ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings''. He is shown not to get on with Dad, as they argue often and this is also where a slightly childish aspect of Dad's personality is revealed. He is said to be fussy, as when he visits he inspects the staircase for dust when he comes in. At the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Silly Siblings'', he calls Dad \"Silly Simon\", which is presumably what he was called when he was a kid. At the end of this episode it is also implied that Peter gets his goody-goody streak from him, while Henry gets his horrid streak from Dad.\n\n==G==\n\n===Goody-Goody Gordon===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Gordon\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Fangmangler\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Goody-Goody Gordon\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Brainy Brian\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nGordon is one of Peter's best friends. He is a member of the Best Boys Club and is friends with Tidy Ted and Spotless Sam. He often speaks with a lisp. He is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]]. Gordon has black hair and dark skin. He wears a mustard-yellow jumper, white undershirt, and blue grey pants.\n\n===Gorgeous Gurinder===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Gurinder\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Secret Club\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Gorgeous Gurinder\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Gorgeous\n}}\nGorgeous Gurinder is a beautiful and gorgeous girl who appears to be best friends with Singing Soraya and Lazy Linda. They are both members of the Secret Club. She has brown skin, purple-black hair, and wears a white shirt with periwinkle flower prints, pink trousers, and beautiful white ballet pumps. In the later episodes, She also good knowledge of makeup products as she is seen teaching Henry how to put on handcream.\n\n===Grandma===\nShe is Henry and Peter's grandmother, and Mum's mother. She always gives nice presents to Henry and Peter. She only appears in the books.\n\n===Granny===\nShe is Henry and Peter's grandmother, and Dad's mother. She only appears in Horrid Henry's Christmas Lunch, and she is shown to be quite bossy.\n\n===Grandpa===\nHe is Henry and Peter's grandfather, and Dad's father. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Christmas Cracker'' when he visits Henry's family for Christmas lunch on Christmas Day.\n\n===Greasy Greta===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Greta\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Demon Dinner Lady\n| last               = Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady\n| portrayer          = Sue Elliot-Nichols\n| nickname           = Demon Dinner Lady\n| alias              = Greasy Greta\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| children           = Pasty Patsy\n}} \nGreasy Greta is the lady from the counter in the school cafeteria who was in charge of the packed lunch room. She first appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Demon Dinner Lady''. She was sent to look after the kids in the lunch room because they were always playing with their food. She always took the children's treats and ate them, but she ran away after she ate hot chili biscuits Henry brought in. However, in the TV series, she ate far too many treats and was wheeled out of the school on a trolley, by Soggy Sid. She is voiced by [[Sue Elliot Nicholls|Sue Elliot-Nichols]]. She returns in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the Book, Horrid Henry's Nightmare. This time she inspects lunch boxes to promote healthy eating. She has maroon-colored hair and crimson-pink skin. She is fired on the spot when Miss Oddbod catches her in the cupboard eating the confiscated sweets that were supposed to be donated to charity.\n\n===Great Aunt Greta===\nVoiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]], Great Aunt Greta is the great aunt of Horrid Henry. She thinks that Henry is a little girl called Henrietta (or Henny in ''Horrid Henry's Underpants''), and that Peter is a teenager. This is reflected in the presents that she sends to the boys. Although Henry's Mum and Dad have told her countless times that Henry is a boy and that Peter is six, Greta refuses to believe this, and usually doesn't hear, most likely due to her senility. Her senility is such that she once cooked cat food for the boys and believed that Fluffy is a dog named Fido. She also mistook it to be the middle of the night when in fact it was only half past five in the afternoon. She wears a light pink sweater, a gold button studded in her white blouse, dark pink skirt, lavender shoes and a walking stick.\n\n===Greedy Graham===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Graham\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = Wayne Forester\n| nickname           = Greedy Graham\n| gender             = Male\n}}\nGreedy Graham is a brown-haired obese boy who is always hungry and is often seen eating carrots and junk food in the earlier episodes. He is shown to be one of Henry's close friends. Voiced by Wayne Forester. He wears an orange shirt with blue outlines, blue sweatpants and red sneakers. He has a Cockney accent in some early episodes and a Cornish accent for the majority of his appearances. It is stated by Aerobic Al that he ate his gloss class zero comic in Horrid Henry's Unhappy Day.\n\n==H==\n===Horrid Henry===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Henry\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Tricks or Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| nickname           = Horrid Henry\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Peter (brother), Mum and Dad\n| children           = none\n| relatives          = Steve (cousin) Ruby (aunt) Great Aunt Greta (great aunt)\n}}\n\nHenry is the main character of the series and is portrayed as a determined and relentless young boy. He believes that life is unfair as the rest of the world is against him, so he fights \"against the tyranny of adults\". He is resistant to defeat as teachers, relatives and babysitters in the series try their best to avoid him. Even his parents argue over whose turn it is to look after him.\n\nHenry is very selfish, inconsiderate, stubborn, and rarely learns from his mistakes. He can also be bluntly honest, as seen when he tells his mother's boss what she calls her at work behind her back and is unafraid of telling people how much he hates them right to their faces. However, he is willing to act nice and collude with Margaret and even Peter, but only if it means he will get to have his own way. Most likely because of his young age, Henry can get frightened by talk of ghosts or monsters, and in one episode, is revealed to have a [[fear of needles]]. He is very imaginative, as he indulges in fantasies, usually transforming into terrifying creatures and attacking the source of his frustrations, and often has \"Eureka moments\" when the stories mention what he thinks is a \"spectacularly wonderful idea\". In every story, there is something Henry has to get or do (or occasionally avoid doing) and the ensuing chaos is the consequence of this overriding desire.\n\nWhenever Henry thinks of a plan it is simply to get his own way, never to make trouble purely for its own sake. He is more often than not seen taking life very seriously and he sincerely believes in what he is doing, making him something of a complex character as well. It has also been further hinted that deep down, Henry never really means to be horrid, and only acts that way as a wanting to get attention and needing to feel important, especially when dealing with his younger brother Peter, implying he has low self-esteem.\n\n===Helpful Hari===\nShe is invited to Peter's party in ''Perfect Peter's Pirate Party'' and is in Peter's class.\n\n==I==\n\n===Inky Ian===\n\nInky Ian is a pupil who isn't very much in Henry's [[classroom]] who is only seen in the book version ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend''.\n\n==J==\n\n===Jazzy Jim===\nJazzy Jim is a minor character in Henry's class who likes music. He only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Arch Enemy'', ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend'' and ''Horrid Henry's Bake Off''.\n\n===Jolly Josh===\n\nJolly Josh is a boy in Henry's class who is always playing and joking. He's shown to be friends with Henry in ''Horrid Henry Tidies Up''. he has a darker skin tone but still lighter than goody-goody gorden,brainy brian and the mossies.\n\n===Jolly Josh's father===\nJolly Josh's father only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Nits'' when he complains about the letter sent home.\n\n===Jumping Jeffrey===\nJeffrey is a boy who loves jumping like a [[kangaroo]] at Henry's karate class.\n\n==K==\n\n===Killer Boy Rats===\nHorrid Henry's favourite band. The lead singer is Ed Banger, Henry's idol.\n\n===Kind Kasim===\nKind Kasim is a minor character in Henry's class. He doesn't appear in the picture of Henry's class.\n\n===Kind Kelly===\nKind Kelly is a girl in Peter's class who once let Henry borrow her mobile phone and is so kind. She is mentioned in ''Horrid Henry and the King Of Bling'' and appears in a photo in ''Horrid Henry, Nothing But the Truth''. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Kung-Fu Kate===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Kate\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Thank You Letter\n| nickname           = Kung-Fu Kate\n}}\nKung-Fu Kate is a girl in Henry's class who is always doing Kung-Fu. She is also friends with Margaret.\n\n==L==\n\n===Lazy Linda===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Linda\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| nickname           = Lazy Linda\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n}}\nThe laziest girl in Henry's class. She is often seen sleeping. She doesn't talk very often, but when she does, she uses the word \"like\" quite a lot and has a [[cockney accent]]. She is a member of the Secret Club, which she initially joined as a replacement for Susan. At some point, Margaret fired her and Susan returned, however at some point Linda returned as well. She and Susan are foes and sometimes friends. Linda wears a light green shirt, red overall dress and green sneakers. She is voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Lisping Lily===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Lily\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sleepover\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Lisping Lily\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Sister of Nick & Mike\n| family             = Nick (brother), Parents, Mike (brother)\n}}\nLisping Lily is New Nick's younger sister; a toddler, who is largely infatuated with Henry (pronouncing his name \"Henwy\") and is known for her noticeable lisp. Her common catchphrases in the book are \"I love you, Henwy.\" and \"Will you mawwy with me, Henwy?\". She wears a blue tunic with a ribbon, and dark blue overalls and she also has a doll that squirts Henry in the face from its mouth/nose.\n\n===Little girl===\nA little girl appears as a minor character in ''Horrid Henry's New Shoes'' when she is buying trousers at the same time as Henry and Mum.\n\n==M==\n\n===Mad Martin===\nMartin is a teenager who babysat henry once.it is currently unknown who he is voiced by.\n\n===Maggie===\nThe presenter of one of Peter's favourite TV programmes, \"Manners with Maggie\" which was one of Henry's least favourite programmes. The show stopped airing after Maggie was dragged off the set screaming following her reaction to Henry's terrible manners.\n\n===Marvin the Maniac===\nThe presenter of one of Henry's favourite TV programmes, Gross-Out. He invites Henry to appear on the show after he wrote to him. He eventually appeared on underpants separate to Henry's old Gross-Out pants.\n\n===Magic Rabbit===\nThe rabbit appears in ''Happy Birthday Peter''.\n\n===Magic Martha===\nMartha is a girl who does magic tricks In Henry's class.\n\n===Milksop Miles===\nThe author of Peter's favourite book, \"The Happy Nappy\". He is Henry's least favourite writer and only appears in \"Horrid Henry's Author Visit\".\n\n===Mini Minnie===\nShe is invited to Peter's party in ''Perfect Peter's Pirate Party'' and is in Peter's class.\n\n===Mischievous Mike===\nHe is one of Horrid Henry's friends who loves [[Airplane|planes]]. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Miss Battle-Axe===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Boudicca Battle-Axe\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = [[Aidan Cook]]<br>[[Anjelica Huston]]\n| nickname           = Miss Battle-Axe\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Teacher]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Miss Battle-Axe, Henry's teacher\n| family             = Mrs. Alicia Battle-Axe (mother) &  Our Lady Giddyantus School Headmistress Battle-Axe (twin sister)\n}}\n\n'''Miss Boudicca Battle-Axe''' is a strict, sadistic schoolteacher who talks with a Scottish accent. She teaches [[Horrid Henry (Character)|Horrid Henry]], and many of his classmates such as [[Rude Ralph]], [[Moody Margaret]] and [[Sour Susan]]. She seems to have a particular disliking towards Henry, which would be because it is usually his horrid behaviour which disrupts her class. She once said that Henry's class was the worst she ever taught. In very few episodes, her mother, Mrs Battle-Axe, has appeared, who appears to discipline her daughter greatly. She wears pointy glasses and has gray hair. She also wears a green cardigan, pale chartreuse top, brown skirt, and brownish stockings. In ''Horrid Henry Delivers a Message'', it is shown that Miss Battle-Axe secretly has a crush on [[Soggy Sid]]. Miss Battle-Axe is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]] ( wayne forester in an interview with BFI ) and portrayed by [[Anjelica Huston]].\n\nDespite hating Henry's class it is apparent that Miss Battle-Axe is tough enough to survive teaching it, as it has been mentioned that all of Henry's teachers prior to her had quit because of him.\n\nIn the season 4 episode ''Horrid Henry's Movie Moments'' it is revealed she has an identical twin sister who is also called ''Miss Battle-Axe'' but is Headmistress of Our Lady Giddiantus and talks with a [[Received pronunciation|posh voice]]. However in the film the Headmistress of Our Lady Giddiantus is named as \"Miss Dinesta Clutterbuck\" on the sign outside.\n\n===Miss Impatience Tutu===\nMiss Impatience Tutu is a dance teacher who first appeared in ''Horrid Henry's Dance Class''. In the TV series, she is referred to as Madame Tutu and speaks with a French accent when talking to her class, but speaks with an English accent when talking to Henry individually. She seems to be a lot nicer in the TV series than in the books. She has blonde hair in a bun and wears a black leotard over a pale pink jumpsuit .she organised the show \"I hear thunder\" in the episode horrid henrys dance class. she is Voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]].\n\n===Miss Lovely===\n\n'''Miss Lydia Lovely''' is Peter's teacher. As her name suggests, she has a gentle nature. She is very proud of Peter's progress and behaviour and is always saying nice things about him to his parents. However, on odd occasions (such as when Peter hands in a \"Why I Hate My Teacher\" essay, which he wrote as \"Why I Love My Teacher\", which Henry edited the night before) she had lost her temper. She is often seen in the library, on library duty when she's in the reading area. During early seasons, she spoke with an Indian accent, which fitted considering she appears to be Asian, however, later on in the series, she speaks with a Welsh accent. She is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Miss Thumper===\nMiss Thumper only appears in ''Horrid Henry's Dance Class'', where she works.\n\n===Moody Margaret===\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #800080\n| name               = Moody Margaret\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| franchise          = \n| image              = Moody Margaret.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Moody Margaret, as she appears in the book series (With an edit done by Horrid Henry)\n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = ''[[Horrid Henry (book)|Horrid Henry]]'' (''Horrid Henry and Moody Margaret'')\n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = Scarlet Stitt\n| voice              = Sue Elliot-Nichols\n| full_name          = Margaret Millicent Mordeates Smythe\n| nickname           = Moody<br>Frogface<br>Bogey Brain\n| alias              = \"The Fangmangler\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Simon|first=Francesca|title=Horrid Henry and the Fangmangler|year=1997|publisher=Orion Children's Books|location=UK|isbn=978-1-85881-353-0|pages=22}}</ref>\n| species            = [[Human]]\n| gender             = [[Female]]\n| occupation         = [[Student]]\n| family             = '''Mother''': Unnamed<br>'''Father''': Unnamed\n| spouse             = \n| significant_other   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| religion           = [[Europe]]an\n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| nationality        = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\nMoody Margaret is a moody girl who is always fussing and wanting to get her own way. She is a spoilt brat. She is portrayed as the secondary main antagonist in the series and serves as Horrid Henry's archenemy. She lives next door to Horrid Henry and her best friend is Sour Susan. She has magenta hair in a spiky ponytail.\nHenry and Margaret are enemies; Margaret has a secret club and Henry has the Purple Hand Gang. She has an ability of screaming and always competes with Henry. She might have a crush on Henry, because in ''Perfect Peter's Revenge'', she is happy when Peter sends her a forged letter that said Henry loves and wants to marry Margaret. This is also seen in other episodes. She wears a violet [[tank top]] with white stripes, green [[cardigan (sweater)|cardigan]] and a bottle-green skirt. Margaret, however, occasionally assists Henry in his plans, as seen in ''Horrid Henry's Horrid Revenge'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Big Dig'', though under the word of being the leader of the Purple Hand Gang for a day or a month or even a whole year you will never know how long it will be maybe a week or even every month/year/day/second/minute. She is voiced by Sue Elliot-Nichols. In the episode ''Horrid Henry Rockstar'' it is suggested that her full name is Margaret Millicent Maudita Smythe which she also uses in subsequent episodes. However she denies this when Rude Ralph asks her if this is true.\n\nAs the primary antagonist of the series, Moody Margaret is the most prominent arch-enemy of the series' protagonist, [[Horrid Henry]]. When Francesca Simon was in the process of creating this character, she suggested a boy called Moody Martin. However, her husband did not approve of the idea as it would be too much like Horrid Henry the main character. Thus, Martin became a female called Margaret. Margaret is depicted as being a self-absorbed, grumpy, spiteful, and cantankerous girl who shares an intense rivalry with Henry, and their opposing neighborhood clubs continuously develop practical jokes or conspiracies against one another. They have resorted to each other's companionship when left with no other options, but nonetheless detest one another and continuously plot against one another, especially in an attempt to soil each other's reputations. Margaret has a tendency to gloat about her various accomplishments in a ridiculously [[narcissistic]] fashion, looking down on others and domineering her friends and peers. True to this, she is resented by her best friend Sour Susan because of her rudeness, but Susan seems to have no other choice than to reluctantly obey Margaret's constant commands. Margaret viciously domineers the Secret Club in various plots formulated against Henry's corresponding Purple Hang Gang, and the two opposing sides share a mutual animosity. She is used to having her own way and is capable of releasing violent, piercing screeches when her demands remain unfulfilled.\n\n====Live-action====\n\n[[File:Scarlet Stitt Moody Margaret.jpg|150px|thumb|Movie poster for ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]'' featuring Scarlet Stitt as Moody Margaret.]]\n* Scarlet Stitt portrays Moody Margaret in the 2011 movie, ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]''. At the beginning of the movie, She, Sour Susan and [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Singing Soroya|Singing Soroya]] are in the Secret Club treehouse eating biscuits and arguing. Henry disguises himself as a spy, steals the biscuits and runs away but Margaret has also stolen his mighty magnet yoyo. Later, on his way home from school, Henry dodges a water balloon thrown by Margaret. He ducks behind a lamppost, waits for Margaret to walk past, throws a balloon filled with water that hovers over her head and finally, flicks a yoyo at the balloon which bursts and soaks Margaret. Margaret shrieks and throws another balloon at Henry but he ducks and it hits [[Perfect Peter]] instead.<br>The next day at school, Margaret hangs a pail filled with purple paint over the door, ties one end of a rope to it and the other end to the door's handle. Instead of Henry who gets painted, it is their teacher [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Battle-Axe|Miss Battle-Axe]] who falls for the trick. Battle-Axe blames it on Henry, giving Margaret a lucky escape. The next day, Miss Battle Axe's class is moved to [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Lovely|Miss Lovely]]'s class after the head sacks Miss Battle-Axe for not controlling the pupils. Margaret snatches Henry's bag and Henry tries to pull it back, resulting in a pot of \"Exploding Gross-Glue\" placed by the school inspectors to fly out. The glue bursts and hits Miss Lovely in the face. She too gets sacked and the head, and [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Miss Oddbod|Miss Oddbod]] bans Henry from entering the school's talent contest. As the school is going bankrupt, many children transfer to another school. Margaret and Henry both get transferred to a girls' school (Henry's Great-Aunt Greta transferred him there as she thinks he is a girl).<br>The girls in the school attack Henry for being a boy and try to attack Margaret too for being with Henry. The two of them escape and form an alliance to save their school. They do this by making Henry sneak into the talent contest and win it so he would be so famous but the plan fails. They try another plan which involves Henry going onto a game show to win the big cash prize so he can give it to Miss Oddbod so she can give it to the school inspectors to bribe them away as they were the ones trying to get the school closed down under the order of the head of a boys' school called [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Vic Van Wrinkle|Vic Van Wrinkle]]. However, although Henry wins, the Best Boy's Club, Miss Lovely and Miss Oddbod had got Vic and the inspectors arrested so she lets Henry keep the money. At the very end, Margaret is seen in a fairy costume at Henry's party.\n\n====Animation====\n\n* In 2006's ''[[Horrid Henry (TV series)|Horrid Henry]]'' TV series, Moody Margaret is voiced by Sue Elliot-Nichols and is the series' most recurring villain. Margaret is represented just like she is in the books and seen as Henry's rival. However she is shown to be smarter. It has been hinted in some episodes, especially in series 4, that she may in fact admire Henry and wants to be his friend. She has shown a very keen interest in wanting to join The Purple Hand Gang. She might have a crush on Henry, e.g. in \"Perfect Peter's Revenge\", she was happy when Peter send her a forged letter that said Henry loves and wants to marry Margaret. On Henry's side he pictures himself marrying Margaret when he imagines himself in the future in the episodes ''Horrid Henry Gets Married'' and ''Horrid Henry's Birthday Bonanza'' although he does not know why this is. From the Series 3 episode ''Horrid Henry Rockstar'' she names herself as Margaret Millicent Maudita Smythe. However she denies this when Rude Ralph asks her if this is true in the first instance. her shouting is able to crack glass as seen in moody Margaret moves in.\n\n===Moody Margaret's parents===\nMoody Margaret's parents give her everything her heart desires.\nMargaret's mum is voiced by Joanna Ruiz and has dark magenta hair while her dad is voiced by Aidan Cook and has grey hair. In Horrid Henry on TV Henry gets these parents but then gets kicked out because he sat on Margaret's Dad's Chair.\n\n===Mouldy Myra===\nShe is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Mr and Mrs Mossy===\nMr and Mrs Mossy are characters who first appeared in ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests''.\nMr Mossy is Mum's boss, although sometimes Mrs Mossy is shown to be Mum's boss. Mr Mossy also appears in TV series ''Horrid Henry Changes a Nappy''. At the start of ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests'' Mr Mossy sabotages all of the tricks of Henry. The Mossys appear to be of black descent and it is revealed at the end of ''Horrid Henry and the Dinner Guests'' that Mr Mossy's first name is Timothy in the TV series, although it is given as Reginald in the book. When Mr Mossy was a child he was called \"Terrible Timothy\". Mr. Mossy is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]] and Mrs. Mossy is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Mrs Battle-Axe===\nMrs Battle-Axe is Miss Boudicca Battle Axe's mother. She disciplines her daughter greatly and is a nice, old woman who likes Henry, in a sharp contrast to her daughter's meanness and dislike of Henry.\n\n===Mrs Crunch===\nMrs Crunch is the guide at Our Town Museum, runs Camp Sunshine and the Happiest Family competition. she has an upper-class English accent.\n\n===Mrs/Miss Oddbod===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Cynthia Oddbod\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's School Fair\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| portrayer          = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| nickname           = Mrs Oddbod (book)<br />Miss Oddbod (TV series)\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Head Teacher]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Miss\n}}\nThe head teacher/principal of Ashton Primary School. Her name is revealed as Mrs Oddbod in the story ''Horrid Henry's School Project'' in the book ''Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb''. However she is addressed as \"Miss\" rather than \"Mrs\" Oddbod in the TV series and the film. Despite her title as head teacher, she is somewhat kinder to Henry than Miss Battle-Axe. She is generally good-natured but can act strange at times, for example, she was the \"time capsule thief\" who dug up time capsules from the school grounds at night. Her first name is Cynthia. This was revealed in the episode ''Horrid Henry, Horrid Headmaster''. She and Chris, the woman who works at the old people's home, have a good friendship, as seen in ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Walking Stick Gang''. She is voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]] in the series. She has ginger hair in a ponytail and wears round glasses, a lavender dress, with a beige collar and button, and a violet hairband in the TV series.\n\n===Mum===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mum\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'' (Books)<br>''Horrid Henry Tricks And Treats'' (TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = Bookshop worker\n| spouse             = Dad (aka \"Silly Simon\") (husband)\n| gender             = Female\n| family             = Henry, Peter, Dad\n| children           = Henry, Peter\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = \n<!--| full_name      = Elizabeth Daniels-->\n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\n\n'''Mum''' is the mother of Henry and Peter, the wife of Dad (\"Silly Simon\") and the younger sister of Rich Aunt Ruby. Mum is usually almost never angry with Peter usually referring to him as \"Sweetie Pie\" and \"Bunny Hop\" etc. Henry on the other hand is usually getting yelled at by his parents, and when he does something horrid, Mum will say \"Go to your room now, Henry!\" or \"No TV, sweets or pocket money for a week!\" or simply \"Don't be horrid, Henry!\" Despite the fact that Peter's perfect behavior leads to Mum being proud of him in the episode \"The Fairy Dance\" Mum finally yells at Peter which of course makes Henry happy. Mum also yells at Peter, for being horrid and chucking food at her, in ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day''. She wears a purple cardigan with a pinkish shirt under. She has blonde hair and wears glasses. Mum also wears blue jeans and pink ballet shoes. It is known that she has a sister named Ruby, a brother-in-law named Fussy Francis. Her mother is Henry and Peter's grandmother, but it's unknown who her father is. She is currently voiced by Tamsin Heatley, and Siobhan Hayes played her role in the ''Horrid Henry Movie'' as well.\n\n==N==\n\n===Nasty Nicola===\nNasty Nicola joins Henry's class in ''Horrid Henry and the New Best Friend'' and appears nice to begin with but turns out to be nasty and vicious. She has light red hair in braided pigtails and wears a teal sweatshirt. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Needy Neil===\nNeedy Neil is Weepy William's younger brother. He is in Miss Lovely's class.\n\n===New Nick===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Nick\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Sleepover\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = New Nick\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Parents, Lily (sister), Mike (brother)\n}}\n\nNick is a boy who joined Henry's class as a \"new\" boy. He makes friends with Henry soon after he joins Henry's class and invites him to stay all night at his house. When Henry arrives, he has a thoroughly miserable evening. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===New Nick's parents===\nThey have two dogs and run a karaoke club of Scandinavian folk songs. They're very loud and only appear in ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover'' and ''Horrid Henry's Skipping Lesson''. They are voiced by [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]] and [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Ninius Nerdon===\nMr Nerdon was a teacher first featured in the story ''Horrid Henry's New Teacher''. After a prank pulled by Henry involving Peter, he collapsed and Miss Battle-Axe took over the class. \n\nIn the TV series, he was the substitute teacher for Henry's class when Miss Battle-Axe got the flu, although a prank involving frogs made him run away screaming from the class. He is voiced by [[Wayne Forester]]. He appears in the adaptation of ''Horrid Henry's New Teacher'' and later appears in Season 5 for the Brainbox of the Year contest.\n\n===Norwegian Norris===\nNorris is a Norwegian boy in Henry's class making his first appearance in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the book Horrid Henry's Nightmare. When there is a practice in the school he does not like, such as the lunchbox inspections and taking names out of the hat to see who should look after the class chicken, he wails that it wouldn't happen in Norway.\n\n===Nudie Foodie===\nMr Nudie Foodie is a celebrity chef based on [[Jamie Oliver]]. In ''Horrid Henry and the Nudie Foodie'', he visits the school to improve school dinners. He is sent away after Henry adds extra ingredients to his pasta sauce to make it taste bad. His name is a parody on the BBC programme ''[[The Naked Chef]]''.\n\n===Nurse Needle===\nNurse Needle is a nurse who appears in ''Horrid Henry's Injection''. She tried to give Henry an injection, but Henry pretended to be sick and was sent home.\n\n==P==\n\n===Park keeper===\nHe works in the park and employs Henry in ''Horrid Henry Gets A Job''. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Pasty Patsy===\nPasty Patsy is the daughter of Greasy Greta and appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Revenge of the Demon Dinner Lady'' from the book ''Horrid Henry's Nightmare''. When Henry asked her why she didn't get her lunchbox inspected, she replied that she is Greta's daughter and she could have what she wanted, much to Henry's surprise. She then opened her lunchbox and ate a handful of sweets and treats, while Henry's mouth watered.\n\n===Patrolling Patrick and Vigilant Vincent===\nIn some stories and episodes of Horrid Henry, there are some security guards that appear. Their names are Patrolling Patrick and Vigilant Vincent. They are voiced by Wayne Forester and Aidan Cook.\n\n===Perfect Peter===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Perfect Peter\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| franchise          = \n| image              = [https://hhenrystories.files.wordpress.com/2011/11/peter.jpg]\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'' (Books)<br>''Horrid Henry Tricks and Treats'' (TV series)\n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Francesca Simon]]\n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = Ross Marron\n| voice              = [[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]]\n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Perfect<br>Worm (as [[Horrid Henry|Henry]] and his friends call him)\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Human]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| occupation         = [[Student]]\n| family             = '''Brother''': [[Horrid Henry]]<br>'''Mother''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Mum|Mum]]<br>'''Father''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Dad|Dad ('Silly Simon')]]\n| spouse             = \n| significant_other   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = '''Cousins''': [[Stuck-up Steve]], [[Prissy Polly]], [[Vomiting Vera]] and [[Pimply Paul]] <br>'''Aunt''': [[Rich Aunt Ruby]]<br>'''Great aunt''': [[Great aunt Greta]]<br>'''Grandmother''': [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Grandma|Grandma]]<br>'''Uncle''': Fussy Francis\n| religion           = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| nationality        = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n}}\n'''[[Perfect Peter]]''' is Henry's perfect younger brother. He is often referred to as a \"worm\" by Henry. Peter has a very effeminate attitude, liking flowers much like [[Walter the Softy]] in the [[Dennis the Menace (UK comics)|Dennis the Menace]] comic strips and [[Dennis the Menace (1996 TV series)|cartoon series]], believes in fairy tales, and is known to always do as he is told and treat others with respect. On several occasions, however, he has revealed that he is in reality, very whiny and spoiled. It is obvious that Peter likes to get back at Henry with the help of his parents, and he always [[Emotional blackmail|emotionally bribes]] them (e.g.: \"You're the best mum in the world! So Henry won't be getting any biscuits will he?\"), resulting in his parents favouring him. Aside from being spoiled, he shows aspects of being sort of like Moody Margaret, except that instead of using a bossy tone, he adopts a crying and sorrowful look to get what he wants.\n\nOften, Henry gets into trouble as a result of Peter telling Mum or Dad when he has done something wrong, usually with the phrases \"Mum/Dad! Henry's being horrid/mean!\" or \"Mum/Dad! Henry called me a [[worm]]/a toad/told me to shut up!\", and he even blames Henry for the most minor offences. He has been known to blame Henry for things Henry doesn't do. He is also similar to his friends as he hates dirt, is always tidy and always does as he is told, unlike Henry. He also expects praise for even the most minor things, such as \"being normal\", using his fork and knife, and also shows off how good he is, especially when Henry is being reprimanded. This, and the fact that he always asks them politely.\n\nAt times, Peter can be desperate for praise and attention; he gets his toys out just to tidy them again in the episode \"Horrid Henry And The Best Boys Club\". In the same episode, it is hinted he sees the other members of \"The Best Boys Club\" as underlings rather than actual friends as he immediately refuses Gordon's suggestion of taking turns to decide things. This suggests that he only acts perfect because he gets praised. At times, he tries to take credit for Henry's rare good deeds, as shown in ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Day'', and in ''Horrid Henry Horrid Headmaster'', when he recorded what Henry said when Henry discovered he had to fill end of term reports (\"No holiday for me, then.\"), then modified it into \"No holiday!\", causing the students to rebel. He seldom defies orders or complains about said orders, though it has been revealed that his sweet-natured personality is soiled with narcissism; he has indeed defied adults or rules in revenge against Henry or while attempting to frame him, and he derives pleasure from Henry's suffering and punishments for poor behavior, implying that he may actually not be much better than his brother. Despite all this, Henry will still help Peter out on occasion, such as rescuing him from a falling shelf in the cellar in ''Horrid Henry Trapped''.\n\n====Live-action====\n* In 2011's ''[[Horrid Henry: The Movie]]'', Perfect Peter is shown as a pure goody-goody and never shows his bad side. He is one of the very few people who help save the school from [[List of Horrid Henry characters#Vic Van Wrinkle|Vic Van Wrinkle]].\n\n====Animation====\n* In 2006's ''[[Horrid Henry (TV series)|Horrid Henry]]'' TV series, Perfect Peter is the most recurring character apart from Henry.\n\n===Perky Parveen===\nShe is in Peter's class and is invited to Peter's birthday party. She is mentioned in ''Perfect Peter's Birthday Party''.\n\n===Pimply Paul===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Paul Peregrine\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Pimply Paul\n| species            = Human\n| spouse             = Polly\n| gender             = Male\n| family             = Polly, Vera\n| children           = Vomiting Vera\n| relatives          = Mum, Dad, Henry, Peter\n}}\n\nThe husband of Prissy Polly, who is a milkman and lives in a world of self pity and misery. He and Henry have a mutual hatred for each other, because Henry\u2019s a brat and Paul\u2019s a sour puss. He is a fan of [[rugby football|Rugby]], as revealed in Horrid Henry Cooks a Meal. He and Henry eventually develop a father-son relationship and start seeing each other eye-to-eye when Henry helps him with his route. Voiced by [[Wayne Forester]].\n\n===Prissy Polly===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Polly Penelope\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| nickname           = Prissy Polly\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| children           = Vera\n| relatives          = Henry, Peter, Mum, Dad, Ruby, Steve, Greta, Francis\n}}\n\nHenry's fussy, childish, ditzy, and uptight cousin who is usually seen smiling, until she reaches her breaking point. She marries Pimply Paul in Horrid Henry's Wedding and together, they had a daughter, Vera. Polly and Henry hate each other, and she wants everything to be her way, all the time (even to the discomfort of others, including her own family). She is voiced by [[Tamsin Heatley]]. She mostly wears a pink top, blue jeans, with a cyan blue sash-belt has curly blonde hair and wears beautiful pink high heel pumps. But in the film, she had her in a side braid with a yellow ribbon on the top of her head and she wore a cream dress with yellow and gold roses on it and a gold bracelet.\n\n==R==\n\n===Rabid Rebecca===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Rebecca Rancid\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter (Books and TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Rabid Rebecca, Miss Rancid\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = Babysitter\n| gender             = Female\n}}\n'''Rabid Rebecca''' is the toughest [[teenager]] in town, and is very strict. She once babysat Henry and Peter. Henry had a tough job getting rid of her, eventually succeeding after discovering that she was [[arachnophobia|scared of spiders]]. She has very large teeth and these are always visible even when her mouth is shut. She is introduced in [[Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter]] and makes a reappearance in ''Revenge of the Bogey Babysitter'' in the books. In the TV series she also appears in ''Horrid Henry's Smelly Stuff'', ''Horrid Henry's Haircut'', ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher'', and ''Horrid Henry and the Football Fiend'' in the audience at the match. She makes a cameo appearance in ''Horrid Henry and the Killer Boy Rats'', when she is shocked and is seen when Henry sings, \"Slimy, slimy, slimy!\" and Dad says, \"Don't be horrid, Henry!\" in the audience. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols. She appears as Miss Rancid, the substitute teacher in ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher'' and she is fired when Miss Oddbod sees her chasing Peter. She is training to become a hairdresser.\n\n===Razor Ron===\nRazor Ron is a barber who hates children. He cuts Henry's hair in ''Horrid Henry's Haircut''.\n\n===Rich Aunt Ruby===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ruby\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Christmas (Books and TV series)\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francesca Simon\n| nickname           = Rich Aunt Ruby\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Mother of Stuck-up Steve\n| family             = Steve\n| children           = [[#Stuck-up Steve|Steve]]\n| relatives          = Mum (sister), Dad, Henry, Peter, Paul, Polly, Vera, Greta, Grandma\n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = \n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n}}\nHenry's wealthy aunt, Mum's sister and Stuck-Up Steve's mother. She is shown to be a very posh lady and she's dressed very fashionable, and she speaks with a posh-sounding accent and she was first seen in Horrid Henry's Christmas, where she buys Steve loads of great presents and Henry \"somehow\" managed to help himself to a few of them by switching the labels, she was next seen in the episode [[Horrid Henry's Haunted House]], where Henry scares her and Steve away from their house and gets to play with all Steve's toys. She has previously been seen in ''Horrid Henry Dines at Restaurant Le Posh'', where she took Steve and Henry's family to a fancy French restaurant, and orders Mum, Dad and Peter the things they don't want. She also spoils Steve greatly and buys him anything and everything he wants and she and Steve live in a very large house. She has burgundy-purple hair, like Steve. Voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Rude Ralph===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ralph\n| series             = [[Horrid Henry]]\n| first              = Horrid Henry's Tricks and Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Aidan Cook]]\n| nickname           = Rude Ralph\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n}}\n'''Rude Ralph''' is Horrid Henry's best friend, who lives the life of luxury that Henry dreams of having. He gladly assists Henry in many of his plans, including plots to raid [[Moody Margaret]]'s Secret Club, with him being a member of Henry's \"Purple Hand Gang\". Contrary to his alliterative nickname, he is actually much more friendly, laid-back, and sensible than Henry. Unlike Henry, he doesn\u2019t mind eating healthy food or hanging out with girls, and he even befriends Peter in a few episodes. He wears a red hoodie and white capri pants. Besides Henry, he is often seen with Al and Bert. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Rude Ralph's dad===\nRude Ralph's dad cheers Ralph on in ''Horrid Henry's Sports Day'' and also appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Go Kart''.\n\n===Rude Ralph's mum===\nRude Ralph's mum picks Ralph up from Henry's in ''Horrid Henry's Fairy Dance'' and is seen calling Henry's Dad on ''Horrid Henry's Sleepover''. She was also seen in ''Horrid Henry Gets The Message'', ''Horrid Henry and the Purple Pass'' and ''Horrid Henry's Perfect Panto'' where she was seeing her son performing in the school panto. She is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n==S==\n\n===Singing Soraya===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Soraya\n| nickname           = Singing Soraya\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n}}\nAn Indian girl in Henry's class who loves singing. She even sounds like she's singing when she's talking normally. Soraya wears a yellow blouse with blue pants and orange [[keds]]. Voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]].\n\n===Slimy Sammy===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Sammy\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Perfect Peter's Pen Pal\n| last               = TBA\n| nickname           = Slimy Sammy, Super Sammy\n| species            = Human\n}}\nSammy first appeared in the episode Perfect Peter's Pen Pal. He stays at Peter's house and attempts to steal his stamp collection, as well as getting Henry into trouble. Despite the fact he appears to be French and speaks French, he talks with a German-sounding accent. Peter first calls him Super Sammy. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Snappy Croc===\nSnappy Croc is a [[crocodile|toy crocodile]] who was first seen in ''Horrid Henry's Bathtime''.\n\n===Soggy Sid===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Sidmouth Soggington\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| portrayer          = Aidan Cook\n| nickname           = Soggy Sid, Mr. Soggington, Sidmouth\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = \n| franchise          = \n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| first              = \n| firstgame          = \n| last               = \n| creator            = \n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| voice              = \n| full_name          = \n| origin             = \n| home               = \n| occupation         = PE teacher\n}}\nSoggy Sid is Horrid Henry's swimming teacher and the school's sport coach. He also appears in some episodes as the caretaker of the school. In one episode, his name is revealed to be Sidmouth Soggington. He is voiced by [[Aidan Cook]].\n\n===Sour Susan===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Susan\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Tricks or Treats\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]<br />[[Helena Barlow]]\n| nickname           = Sour Susan\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| family             = Vicious Vicky (younger sister)\n}}\n\nSour Susan is the best friend of Moody Margaret. She always has a sour look on her face and often says \"Yeah, Henry.\" when Margaret offends or annoys him. She acts as a budgie and sidekick to Moody Margaret, but often has fallouts with her. She has a baby sister called Vicious Vicky. In TV Series, she has orange hair and wears a lime dress with dark green effects. In ''Horrid Henry's Stinkbomb'', she joins the Purple Hand Gang, and warns Henry about Margaret's stinkbomb. She is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]] and portrayed by [[Helena Barlow]].\n\n===Spotless Sam===\nSpotless Sam is one of Peter's friends and a member of the Best Boys Club. He is voiced by Emma Tate. He has black hair and wears a white shirt with blue stripes, and blue [[capri pants]].\n\n===Stone-Age Steven===\nStone-Age Steven is a minor character in Henry's class. He likes pretending to be a caveman.\n\n===Stuck-Up Steve===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Steve\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| last               = Ongoing\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = [[Joanna Ruiz]]\n| nickname           = Stuck-up Steve\n| species            = Human\n| spouse             = Unknown\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Son of Rich Aunt Ruby\n| family             = [[#Rich Aunt Ruby|Ruby]]\n| children           = none\n| relatives          = [[#Horrid Henry|Henry]], [[#Perfect Peter|Peter]], [[#Dad|Dad]], Mum, Grandma, Grandpa, Paul, Polly, Vera, Greta\n}}\n\nSteve is Henry's Stuck up Cousin. Henry calls him \"Stuck-Up\" because of how rich, greedy and spoiled he is compared to him. Once Steve got a taste of his own medicine in Horrid Henry and The Perfect Plane when the park keeper caught him flying his toy plane in the park and he takes it away from Steve and gives it to Mike. In the series 5 episode ''Horrid Henry\u2019s Class Action,'' he faces Henry in the School Council election'','' also In ''Horrid Henry Eats Out'', Henry wins by eating all his snails. Steve is hated by Henry for a particular reason - because he is spoiled and refuses to share with his cousin, Henry. Henry always knows that Steve does not look forward to seeing him, as in ''Horrid Henry's Christmas'', he switched the labels on his and Steve's presents, allowing him to help himself to some presents intended for Steve while Steve gets presents, such as socks, intended for Henry, and in ''Horrid Henry's Haunted House'', he convinced Steve that there was a monster under his bed. In the television series, he speaks with what is seemingly an upper class London accent and has reddish-purple hair. The turtleneck jumper he wears also appears to change colour between episodes - it is light green in most episodes, but is purple in ''Horrid Henry's Haunted House''. He is voiced by [[Joanna Ruiz]] in the TV series.\n\n===Super Sally===\n\nSuper Sally is a character in ''Manners with Maggie'' in \"''Horrid Henry Minds His Manners''\". She works at the TV station.\n\n==T==\n\n===T.J. Fizz===\nShe is Henry's favourite author and Peter's least favourite, because he says \"her books are too scary\". She has only been seen in ''Horrid Henry's Author Visit''. Miss Battle-axe sent him off from his to Peter's class because of his horridness and was stuck with Peter's favourite author. In the TV Series, she is known as \"B.B. Silver\".\n\n===Tell-Tale Tim===\nHe is one of Peter's friends.\n\n===Tetchy Tess===\nTetchy Tess is one of Horrid Henry's babysitters. After Henry floods the bathroom, she refuses to come back. She appears in ''Horrid Henry and the Bogey Babysitter'' and ''Horrid Henry Goes to the Park''. She is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Tidy Ted===\nTidy Ted is one of Peter's friends and is a member of the Best Boys Club. He is always tidy, hence his name. He is voiced by Tamsin Heatley. He has ginger-colored hair, wears a [[Periwinkle (color)|periwinkle]] sweater, cyan neck-tie, white shirt, with blue trousers, and brown shoes. His hairstyle and voice often mistake some for thinking he is a girl.\n\n===Tiddles===\nTiddles is Mrs (Miss) Oddbod's cat. It appeared in ''Horrid Henry on Trial'', ''Horrid Henry:'' ''It's All Your Fault!'' and ''Horrid Henry and the Terrible Teacher''.\n\n===Toddler Tom===\nHe is a toddler who is mentioned in several episodes.\n\n===Tornado Tariq===\nHe is mentioned in ''Horrid Henry's household chores'' and is a contestant in Hog House.\n\n===Tough Toby===\nTough Toby is a boy in Henry's class who is tough. He invited Henry to his party at Lazer Zap in ''Horrid Henry's Birthday Party''.\n\n==V==\n\n===Vain Violet===\nShe appears in several of the books and is friends with Margaret. She takes a lot of pride in her appearance, and she enjoys makeovers. She never appeared in the TV series.\n\n===Vicious Vicky===\nVicious Vicky first appears in ''Horrid Henry The Movie'' and in the TV Series 3 episode ''Horrid Henry Bogus Babysitter''. She is Sour Susan's younger sister. In the Series 2 episode ''Horrid Henry Changes a Nappy'' Susan mentions a baby sister whom she has to change her nappies explaining her experience. However, Vicky is seen as a toddler or possibly an infant at Ashton Primary.\nVicious Vicky is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols and played by [[Kia Pegg]]. In ''The Movie'' she bites people. In the TV series after being thrown out by Moody Margaret, Vicky finds her way into Henry's house and raids the kitchen. She then steals Margaret's cutlass and uses it to frame her. Henry is impressed by this after initially being afraid of her. However in her next appearance in ''It's All Your Fault'' she scares Henry away from the climbing frame in the school playground and also intimidates Wheely Walter.\n\n===Vic Van Wrinkle===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Vicent Van Wrinkle\n| first              = Horrid Henry The Movie (only appearance)\n| nickname           = Vic Van Wrinkle\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Headmaster of Brickhouse School\n}}\n\nVic Van Wrinkle is the strict, fiery-tempered headmaster of \"Brickhouse School\" and the main antagonist in ''Horrid Henry The Movie''. He tries to shut down Ashton Primary school and send all the students to Brickhouse School so he can make lots of money to shut down all the schools in Ashton.\n\n===Vomiting Vera===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Vera Venetia Verocula\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Horrid Henry Changes A Nappy\n| last               = TBA\n| creator            = Francessa Simon\n| portrayer          = '''Voice'''<br>[[Tamsin Heatley]]\n| nickname           = Vomiting Vera\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = Daughter of Prissy Polly & Pimply Paul\n| family             = [[#Pimply Paul|Paul]], [[#Prissy Polly|Polly]]\n| relatives          = [[#Mum|Mum]], [[Perfect Peter|Peter]], [[#Horrid Henry|Henry]], Dad\n}}\nHenry and Peter's baby first cousin once removed who is always vomiting, much to the annoyance of others. Henry will refuse to see her unless she is older and behind bars. She has blonde hair, wears a pink long-sleeved undershirt, light pink tank top with vertical magenta stripes, pink skirt, an orange hair ribbon, and dark pink stockings. She likes to watch Happy Hippos.\n\n==W==\n\n===Weepy William===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = William\n| series             = Horrid Henry\n| first              = Unknown\n| last               = TBA\n| portrayer          = Sue Elliott-Nichols\n| nickname           = Weepy William\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Son of his mum and dad\n| family             = Dad, Mum, [[Needy Neil]] (brother)\n}}\nA boy in Henry's class who is often seen crying at the slightest things. His best friend is Anxious Andrew. William has a younger brother called Needy Neil.\n\nNeedy Neil is in Miss Lovely's class. He wears a [[purple]] [[sweatshirt]], pale green undershirt with [[beige]]-trousers and brown shoes. He is voiced by Sue Elliott-Nichols.\n\n===Weepy William's Dad===\nWeepy William's dad is a newspaper reporter and appears in ''Horrid Henry Ace Reporter'' and ''Horrid Henry on TV''.\n\n===Weepy William's Mum===\nWeepy William's mum only appears in ''Horrid Henry on TV'' when her and her husband have Margaret round.\n\n===Wheely Walter===\nWheely Walter is a teacher at Ashton Primary who is disabled and uses a wheelchair. He is introduced in the third series episode ''Horrid Henry and the Climbing Frame Clincher'', teaching science, and his name is revealed in the episode ''Horrid Henry and the Movie Star'' when he auditions for the part of a dead ringer for Lose Laser Larry but is fired for being \"too wheely\". He appears to get along with Henry, unlike the other teachers, but still sends him along with Moody Margaret to Miss Oddbod's office when they argue in his class during his first appearance. In the episode ''Horrid Henry's Teacher Talk'', he claims that once Horrid Henry once turned the ceiling blue in his class while he was making a cup of tea.\n\n==Z==\n\n===Zippy Zoe===\nZippy Zoe is a girl who is very fast and only appears in the books. She is in Henry's class.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Horrid Henry]]\n*[[Horrid Henry (TV series)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Horrid Henry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horrid Henry Characters}}\n[[Category:Horrid Henry characters| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of characters in British television animation]]\n", "name_user": "Tbun2873", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBossy Bill", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Horrid_Henry_characters"}
{"title_page": "Maya Hawke", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020|cs1-dates=ll}}\n{{short description|American actress and model}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maya Hawke\n| image              = Maya Hawke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| caption            = Hawke in 2019\n| birth_name         = Maya Ray Thurman Hawke\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1998|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actress\n* model \n}}\n| years_active       = 2017\u2013present\n| parents            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ethan Hawke]]\n* [[Uma Thurman]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Maya Ray Thurman Hawke'''<ref name=obit>{{cite news|date=October 14, 2005|title=Obituaries|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|pages=B5 Metro|quote=Howard Green, 84, passed away Thursday, Oct. 13, 2005.... Survivors: Wife, Mary Utley Green; daughter, Leslie Green Hawke of Bucharest, Romania; grandson, Ethan Green Hawke and his offspring: Maya Thurman Hawke and Levon Green Hawke, of New York, N.Y....|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10D3E36BDF31CB48&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|access-date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> (born July 8, 1998<ref name=\"ET-Online\" />) is an American actress and model. She is the daughter of actress [[Uma Thurman]] and actor [[Ethan Hawke]]. After beginning her career in modeling, Hawke made her screen debut as [[Jo March]] in the 2017 [[BBC]] [[Little Women (2017 TV series)|adaptation]] of ''[[Little Women]]'' and starred as [[List_of_Stranger_Things_characters#Robin_Buckley|Robin]] in the third season of the [[Netflix]] series, ''[[Stranger Things]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nHawke was born on July 8, 1998,<ref name=\"ET-Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/movies/211045_uma_thurman_opens_up_about_the_worst_decision_she_made_turning_down_a_role|title=Uma Thurman Opens Up About the 'Worst Decision' She's Made in Turning Down a Role|last=Chestang|first=Raphael|date=February 21, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref> in [[New York City]], the older of two children born to actors [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Uma Thurman]].<ref name=vogue/> Her parents met on the set of ''[[Gattaca]]'' (1997), married in May 1998,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,283132,00.html |title=Monitor|last1=Cheng|first1=Kipp|last2=Chang|first2=Suna|date=May 15, 1998|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref> and divorced in 2005.<ref name=\"people2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1115532,00.html|title=Uma Calls Split from Ethan 'Excruciating'|date=October 7, 2005 |work = People |publisher=Time Inc. |access-date=July 17, 2013 |first=Stephen M.|last=Silverman}}</ref> Hawke's brother was born in 2002.<ref name=obit /><ref name=sydney>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke, daughter of Hollywood royalty, on scaring men and making Little Women |date=December 22, 2017 |author=Mulkerrins, Jane |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/maya-hawke-daughter-of-hollywood-royalty-on-scaring-men-and-making-little-women-20171213-h04dvj.html|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> She also has two half-sisters (born in 2008 and 2011) by her father's second wife, Ryan  Shawhughes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2008-07-23-ethan-hawke_N.htm|title=Ethan Hawke and wife welcome daughter Clementine|date=July 23, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=February 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/report-ethan-hawke-welcomes-a-baby-girl_article_51735|title=Report: It's A Girl For Ethan Hawke|date=August 6, 2011|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|access-date=August 6, 2011}}</ref> She has another half-sister (born in 2012) from her mother's ex-fianc\u00e9, [[financier]] [[Arpad Busson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2012/10/17/uma-thurman-arpad-busson-name-daughter-rosalind-arusha-arkadina-altalune-florence/|title=Uma Thurman Daughter's Name Revealed|date=October 17, 2012|work=People|publisher=Time Inc.|access-date=July 17, 2013|quote='I would like to announce Uma and Arki's daughter's name for the first time officially: Rosalind Arusha Arkadina Altalune Florence Thurman-Busson, better known to family and friends as Luna,' the actress's rep Gabrielle Kachman tells ''People'' exclusively.}}</ref>\n\nOn her father's side, Hawke is a great-great-grandniece of playwright [[Tennessee Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2013/01/13/theater/in-his-comfort-zone.html?pagewanted=all|title=In His Comfort Zone|last=Carr|first=David|date=January 10, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 22, 2013}}</ref> On her mother's side, she is a granddaughter of Buddhist scholar [[Robert A. F. Thurman]] and model [[Nena von Schlebr\u00fcgge]].<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Robert Thurman Doesn't Look Buddhist |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/07/12/specials/thurman-profile.html|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|date=May 5, 1996|access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Schlebr\u00fcgge's mother, Birgit Holmquist, was also a model, having posed for Axel Ebbe's statue ''Famntaget'', currently in [[Smygehuk]] in [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/kultur--nojen/uma-thurmans-mormor-staty-i-trelleborg/ |first=Alexander |last=Kuprijanko |title=Uma Thurmans mormor staty i Trelleborg |trans-title=Uma Thurman's grandmother's statue in Trelleborg |date=July 20, 2006 |work=[[Sydsvenskan]] |language=sv}}</ref>\n\nHawke has [[dyslexia]], which resulted in her changing schools frequently during her primary education before she was finally enrolled at [[Saint Ann's School (Brooklyn)|Saint Ann's School]], a private school in [[Brooklyn]], New York that emphasizes artistic creativity and does not grade work. The artistic environment eventually led her to acting.<ref name=sydney/> Hawke also took part in summer studies at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts in London and the renowned [[Stella Adler Studio of Acting]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lynn|last=Elber|url=https://www.apnews.com/68411f63a358436db774961e18df114b|title=Maya Hawke makes the most of 'Little Women' screen debut|agency=Associated Press|date=May 10, 2018|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref> She attended the performing arts school [[Juilliard School|Juilliard]] for one year before being forced to drop out after accepting her role in ''Little Women''.<ref name=sydney/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Modeling===\nLike both her mother and grandmother, Hawke modelled for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' at the beginning of her career.<ref name=vogue>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke On Little Women And Following Her Parents Footsteps|author=Olivia Markes|date=December 26, 2017|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/maya-hawke-on-little-women-and-following-her-parents-footsteps|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Norman Parkinson|date=October 12, 2009|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/norman-parkinson|access-date=February 5, 2018}}</ref> She was also chosen as the face of the British fashion retailer [[AllSaints]]'s 2016/2017 collection.<ref name=sydney/> In 2017, she starred as one of several faces in a video campaign for [[Calvin Klein]]'s underwear range, directed by [[Sofia Coppola]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/nenvd7/sofia-coppola-explores-first-kisses-and-crushes-for-calvin-kleins-new-underwear-campaign|title=sofia coppola explores first kisses and crushes for calvin klein's new underwear campaign|author=Hannah Ongley|website=[[i-D]]|date=April 18, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Acting===\nHawke was Sofia Coppola's choice to play the title role of [[The Little Mermaid]] in [[Universal Pictures]]'s planned live-action adaptation. However, the producers preferred the better-known [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]. This and other conflicts ultimately led to Coppola leaving the project.<ref name=variety>{{cite web|title=Sofia Coppola Is No Longer Directing 'The Little Mermaid'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sofia-coppola-exits-the-little-mermaid-1201509589/|date=June 1, 2015|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> However, Moretz eventually dropped out as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid' Gets 3 Different Movie Adaptations|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/the-little-mermaid-gets-3-different-movie-adaptations|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|author=De Elizabeth|date=April 5, 2017|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Hawke made her acting debut as [[Jo March]] in the [[BBC]] [[Little Women (2017 TV series)|miniseries adaptation]] of ''[[Little Women]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC One and Playground announce Little Women cast|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/little-women|date=July 6, 2017|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=sydney /> Hawke's breakout role came through her co-starring performance as Robin Buckley in the [[Stranger Things (season 3)|third season]] of [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things]]'', which was released in 2019. Hawke, as Robin, spent most of her scenes with [[Joe Keery]]'s character of [[Steve Harrington]] as co-workers at a local ice-cream parlor before stumbling onto a larger mystery, creating a popular and critically favored pair of characters for the season.<ref name=\"Stranger-Things\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/stranger-things-season-3-new-character-maya-thurman-hawke-1202715637/|title='Stranger Things' Season 3 Adds Maya Hawke, Ups Priah Ferguson|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=Variety|date=March 2, 2018|access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/stranger-things-season-3-maya-hawke-robins-breakout-storyline-1222560 | title = 'Stranger Things': Maya Hawke Pulls the Curtain Back on Season 3 Breakout Role | first = Josh | last=  Wigler | date = July 4, 2019 | accessdate = July 24, 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref> Also that summer, Hawke played [[Linda Kasabian]] in [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''.<ref name=\"OUaTiH\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/lena-dunham-austin-butler-maya-hawke-lorenza-izzo-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202450671/|title=Lena Dunham, Austin Butler, Maya Hawke, Lorenza Izzo Board Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=August 22, 2018|access-date=August 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, it was announced that Hawke will star in [[Gia Coppola]]'s sophomore film, ''[[Mainstream (film)|Mainstream]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenandhollywood.com/gia-coppola-to-direct-mainstream-a-love-triangle-featuring-rising-star-maya-hawke/|title=Gia Coppola to Direct \u201cMainstream,\u201d a Love Triangle Featuring Rising Star Maya Hawke|website=Womenandhollywood.com|first=Laura|last=Berger|date=October 31, 2018|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/gia-coppola-mainstream-johnny-knoxville-chris-messina-alexa-demie-colleen-camp-1202614841/|title=Johnny Knoxville, Chris Messina, Alexa Demie, Colleen Camp Join Gia Coppola\u2019s \u2018Mainstream\u2019|first=Mike Jr|last=Fleming|date=May 14, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nIn August 2019, Hawke released her first two singles, \"To Love A Boy\" and \"Stay Open\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/maya-hawke-debut-singles/|title=Maya Hawke's Debut Singles: Stream Them Here|last=Sawyer|first=Jonathan|date=August 22, 2019|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> The songs were written and recorded by Hawke and [[Grammy Award]]-winning singer-songwriter [[Jesse Harris]], on March 18, 2020 Hawke released the first single \u201cBy Myself\u201d from her upcoming debut album titled \u201cBlush\u201d which is set to release on June 19, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke Announces Her Debut Album Blush, Shares New Single \u201cBy Myself\u201d|author=Isabella DeLeo |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/maya-hawke/maya-hawke-shares-new-single-by-myself-and-announc/|date= March 18, 2020|publisher=paste.com|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/maya-hawke-new-music-debut-singles-1203305567/|title=Maya Hawke Debuts Two Singles Ahead of Album Release|last=Nickolai|first=Nate|date=August 18, 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television and film roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Little Women (2017 TV series)|Little Women]]''\n| Jo March\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Ladyworld]]''\n| Romy\n| Film<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a19181626/maya-hawke-april-2018/|title=Maya Hawke Gets Into the Family Business With the Literary Role of a Lifetime: Jo March|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|first=Keziah|last=Weir|date=April 2, 2018|accessdate=August 26, 2018|quote=...and shot her first movie, a female-driven indie called ''Ladyworld'' about a group of teenage girls at a truly hellish sleepover birthday party.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/fantastic-fest-2018-overlord-apostle-the-night-comes-for-us-first-wave-1202436895/|title=Fantastic Fest 2018 Sets 'Overlord', 'Apostle', & 'The Night Comes For Us' In First Wave Of Programming|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Dino-Ray|last=Ramos|date=July 31, 2018|access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''\n| [[Linda Kasabian|\"Flower Child\"]]\n| Film<ref name=\"OUaTiH\" />\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| Robin Buckley\n| Main role ([[Stranger Things (season 3)|season 3]])<ref name=\"Stranger-Things\" /><br/>Won \u2013 [[Saturn Award]] for Best Supporting Actress in Streaming Presentation (2019)<ref>{{cite web |first=Geoff|last=Boucher |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/saturn-awards-2019-winners-list-jon-favreau-kevin-feige-stan-lee-1202734450/ |title=Saturn Awards: 'Spider-Man' Star Tom Holland Wins For Third Year In A Row |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 13, 2019 |access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Human Capital (2019 film)|Human Capital]]''\n| Shannon\n| Film<ref>{{cite web|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/peter-sarsgaard-maya-hawke-betty-gabriel-human-capital-1202502097/|title=Peter Sarsgaard, Maya Hawke & 'Get Out's Betty Gabriel Are 'Human Capital'|date=November 14, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| ''[[Mainstream (film)|Mainstream]]''\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Film; post-production<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/andrew-garfield-gia-coppola-mainstream-1203015645/|title=Film News Roundup: Andrew Garfield Joins Gia Coppola's Romance Movie 'Mainstream'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=October 30, 2018|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawke, Maya}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Saint Ann's School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Stella Adler Studio of Acting alumni]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019|cs1-dates=ll}}\n{{short description|American actress and model}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maya Hawke\n| image              = Maya Hawke 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| caption            = Hawke in 2019\n| birth_name         = Maya Ray Thurman Hawke\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1998|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actress\n* model \n}}\n| years_active       = 2017\u2013present\n| parents            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ethan Hawke]]\n* [[Uma Thurman]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Maya Ray Thurman Hawke'''<ref name=obit>{{cite news|date=October 14, 2005|title=Obituaries|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|pages=B5 Metro|quote=Howard Green, 84, passed away Thursday, Oct. 13, 2005.... Survivors: Wife, Mary Utley Green; daughter, Leslie Green Hawke of Bucharest, Romania; grandson, Ethan Green Hawke and his offspring: Maya Thurman Hawke and Levon Green Hawke, of New York, N.Y....|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10D3E36BDF31CB48&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|access-date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> (born July 8, 1998<ref name=\"ET-Online\" />) is an American actress and model. She is the daughter of actress [[Uma Thurman]] and actor [[Ethan Hawke]]. After beginning her career in modeling, Hawke made her screen debut as [[Jo March]] in the 2017 [[BBC]] [[Little Women (2017 TV series)|adaptation]] of ''[[Little Women]]'' and starred as [[List_of_Stranger_Things_characters#Robin_Buckley|Robin]] in the third season of the [[Netflix]] series, ''[[Stranger Things]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nHawke was born on July 8, 1998,<ref name=\"ET-Online\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/movies/211045_uma_thurman_opens_up_about_the_worst_decision_she_made_turning_down_a_role|title=Uma Thurman Opens Up About the 'Worst Decision' She's Made in Turning Down a Role|last=Chestang|first=Raphael|date=February 21, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref> in [[New York City]], the older of two children born to actors [[Ethan Hawke]] and [[Uma Thurman]].<ref name=vogue/> Her parents met on the set of ''[[Gattaca]]'' (1997), married in May 1998,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,283132,00.html |title=Monitor|last1=Cheng|first1=Kipp|last2=Chang|first2=Suna|date=May 15, 1998|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=March 28, 2011}}</ref> and divorced in 2005.<ref name=\"people2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1115532,00.html|title=Uma Calls Split from Ethan 'Excruciating'|date=October 7, 2005 |work = People |publisher=Time Inc. |access-date=July 17, 2013 |first=Stephen M.|last=Silverman}}</ref> Hawke's brother was born in 2002.<ref name=obit /><ref name=sydney>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke, daughter of Hollywood royalty, on scaring men and making Little Women |date=December 22, 2017 |author=Mulkerrins, Jane |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/maya-hawke-daughter-of-hollywood-royalty-on-scaring-men-and-making-little-women-20171213-h04dvj.html|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> She also has two half-sisters (born in 2008 and 2011) by her father's second wife, Ryan  Shawhughes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2008-07-23-ethan-hawke_N.htm|title=Ethan Hawke and wife welcome daughter Clementine|date=July 23, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=February 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/report-ethan-hawke-welcomes-a-baby-girl_article_51735|title=Report: It's A Girl For Ethan Hawke|date=August 6, 2011|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|access-date=August 6, 2011}}</ref> She has another half-sister (born in 2012) from her mother's ex-fianc\u00e9, [[financier]] [[Arpad Busson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2012/10/17/uma-thurman-arpad-busson-name-daughter-rosalind-arusha-arkadina-altalune-florence/|title=Uma Thurman Daughter's Name Revealed|date=October 17, 2012|work=People|publisher=Time Inc.|access-date=July 17, 2013|quote='I would like to announce Uma and Arki's daughter's name for the first time officially: Rosalind Arusha Arkadina Altalune Florence Thurman-Busson, better known to family and friends as Luna,' the actress's rep Gabrielle Kachman tells ''People'' exclusively.}}</ref>\n\nOn her father's side, Hawke is a great-great-grandniece of playwright [[Tennessee Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2013/01/13/theater/in-his-comfort-zone.html?pagewanted=all|title=In His Comfort Zone|last=Carr|first=David|date=January 10, 2013|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 22, 2013}}</ref> On her mother's side, she is a granddaughter of Buddhist scholar [[Robert A. F. Thurman]] and model [[Nena von Schlebr\u00fcgge]].<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Robert Thurman Doesn't Look Buddhist |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/07/12/specials/thurman-profile.html|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|date=May 5, 1996|access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Schlebr\u00fcgge's mother, Birgit Holmquist, was also a model, having posed for Axel Ebbe's statue ''Famntaget'', currently in [[Smygehuk]] in [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/kultur--nojen/uma-thurmans-mormor-staty-i-trelleborg/ |first=Alexander |last=Kuprijanko |title=Uma Thurmans mormor staty i Trelleborg |trans-title=Uma Thurman's grandmother's statue in Trelleborg |date=July 20, 2006 |work=[[Sydsvenskan]] |language=sv}}</ref>\n\nHawke has [[dyslexia]], which resulted in her changing schools frequently during her primary education before she was finally enrolled at [[Saint Ann's School (Brooklyn)|Saint Ann's School]], a private school in [[Brooklyn]], New York that emphasizes artistic creativity and does not grade work. The artistic environment eventually led her to acting.<ref name=sydney/> Hawke also took part in summer studies at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts in London and the renowned [[Stella Adler Studio of Acting]] in New York.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lynn|last=Elber|url=https://www.apnews.com/68411f63a358436db774961e18df114b|title=Maya Hawke makes the most of 'Little Women' screen debut|agency=Associated Press|date=May 10, 2018|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref> She attended the performing arts school [[Juilliard School|Juilliard]] for one year before being forced to drop out after accepting her role in ''Little Women''.<ref name=sydney/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Modeling===\nLike both her mother and grandmother, Hawke modelled for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' at the beginning of her career.<ref name=vogue>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke On Little Women And Following Her Parents Footsteps|author=Olivia Markes|date=December 26, 2017|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/maya-hawke-on-little-women-and-following-her-parents-footsteps|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Norman Parkinson|date=October 12, 2009|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/norman-parkinson|access-date=February 5, 2018}}</ref> She was also chosen as the face of the British fashion retailer [[AllSaints]]'s 2016/2017 collection.<ref name=sydney/> In 2017, she starred as one of several faces in a video campaign for [[Calvin Klein]]'s underwear range, directed by [[Sofia Coppola]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/nenvd7/sofia-coppola-explores-first-kisses-and-crushes-for-calvin-kleins-new-underwear-campaign|title=sofia coppola explores first kisses and crushes for calvin klein's new underwear campaign|author=Hannah Ongley|website=[[i-D]]|date=April 18, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Acting===\nHawke was Sofia Coppola's choice to play the title role of [[The Little Mermaid]] in [[Universal Pictures]]'s planned live-action adaptation. However, the producers preferred the better-known [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]. This and other conflicts ultimately led to Coppola leaving the project.<ref name=variety>{{cite web|title=Sofia Coppola Is No Longer Directing 'The Little Mermaid'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sofia-coppola-exits-the-little-mermaid-1201509589/|date=June 1, 2015|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> However, Moretz eventually dropped out as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Little Mermaid' Gets 3 Different Movie Adaptations|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/the-little-mermaid-gets-3-different-movie-adaptations|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|author=De Elizabeth|date=April 5, 2017|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Hawke made her acting debut as [[Jo March]] in the [[BBC]] [[Little Women (2017 TV series)|miniseries adaptation]] of ''[[Little Women]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC One and Playground announce Little Women cast|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/little-women|date=July 6, 2017|access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=sydney /> Hawke's breakout role came through her co-starring performance as Robin Buckley in the [[Stranger Things (season 3)|third season]] of [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Stranger Things]]'', which was released in 2019. Hawke, as Robin, spent most of her scenes with [[Joe Keery]]'s character of [[Steve Harrington]] as co-workers at a local ice-cream parlor before stumbling onto a larger mystery, creating a popular and critically favored pair of characters for the season.<ref name=\"Stranger-Things\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/stranger-things-season-3-new-character-maya-thurman-hawke-1202715637/|title='Stranger Things' Season 3 Adds Maya Hawke, Ups Priah Ferguson|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=Variety|date=March 2, 2018|access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/stranger-things-season-3-maya-hawke-robins-breakout-storyline-1222560 | title = 'Stranger Things': Maya Hawke Pulls the Curtain Back on Season 3 Breakout Role | first = Josh | last=  Wigler | date = July 4, 2019 | accessdate = July 24, 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref> Also that summer, Hawke played [[Linda Kasabian]] in [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''.<ref name=\"OUaTiH\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/lena-dunham-austin-butler-maya-hawke-lorenza-izzo-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202450671/|title=Lena Dunham, Austin Butler, Maya Hawke, Lorenza Izzo Board Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=August 22, 2018|access-date=August 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, it was announced that Hawke will star in [[Gia Coppola]]'s sophomore film, ''[[Mainstream (film)|Mainstream]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenandhollywood.com/gia-coppola-to-direct-mainstream-a-love-triangle-featuring-rising-star-maya-hawke/|title=Gia Coppola to Direct \u201cMainstream,\u201d a Love Triangle Featuring Rising Star Maya Hawke|website=Womenandhollywood.com|first=Laura|last=Berger|date=October 31, 2018|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/gia-coppola-mainstream-johnny-knoxville-chris-messina-alexa-demie-colleen-camp-1202614841/|title=Johnny Knoxville, Chris Messina, Alexa Demie, Colleen Camp Join Gia Coppola\u2019s \u2018Mainstream\u2019|first=Mike Jr|last=Fleming|date=May 14, 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nIn August 2019, Hawke released her first two singles, \"To Love A Boy\" and \"Stay Open\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/maya-hawke-debut-singles/|title=Maya Hawke's Debut Singles: Stream Them Here|last=Sawyer|first=Jonathan|date=August 22, 2019|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref> The songs were written and recorded by Hawke and [[Grammy Award]]-winning singer-songwriter [[Jesse Harris]], on March 18, 2020 Hawke released the first single \u201cBy Myself\u201d from her upcoming debut album titled \u201cBlush\u201d which is set to release on June 19, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maya Hawke Announces Her Debut Album Blush, Shares New Single \u201cBy Myself\u201d|author=Isabella DeLeo |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/maya-hawke/maya-hawke-shares-new-single-by-myself-and-announc/|date= March 18, 2020|publisher=paste.com|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/maya-hawke-new-music-debut-singles-1203305567/|title=Maya Hawke Debuts Two Singles Ahead of Album Release|last=Nickolai|first=Nate|date=August 18, 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television and film roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Little Women (2017 TV series)|Little Women]]''\n| Jo March\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Ladyworld]]''\n| Romy\n| Film<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a19181626/maya-hawke-april-2018/|title=Maya Hawke Gets Into the Family Business With the Literary Role of a Lifetime: Jo March|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|first=Keziah|last=Weir|date=April 2, 2018|accessdate=August 26, 2018|quote=...and shot her first movie, a female-driven indie called ''Ladyworld'' about a group of teenage girls at a truly hellish sleepover birthday party.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/fantastic-fest-2018-overlord-apostle-the-night-comes-for-us-first-wave-1202436895/|title=Fantastic Fest 2018 Sets 'Overlord', 'Apostle', & 'The Night Comes For Us' In First Wave Of Programming|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Dino-Ray|last=Ramos|date=July 31, 2018|access-date=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]''\n| [[Linda Kasabian|\"Flower Child\"]]\n| Film<ref name=\"OUaTiH\" />\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| Robin Buckley\n| Main role ([[Stranger Things (season 3)|season 3]])<ref name=\"Stranger-Things\" /><br/>Won \u2013 [[Saturn Award]] for Best Supporting Actress in Streaming Presentation (2019)<ref>{{cite web |first=Geoff|last=Boucher |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/saturn-awards-2019-winners-list-jon-favreau-kevin-feige-stan-lee-1202734450/ |title=Saturn Awards: 'Spider-Man' Star Tom Holland Wins For Third Year In A Row |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=September 13, 2019 |access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Human Capital (2019 film)|Human Capital]]''\n| Shannon\n| Film<ref>{{cite web|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/peter-sarsgaard-maya-hawke-betty-gabriel-human-capital-1202502097/|title=Peter Sarsgaard, Maya Hawke & 'Get Out's Betty Gabriel Are 'Human Capital'|date=November 14, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| ''[[Mainstream (film)|Mainstream]]''\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Film; post-production<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/andrew-garfield-gia-coppola-mainstream-1203015645/|title=Film News Roundup: Andrew Garfield Joins Gia Coppola's Romance Movie 'Mainstream'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=October 30, 2018|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawke, Maya}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Saint Ann's School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Stella Adler Studio of Acting alumni]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n", "name_user": "Abbyjjjj96", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unified date format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_Hawke"}
{"title_page": "Trial of Louis XVI", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:ExaminationLouistheLast.jpg|thumb|325px|\"Louis the Last\" being cross-examined by the Convention.]]\n{{Expand French|Proc\u00e8s de Louis XVI|date=January 2009}}\nThe '''trial of Louis XVI'''. in December 1792, a key event of the [[French Revolution]], was the trial of the [[Louis XVI of France|former king]]\u2013officially called \"Citizen Louis Capet\" since being dethroned in September\u2013before the [[National Convention]]. He was convicted of high treason and other crimes, resulting in his [[execution of Louis XVI|execution]].\n\n== December 1792 ==\nThe trial began on 3 December. On 4 December the Convention's president [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re]] presented it with the fatal indictment (drafted by [[Jean-Baptiste Robert Lindet]]) and decreed the interrogation of Louis XVI. Louis made his entrance into the Convention chamber then:\n\"Louis\", said [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re|Bar\u00e8re]] de Vieuzac, \"the nation accuses you, the National Assembly decreed on 3 December that you would be judged by it; on 6 December, it decided that you would be brought to the dock. We shall read you the act giving the offenses with which you are charged...\".{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n=== The charges ===\nLouis was then read the charges by the Convention's secretary, [[Jean-Baptiste Mailhe]]:\n\n\"Louis, the French Nation accuses you of having committed a multitude of crimes to establish your tyranny, in destroying her freedom.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}\n# On 20 June 1789, Louis shut down the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]], resulting in the [[Third Estate|commoners]] (non-nobles, non-clergy) [[Tennis Court Oath|swearing not to disband.]] Mailhe characterized this as an attack on the sovereignty of the people.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref> ''Louis's answer'': \"No laws then existed to prevent me from it.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}\n# \"You ordered an army to march against the citizens of Paris\" and ceased only after the [[storming of the Bastille]] on 14 July 1789. ''Louis's answer'': It was my right but \"I never had an intention of spilling blood.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=55\u201356}}\n# Despite promises made to the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]], Louis refused to acknowledge the [[Abolition of feudalism in France|abolition of feudalism]], as stated in the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen]]. He invited troops to [[Versailles]] and feted them in a lavish banquet where the [[cockade of France]] was (purportedly) \"trampled under foot\" resulting in the insurrectionary [[Women's March on Versailles]] on 5 October 1789. ''Louis's answer'': My refusals were just; I never saw the desecration of the cockade.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=56\u201357}}\n# At [[F\u00eate de la F\u00e9d\u00e9ration]] of 14 July 1790, Louis took an oath which Mailhe said he did not keep by conspiring with the counter-revolutionaries [[Antoine Omer Talon]] and [[Honor\u00e9 Gabriel Riqueti, comte de Mirabeau|Mirabeau]]. ''Louis's answer'': I do not remember.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis is accused of disbursing millions to \"effect this corruption\" and planning escape. ''Louis's answer'': \"I felt no greater pleasure, than that of relieving the needy.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis planned to escape on the [[Day of Daggers]] on 28 February 1790 when hundreds of nobles with concealed weapons entered the [[Tuileries Palace]] and again when he wanted to visit [[Saint-Cloud]] 10 April 1790. ''Louis's answer'': \"Absurd.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis did attempt to [[Flight to Varennes|escape to Varennes]] on 21 June 1791, protesting in writing the activities of the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]]. ''Louis's answer:'' Refer to what I told the assembly at that time.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=58}}\n# That Louis was complicit in the [[Champ de Mars Massacre]] on 17 July 1791. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I do know nothing of it.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=59}}\n# Back in July 1791, the [[Declaration of Pillnitz]] was being drafted by [[Leopold II, Holy Roman Emperor|Leopold II]] of Austria (brother of Queen [[Marie Antoinette]]) and [[Frederick William II of Prussia]] who \"pledged themselves to re-erect in France the throne of the absolute monarchy, and you were silent on this convention till the moment when it was known by all Europe.\" ''Louis's answer:'' This is my minister's fault.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=59}}\n# Louis supported the counter-revolutionary [[Arles]] rebellion. ''Louis's answer:'' I followed my ministers' advice.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=59\u201360}}\n# When [[Avignon]] and the [[Comtat Venaissin]] were annexed to France following a referendum, Louis delayed and sent commissioners that supported its civil war. ''Louis's answer:'' I don't remember the delay and the fault lies in the commissioners, not me.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis did nothing about the counter-revolutions in [[N\u00eemes]], [[Montauban]], and Jal\u00e8s ([[:fr:Camps de Jal\u00e8s|fr]]) until [[Saillant|Saillant's]] rebellion. ''Louis's answer:'' This was done by my ministers.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis sent twenty-two battalions against the people of [[Marseilles]] who were marching to subdue the counter-revolutionaries of [[Arles]]. ''Louis's answer:'' Provide written proof.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis received a letter from M. de Wittgenstein, Commandant General of the Army of [[Southern France]] (le Midi)<ref>{{cite web\n|date= 4 April 1792\n|last= Wittgenstein\n|first= M. de\n|url= http://ccfr.bnf.fr/portailccfr/ark:/06871/0015164842\n|language=French\n|title= Copie de la lettre \u00e9crite par M. de Wittgenstein, commandant g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de l'arm\u00e9e du Midi\n|publisher= Catalogue Collectif de France\n|accessdate= 19 October 2016\n}}</ref> asking for additional time to rally support for the throne. ''Louis's answer:'' I don't remember the letter and he doesn't work for me anymore.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=61}}\n# Louis paid his former bodyguards even after they emigrated out of France to [[Koblenz|Coblentz]] along with other noble [[French Emigration (1789\u20131815)|\u00e9migr\u00e9s]]. ''Louis's answer:'' I stopped paying the bodyguards after they emigrated. As for the nobles, I don't remember.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=61}}\n# Louis's two exiled brothers, [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis Stanislas Xavier]] and [[Charles X of France|Charles Philippe]], both future French kings, are accused of raising regiments, borrowing money and contracting alliances to overturn the revolution. A letter signed by the two written to Louis is produced. ''Louis's answer:'' I disowned them once I became aware of their proceedings. I know nothing of this letter.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=61\u201362}}\n# Louis is accused of neglecting the defense of the country by not providing sufficient men, money or arms and refusing the establishment of a camp of 20,000 near Paris. ''Louis's answer:'' The fault lies with my ministers.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=62}}\n# A letter from Hippolyte-Jean-Ren\u00e9 de Toulongeon ([[:fr:Hippolyte-Jean-Ren\u00e9 de Toulongeon|fr]]) is produced that indicates Louis's approval of his emigration to [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1811\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=f5BBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=by+a+letter+from+Toulongeon&source=bl&ots=iAtj41E6sH&sig=Us4KEW5b-Kep-xty-3xDPNhXYqU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiRoaD8j-jPAhXrrFQKHcfjBl8Q6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=by%20a%20letter%20from%20Toulongeon&f=false\n|title= An Impartial History of the War, from the Commencement of the Revolution in France\n|publisher= Russel & Allen\n|accessdate= 19 October 2016\n}}</ref> This is used as evidence that he encourages desertion to the service of his brothers. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I know nothing of this; there is not a word true in this charge.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=62\u201363}}\n# A letter from [[Marie-Gabriel-Florent-Auguste de Choiseul-Gouffier|Choiseul-Gouffier]], former ambassador to [[Constantinople]], establishes Louis's desire for peace between [[Turkey]] and [[Austria]] so that Austria could use the Turkish border troops against France. ''Louis's answer:'' Choiseul-Gouffier is a liar.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=63}}\n# The [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]]ns were advancing on France but Louis waited until 10 July 1792 to inform the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]]. ''Louis's answer:'' I didn't know until then; my ministers were responsible.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=63}}\n# Louis made [[Charles d'Abancour]] [[Minister of Defence (France)|minister of war]], a suspicious choice since he was the nephew of ex-Finance Minister [[Charles Alexandre de Calonne]] who had joined the anti-revolution \u00e9migr\u00e9 group at [[Coblenz]]. It was during D'Abancour's tenue that [[Longwy]] and [[Battle of Verdun (1792)|Verdun]] were lost to the Prussians and \u00e9migr\u00e9s. ''Louis's answer:'' I didn't know he was his nephew.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=63\u201364}} \n# Louis is accused of destroying the French navy with his [[ministre de la Marine et des Colonies|Secretary of Navy]] [[Bertrand de Molleville]] organizing the mass emigration of officers. When the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] accused Molleville, Louis replied he was \"satisfied with his services.\" ''Louis's answer:'' \"I have done all that I could to retain the Officers.\" A lack of proper complaint precluded me from removing him.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=64}}\n# Louis is accused of having agents in the French colonies fomenting counter-revolution (see [[Haitian Revolution]]). ''Louis's answer:'' \"I had nothing to do with [that].\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=64}}\n# Louis is protecting fanatical internal enemies of France, aristocrats and \"non-juring\" clergy (those who refuse to take the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]] oath), so that he can restore the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I know nothing of this project.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# On 29 November 1791 the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] issued a decree that \"non-juring\" priests would no longer receive state funds. Louis vetoed this decree. ''Louis's answer:'' The [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]] gave me the power to veto.<ref>{{cite web\n|date= 1817\n|last= Baines\n|first= Edward\n|authorlink= Edward_Baines_(1774\u20131848)\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=3KzSAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA53&dq=1792+french+legislative+decrees&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcxvSh_unPAhUll1QKHfQUC_Y4ChDoAQgjMAE#v=onepage&q=1792%20french%20legislative%20decrees&f=false\n|title= History of the Wars of the French Revolution, from the Breaking Point of the War in 1792, to the Restoration of a General Peace in 1815\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1911\n|last= Belloc\n|first= Hilaire\n|authorlink= Hilaire Belloc\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kNn0AkDa8w0C&pg=PT189&lpg=PT189&dq=november+29+1791+french+decree+priests&source=bl&ots=OtqY_8BJf3&sig=mN4Htu7XiCdZnYc3l19dt9ejSbw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyoKapgerPAhUS2WMKHYFGALcQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=november%2029%201791%20french%20decree%20priests&f=false\n|title= The French Revolution\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref>\n# Anti-revolutionary disturbances from these \"non-juring\" clerics increase and Louis's ministers say they are not breaking the law. On 27 May 1792 the Assembly issues a decree allowing for the deportation of the clerics, if twenty \"active citizens\" (over the age of 25, paid direct taxes equal to three days' labor) request and the [[Departments of France|department]] concurs. Louis, again, vetoes. ''Louis's answer:'' The [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]] gave me the power to veto.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|1913|p=209}}{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# The reputation of the King's bodyguards was poor, accused of anti-revolutionary sentiments. On 29 May 1792, the Assembly decreed their disbanding. Louis signed, if reluctantly. He is accused of writing the guards \"a letter of satisfaction\" and continuing to pay them. ''Louis's answer:'' I stopped paying them once new guards were appointed.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|1913|pp=209\u2013212}}{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# Louis kept the [[Swiss Guards#Swiss Guards (Gardes Suisses)|Swiss Guards]] among his bodyguards contrary to the [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]].<ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1791 \n|url= http://www.historywiz.com/primarysources/const1791text.html\n|title= The Constitution of 1791 National Assembly \n|quote= The King may choose the men of his guard only from among those who are at present on active service in the troops of the line, or from among citizens who have served for a year as National Guards, provided they are resident in the kingdom and have previously taken the civic oath.\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref> The [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] had expressly ordered their departure. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I have executed all the decrees that have been enacted....\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# Louis Collenot d'Angremont ([[:fr:Louis Collenot d'Angremont)|fr]]) (first to be guillotined due to his activities on [[10 August (French Revolution)|August 10]]) and a person going by the name of Gilles were counter-revolutionaries in the pay of Louis. ''Louis's answer:'' I have no knowledge. \"The idea of counter-revolution never entered my head.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=65\u201366}}\n# You tried to bribe, with considerable sums, several members of the Constituent and Legislative Assemblies;<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref> letters from Dufresne Saint-L\u00e9on and several others, which will be presented to you, establish this fact.\n# You allowed the French nation to be disgraced in Germany, in Italy, and in Spain, since you did nothing to exact reparation for the ill treatment which the French experienced in those countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n# On [[10 August (French Revolution)|10 August]] you reviewed the Swiss Guards at five o\u2019clock in the morning; and the Swiss Guards fired first on the citizens.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n# You caused the blood of Frenchmen to flow.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Cross-examination ===\nLouis XVI heard the 33 charges sitting in the armchair in which he had accepted the Constitution. After the secretary had read him the accusation act, [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re]] de Vieuzac repeated each charge and questioned Louis XVI.\n<!---\n{{Guil|Citoyens repr\u00e9sentants de la Nation, commen\u00e7a-t-il, il est donc enfin arriv\u00e9 ce moment o\u00f9 Louis accus\u00e9 au nom du peuple fran\u00e7ais, peut se faire entendre au milieu de ce peuple lui-m\u00eame ! Il est arriv\u00e9 ce moment o\u00f9 entour\u00e9 des conseils que l\u2019humanit\u00e9 et la loi lui ont donn\u00e9s, il peut pr\u00e9senter \u00e0 la Nation une d\u00e9fense et d\u00e9velopper devant elle les intentions qui l\u2019ont toujours anim\u00e9 ! Citoyens je vous parlerai avec la franchise d\u2019un homme libre : je cherche parmi vous des juges, et je n\u2019y vois que des accusateurs ! Vous voulez prononcer sur le sort de Louis, et c\u2019est vous m\u00eames qui l\u2019accusez ! Vous voulez et vous avez d\u00e9j\u00e0 \u00e9mis votre v\u0153u ! Vous voulez prononcez sur le sort de Louis  et vos opinions parcourent l\u2019Europe ! Louis sera donc le seul Fran\u00e7ais pour lequel il n\u2019existe aucune loi, ni aucune forme ! Il ne jouira ni de son ancienne condition ni de la nouvelle ! Quelle \u00e9trange et inconcevable destin\u00e9e ! Fran\u00e7ais la r\u00e9volution qui vous r\u00e9g\u00e9n\u00e8re a d\u00e9velopp\u00e9 en vous de grandes vertus ; mais craignez, qu\u2019elle n\u2019ait affaibli dans vos \u00e2mes le sentiment de l\u2019humanit\u00e9, sans lequel il ne peut y en avoir que de fausses ! Entendez d\u2019avance l\u2019Histoire, qui redira \u00e0 la renomm\u00e9e : \"Louis \u00e9tait mont\u00e9 sur le tr\u00f4ne \u00e0 vingt ans, et \u00e0 vingt ans il donna l\u2019exemple des m\u0153urs : il n\u2019y porta aucune faiblesse coupable ni aucune passion corruptrice ; il fut \u00e9conome, juste et s\u00e9v\u00e8re ; il s\u2019y montra toujours l\u2019ami constant du peuple. Le peuple d\u00e9sirait la destruction d\u2019un imp\u00f4t d\u00e9sastreux qui pesait sur lui, il le d\u00e9truisit ; le peuple demandait l\u2019abolition de la servitude, il commen\u00e7a par l\u2019abolir lui-m\u00eame dans ses domaines ; le peuple sollicitait des r\u00e9formes dans la l\u00e9gislation criminelle pour l\u2019adoucissement du sort des accus\u00e9s, il fit ces r\u00e9formes ; le peuple voulait que des milliers de Fran\u00e7ais que la rigueur de nos usages avait priv\u00e9s jusqu\u2019alors des droits qui appartient aux citoyens, acquissent ces droits ou les recouvrassent, il les en fit jouir par ses lois. Le peuple voulut la libert\u00e9, il la lui donna ! Il vint m\u00eame au devant de lui par ses sacrifices, et cependant c\u2019est au nom de ce m\u00eame peuple qu\u2019on demande aujourd\u2019hui... Citoyens, je n\u2019ach\u00e8ve pas... JE M\u2019ARR\u00caTE DEVANT L\u2019HISTOIRE : songez qu\u2019elle jugera votre jugement et que le sien sera celui des si\u00e8cles\". En venant \u00e0 la r\u00e9futation des chefs d\u2019accusation, Romain de S\u00e8ze les divisa adroitement : tenant pour nuls ceux qui \u00e9taient ant\u00e9rieurs \u00e0 la Constitution ou qui avaient \u00e9t\u00e9 amnisti\u00e9s par elle, et ceux qui lui \u00e9taient post\u00e9rieurs mais dont les ministres assumaient l\u00e9galement, la responsabilit\u00e9, il nia l\u2019appel \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9tranger et d\u00e9clara Louis XVI irresponsable des tractations men\u00e9es par ses fr\u00e8res avec l\u2019Autriche. Il nia pareillement l\u2019envoi des subsides aux \u00e9migr\u00e9s, l\u2019accusation manquant \u00e0 vrai dire de preuves formelles. Ce fut la partie la moins solide de la d\u00e9fense, ce qui importait d\u2019ailleurs assez peu, les d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la Convention ayant la conviction que Louis XVI avait pactis\u00e9 avec l\u2019ennemi.}}\n--->\n\n==The defense, 26 December 1792==\n\n=== The defense team ===\n\nLouis XVI sought the most illustrious legal minds in France as his defense team. He first asked [[Gui-Jean-Baptiste Target]], former deputy of the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]] and hero of the [[Parlement]]s of the [[ancien r\u00e9gime]], to lead his defense, but the elderly lawyer refused on account of his age. The task of lead counsel fell to [[Raymond Des\u00e8ze]], who was assisted by [[Fran\u00e7ois Denis Tronchet]] (Target's closest colleague, who came on board reluctantly, only at the King's insistence) and [[Guillaume-Chr\u00e9tien de Lamoignon de Malesherbes]] (Louis XVI's former [[Secretary of State of the Maison du Roi|Secretary of State]]).\n\nThough he had only two weeks to prepare his defense arguments. Des\u00e8ze's brilliance so shone through in a first draft that, although it was moving, Louis rejected it as too rhetorical, saying, \"I do not want to play on their (the Convention's) feelings\".\n\nWhen the time came to deliver the defense (26 December 1792), despite having had no sleep for over four days, he pleaded the king's case for three hours, arguing eloquently yet discreetly that the revolution spare his life. Beginning with a description of why the charges were invalid (under the terms of the [[French Constitution of 1791|Constitution of 1791]] Louis, as king, was immune from prosecution), he attacked the right of [[National Convention]] to stand as judge and jury. Finally, he moved to a rejection of the charges in the ''acte enonciatif'' drawn up by the constitution charge by charge, with a royalist history of the revolution, portraying Louis as \"the restorer of French Liberty\". He finished, like many of the set-piece speeches of the revolution, with an appeal to history:\n{{quote|Louis ascended the throne at the age of twenty, and at the age of twenty he gave to the throne the example of character. He brought to the throne no wicked weaknesses, no corrupting passions. He was economical, just, severe. He showed himself always the constant friend of the people. The people wanted the abolition of servitude. He began by abolishing it on his own lands. The people asked for reforms in the criminal law... he carried out these reforms. The people wanted liberty: he gave it to them. The people themselves came before him in his sacrifices. Nevertheless, it is in the name of these very people that one today demands... Citizens, I cannot finish... I stop myself before History. Think how it will judge your judgement, and that the judgement of him will be judged by the centuries.}}\n\n=== Declaration of Louis XVI in his defense. ===\n\"You have heard my defense, I would not repeat the details. In talking to you perhaps for the last time, I declare that my conscience reproaches me with nothing, and my defenders have told you the truth. I never feared the public examination of my conduct, but my heart is torn by the imputation that I would want to shed the blood of the people and especially that the misfortunes of August 10th be attributed to me. I avow that the many proofs that I have always acted from my love of the people, and the manner in which I have always conducted myself, seemed to prove that I did not fear to put myself forward in order to spare their blood, and forever prevent such an imputation.\"\n<!---\n{{On vient de vous exposer mes moyens de d\u00e9fense, je ne les renouvellerai point ! En vous parlant peut-\u00eatre pour la derni\u00e8re fois, je vous d\u00e9clare que ma conscience ne me reproche rien, et que mes d\u00e9fenseurs ne vous ont dit que la v\u00e9rit\u00e9.\nJe n\u2019ai jamais craint que ma conduite f\u00fbt examin\u00e9e publiquement, mais mon c\u0153ur est d\u00e9chir\u00e9 de trouver dans l\u2019acte d\u2019accusation l\u2019imputation d\u2019avoir voulu r\u00e9pandre le sang du peuple, et surtout que les malheurs du 10 ao\u00fbt me soient attribu\u00e9s.\nJ\u2019avoue que les preuves multipli\u00e9es que j\u2019avais donn\u00e9es dans tous les temps de mon amour pour le peuple, et la mani\u00e8re dont je m\u2019\u00e9tais toujours conduit, me paraissaient devoir prouver que je craignais peu de m\u2019exposer pour \u00e9pargner son sang, et \u00e9loigner \u00e0 jamais de moi une pareille imputation}}m\n--->\n\n==The verdict, 14\u201315 January==\nGiven overwhelming evidence of Louis' collusion with the invaders, the verdict was a foregone conclusion.  Ultimately, 693 deputies voted to convict the former king. Not a single deputy voted \"no,\" though 26 attached some condition to their votes.  Twenty-six deputies were absent from the vote, most on official business. Twenty-three deputies abstained, for various reasons. Several abstained because they felt they had been elected to make laws rather than to judge.\n\n==The punishment, 16\u201317 January==\n\n===The Mailhe amendment===\nFor the king's sentence, deputy [[Jean-Baptiste Mailhe]] proposed  \"Death, but [...] I think it would be worthy of the Convention to consider whether it would be useful to policy to delay the execution\" which was supported by twenty-six deputies. This \"Mailhe amendment\" was regarded by some of Mailhe's contemporaries as a conspiracy to save the king's life. It was even suggested that Mailhe had been paid, perhaps by Spanish gold.\n\n===The vote===\nParis voted overwhelmingly for death, 21 to 3. Robespierre voted first, and said \"The sentiment that led me to call for the abolition of the death penalty is the same that today forces me to demand that it be applied to the tyrant of my country.\" [[Louis Philippe II, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Philippe \u00c9galit\u00e9]], formerly the Duke of Orl\u00e9ans and Louis' own cousin, voted for his execution, a cause of much future bitterness among French monarchists.\n\nThere were 721 voters in total. 34 voted for death with attached conditions (23 of whom invoked the Mailhe amendment), 2 voted for life imprisonment in irons, 319 voted for imprisonment until the end of the war (to be followed by banishment). 361 voted for death without conditions, just carrying the vote by a marginal majority. Louis was to be put to death.\n\n===Execution===\n{{main|Execution of Louis XVI}} \nLouis was [[guillotine]]d on 21 January 1793 in the Place de la R\u00e9volution (renamed [[Place de la Concorde]] in 1795).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* David P. Jordan, ''The King's Trial \u2013 Louis XVI vs. the French Revolution'', University of California Press, 1979. {{ISBN|0-520-04399-5}}.\n*{{Cite book |last1=Pfeiffer|first1=Laura Belle|title=The Uprising of June 20, 1792|publisher=University of Nebraska|url=https://archive.org/details/uprisingjune00unkngoog|year=1793|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Trapp|first1=Joseph|authorlink=Joseph Trapp|title=Proceedings of the French National Convention on the Trial of Louis XVI|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D4pJAAAAMAAJ|year=1913|ref=harv}}\n* Michael Walzer, ''Regicide and Revolution \u2013 Speeches at the Trial of Louis XVI'', Columbia University Press, 1993. {{ISBN|978-0-231-08259-4}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://les.guillotines.free.fr/les%20deputes%20regicides.htm The regicide d\u00e9put\u00e9s.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trial of Louis Xvi}}\n[[Category:Regicides of Louis XVI|*]]\n[[Category:1792 events of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:1793 events of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Trials in France|Louis XVI]]\n[[Category:Louis XVI of France]]\n[[Category:1792 in law]]\n[[Category:1793 in law]]\n[[Category:Trials of political people]]\n[[Category:French National Convention]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:ExaminationLouistheLast.jpg|thumb|325px|\"Louis the Last\" being cross-examined by the Convention.]]\n{{Expand French|Proc\u00e8s de Louis XVI|date=January 2009}}\nThe '''trial of Louis XVI'''. in December 1792, a key event of the [[French Revolution]], was the trial of the [[ Louis XVI of France |former king]]\u2013officially called \"Citizen Louis Capet\" since being dethroned in September\u2013before the [[National Convention]]. He was convicted of high treason and other crimes, resulting in his [[execution of Louis XVI|execution]].\n\n== December 1792 ==\nThe trial began on 3 December. On 4 December the Convention's president [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re]] presented it with the fatal indictment (drafted by [[Jean-Baptiste Robert Lindet]]) and decreed the interrogation of Louis XVI. Louis made his entrance into the Convention chamber then:\n\"Louis\", said [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re|Bar\u00e8re]] de Vieuzac, \"the nation accuses you, the National Assembly decreed on 3 December that you would be judged by it; on 6 December, it decided that you would be brought to the dock. We shall read you the act giving the offenses with which you are charged...\".{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n=== The charges ===\nLouis was then read the charges by the Convention's secretary, [[Jean-Baptiste Mailhe]]:\n\n\"Louis, the French Nation accuses you of having committed a multitude of crimes to establish your tyranny, in destroying her freedom.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}\n# On 20 June 1789, Louis shut down the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]], resulting in the [[Third Estate|commoners]] (non-nobles, non-clergy) [[Tennis Court Oath|swearing not to disband.]] Mailhe characterized this as an attack on the sovereignty of the people.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref> ''Louis's answer'': \"No laws then existed to prevent me from it.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=55}}\n# \"You ordered an army to march against the citizens of Paris\" and ceased only after the [[storming of the Bastille]] on 14 July 1789. ''Louis's answer'': It was my right but \"I never had an intention of spilling blood.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=55-56}}\n# Despite promises made to the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]], Louis refused to acknowledge the [[Abolition of feudalism in France|abolition of feudalism]], as stated in the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen]]. He invited troops to [[Versailles]] and feted them in a lavish banquet where the [[cockade of France]] was (purportedly) \"trampled under foot\" resulting in the insurrectionary [[Women's March on Versailles]] on 5 October 1789. ''Louis's answer'': My refusals were just; I never saw the desecration of the cockade.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=56-57}}\n# At [[F\u00eate de la F\u00e9d\u00e9ration]] of 14 July 1790, Louis took an oath which Mailhe said he did not keep by conspiring with the counter-revolutionaries [[Antoine Omer Talon]] and [[Honor\u00e9 Gabriel Riqueti, comte de Mirabeau|Mirabeau]]. ''Louis's answer'': I do not remember.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis is accused of disbursing millions to \"effect this corruption\" and planning escape. ''Louis's answer'': \"I felt no greater pleasure, than that of relieving the needy.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis planned to escape on the [[Day of Daggers]] on 28 February 1790 when hundreds of nobles with concealed weapons entered the [[Tuileries Palace]] and again when he wanted to visit [[Saint-Cloud]] 10 April 1790. ''Louis's answer'': \"Absurd.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=57}}\n# Louis did attempt to [[ Flight to Varennes |escape to Varennes]] on 21 June 1791, protesting in writing the activities of the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]]. ''Louis's answer:'' Refer to what I told the assembly at that time.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=58}}\n# That Louis was complicit in the [[Champ de Mars Massacre]] on 17 July 1791. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I do know nothing of it.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=59}}\n# Back in July 1791, the [[Declaration of Pillnitz]] was being drafted by [[Leopold II, Holy Roman Emperor|Leopold II]] of Austria (brother of Queen [[Marie Antoinette]]) and [[Frederick William II of Prussia]] who \"pledged themselves to re-erect in France the throne of the absolute monarchy, and you were silent on this convention till the moment when it was known by all Europe.\" ''Louis's answer:'' This is my minister's fault.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=59}}\n# Louis supported the counter-revolutionary [[Arles]] rebellion. ''Louis's answer:'' I followed my ministers' advice.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=59-60}}\n# When [[Avignon]] and the [[Comtat Venaissin]] were annexed to France following a referendum, Louis delayed and sent commissioners that supported its civil war. ''Louis's answer:'' I don't remember the delay and the fault lies in the commissioners, not me.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis did nothing about the counter-revolutions in [[N\u00eemes]], [[Montauban]], and Jal\u00e8s ([[:fr:Camps de Jal\u00e8s|fr]]) until [[Saillant|Saillant's]] rebellion. ''Louis's answer:'' This was done by my ministers.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis sent twenty-two battalions against the people of [[Marseilles]] who were marching to subdue the counter-revolutionaries of [[Arles]]. ''Louis's answer:'' Provide written proof.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=60}}\n# Louis received a letter from M. de Wittgenstein, Commandant General of the Army of [[Southern France]] (le Midi)<ref>{{cite web\n|date= 4 April 1792\n|last= Wittgenstein\n|first= M. de\n|url= http://ccfr.bnf.fr/portailccfr/ark:/06871/0015164842\n|language=French\n|title= Copie de la lettre \u00e9crite par M. de Wittgenstein, commandant g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de l'arm\u00e9e du Midi\n|publisher= Catalogue Collectif de France\n|accessdate= 19 October 2016\n}}</ref> asking for additional time to rally support for the throne. ''Louis's answer:'' I don't remember the letter and he doesn't work for me anymore.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=61}}\n# Louis paid his former bodyguards even after they emigrated out of France to [[Koblenz|Coblentz]] along with other noble [[French Emigration (1789\u20131815)|\u00e9migr\u00e9s]]. ''Louis's answer:'' I stopped paying the bodyguards after they emigrated. As for the nobles, I don't remember.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=61}}\n# Louis's two exiled brothers, [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis Stanislas Xavier]] and [[Charles X of France|Charles Philippe]], both future French kings, are accused of raising regiments, borrowing money and contracting alliances to overturn the revolution. A letter signed by the two written to Louis is produced. ''Louis's answer:'' I disowned them once I became aware of their proceedings. I know nothing of this letter.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=61-62}}\n# Louis is accused of neglecting the defense of the country by not providing sufficient men, money or arms and refusing the establishment of a camp of 20,000 near Paris. ''Louis's answer:'' The fault lies with my ministers.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=62}}\n# A letter from Hippolyte-Jean-Ren\u00e9 de Toulongeon ([[:fr:Hippolyte-Jean-Ren\u00e9 de Toulongeon|fr]]) is produced that indicates Louis's approval of his emigration to [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1811\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=f5BBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=by+a+letter+from+Toulongeon&source=bl&ots=iAtj41E6sH&sig=Us4KEW5b-Kep-xty-3xDPNhXYqU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiRoaD8j-jPAhXrrFQKHcfjBl8Q6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=by%20a%20letter%20from%20Toulongeon&f=false\n|title= An Impartial History of the War, from the Commencement of the Revolution in France\n|publisher= Russel & Allen\n|accessdate= 19 October 2016\n}}</ref> This is used as evidence that he encourages desertion to the service of his brothers. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I know nothing of this; there is not a word true in this charge.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=62-63}}\n# A letter from [[Marie-Gabriel-Florent-Auguste de Choiseul-Gouffier|Choiseul-Gouffier]], former ambassador to [[Constantinople]], establishes Louis's desire for peace between [[Turkey]] and [[Austria]] so that Austria could use the Turkish border troops against France. ''Louis's answer:'' Choiseul-Gouffier is a liar.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=63}}\n# The [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]]ns were advancing on France but Louis waited until 10 July 1792 to inform the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]]. ''Louis's answer:'' I didn't know until then; my ministers were responsible.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=63}}\n# Louis made [[Charles d'Abancour]] [[Minister of Defence (France)|minister of war]], a suspicious choice since he was the nephew of ex-Finance Minister [[Charles Alexandre de Calonne]] who had joined the anti-revolution \u00e9migr\u00e9 group at [[Coblenz]]. It was during D'Abancour's tenue that [[Longwy]] and [[Battle of Verdun (1792)|Verdun]] were lost to the Prussians and \u00e9migr\u00e9s. ''Louis's answer:'' I didn't know he was his nephew.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=63-64}} \n# Louis is accused of destroying the French navy with his [[ministre de la Marine et des Colonies|Secretary of Navy]] [[Bertrand de Molleville]] organizing the mass emigration of officers. When the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] accused Molleville, Louis replied he was \"satisfied with his services.\" ''Louis's answer:'' \"I have done all that I could to retain the Officers.\" A lack of proper complaint precluded me from removing him.{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=64}}\n# Louis is accused of having agents in the French colonies fomenting counter-revolution (see [[Haitian Revolution]]). ''Louis's answer:'' \"I had nothing to do with [that].\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=64}}\n# Louis is protecting fanatical internal enemies of France, aristocrats and \"non-juring\" clergy (those who refuse to take the [[Civil Constitution of the Clergy]] oath), so that he can restore the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I know nothing of this project.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# On 29 November 1791 the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] issued a decree that \"non-juring\" priests would no longer receive state funds. Louis vetoed this decree. ''Louis's answer:'' The [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]] gave me the power to veto.<ref>{{cite web\n|date= 1817\n|last= Baines\n|first= Edward\n|authorlink= Edward_Baines_(1774\u20131848)\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=3KzSAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA53&dq=1792+french+legislative+decrees&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcxvSh_unPAhUll1QKHfQUC_Y4ChDoAQgjMAE#v=onepage&q=1792%20french%20legislative%20decrees&f=false\n|title= History of the Wars of the French Revolution, from the Breaking Point of the War in 1792, to the Restoration of a General Peace in 1815\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1911\n|last= Belloc\n|first= Hilaire\n|authorlink= Hilaire Belloc\n|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=kNn0AkDa8w0C&pg=PT189&lpg=PT189&dq=november+29+1791+french+decree+priests&source=bl&ots=OtqY_8BJf3&sig=mN4Htu7XiCdZnYc3l19dt9ejSbw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyoKapgerPAhUS2WMKHYFGALcQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=november%2029%201791%20french%20decree%20priests&f=false\n|title= The French Revolution\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref>\n# Anti-revolutionary disturbances from these \"non-juring\" clerics increase and Louis's ministers say they are not breaking the law. On 27 May 1792 the Assembly issues a decree allowing for the deportation of the clerics, if twenty \"active citizens\" (over the age of 25, paid direct taxes equal to three days' labor) request and the [[Departments of France|department]] concurs. Louis, again, vetoes. ''Louis's answer:'' The [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]] gave me the power to veto.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|1913|p=209}}{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# The reputation of the King's bodyguards was poor, accused of anti-revolutionary sentiments. On 29 May 1792, the Assembly decreed their disbanding. Louis signed, if reluctantly. He is accused of writing the guards \"a letter of satisfaction\" and continuing to pay them. ''Louis's answer:'' I stopped paying them once new guards were appointed.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|1913|pp=209-212}}{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# Louis kept the [[Swiss Guards#Swiss Guards (Gardes Suisses)|Swiss Guards]] among his bodyguards contrary to the [[French Constitution of 1791|constitution]].<ref>{{cite web\n|year= 1791 \n|url= http://www.historywiz.com/primarysources/const1791text.html\n|title= The Constitution of 1791 National Assembly \n|quote= The King may choose the men of his guard only from among those who are at present on active service in the troops of the line, or from among citizens who have served for a year as National Guards, provided they are resident in the kingdom and have previously taken the civic oath.\n|accessdate= 20 October 2016\n}}</ref> The [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Assembly]] had expressly ordered their departure. ''Louis's answer:'' \"I have executed all the decrees that have been enacted....\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|p=65}}\n# Louis Collenot d'Angremont ([[:fr:Louis Collenot d'Angremont)|fr]]) (first to be guillotined due to his activities on [[10 August (French Revolution)|August 10]]) and a person going by the name of Gilles were counter-revolutionaries in the pay of Louis. ''Louis's answer:'' I have no knowledge. \"The idea of counter-revolution never entered my head.\"{{sfn|Trapp|1793|pp=65-66}}\n# You tried to bribe, with considerable sums, several members of the Constituent and Legislative Assemblies;<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref> letters from Dufresne Saint-L\u00e9on and several others, which will be presented to you, establish this fact.\n# You allowed the French nation to be disgraced in Germany, in Italy, and in Spain, since you did nothing to exact reparation for the ill treatment which the French experienced in those countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n# On [[10 August (French Revolution)|10 August]] you reviewed the Swiss Guards at five o\u2019clock in the morning; and the Swiss Guards fired first on the citizens.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n# You caused the blood of Frenchmen to flow.<ref>{{cite web|title=the Trial and Execution of Louis XVI|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/louis_trial.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Cross-examination ===\nLouis XVI heard the 33 charges sitting in the armchair in which he had accepted the Constitution. After the secretary had read him the accusation act, [[Bertrand Bar\u00e8re]] de Vieuzac repeated each charge and questioned Louis  XVI.\n<!---\n{{Guil|Citoyens repr\u00e9sentants de la Nation, commen\u00e7a-t-il, il est donc enfin arriv\u00e9 ce moment o\u00f9 Louis accus\u00e9 au nom du peuple fran\u00e7ais, peut se faire entendre au milieu de ce peuple lui-m\u00eame ! Il est arriv\u00e9 ce moment o\u00f9 entour\u00e9 des conseils que l\u2019humanit\u00e9 et la loi lui ont donn\u00e9s, il peut pr\u00e9senter \u00e0 la Nation une d\u00e9fense et d\u00e9velopper devant elle les intentions qui l\u2019ont toujours anim\u00e9 ! Citoyens je vous parlerai avec la franchise d\u2019un homme libre : je cherche parmi vous des juges, et je n\u2019y vois que des accusateurs ! Vous voulez prononcer sur le sort de Louis, et c\u2019est vous m\u00eames qui l\u2019accusez ! Vous voulez et vous avez d\u00e9j\u00e0 \u00e9mis votre v\u0153u ! Vous voulez prononcez sur le sort de Louis  et vos opinions parcourent l\u2019Europe ! Louis sera donc le seul Fran\u00e7ais pour lequel il n\u2019existe aucune loi, ni aucune forme ! Il ne jouira ni de son ancienne condition ni de la nouvelle ! Quelle \u00e9trange et inconcevable destin\u00e9e ! Fran\u00e7ais la r\u00e9volution qui vous r\u00e9g\u00e9n\u00e8re a d\u00e9velopp\u00e9 en vous de grandes vertus ; mais craignez, qu\u2019elle n\u2019ait affaibli dans vos \u00e2mes le sentiment de l\u2019humanit\u00e9, sans lequel il ne peut y en avoir que de fausses ! Entendez d\u2019avance l\u2019Histoire, qui redira \u00e0 la renomm\u00e9e : \"Louis \u00e9tait mont\u00e9 sur le tr\u00f4ne \u00e0 vingt ans, et \u00e0 vingt ans il donna l\u2019exemple des m\u0153urs : il n\u2019y porta aucune faiblesse coupable ni aucune passion corruptrice ; il fut \u00e9conome, juste et s\u00e9v\u00e8re ; il s\u2019y montra toujours l\u2019ami constant du peuple. Le peuple d\u00e9sirait la destruction d\u2019un imp\u00f4t d\u00e9sastreux qui pesait sur lui, il le d\u00e9truisit ; le peuple demandait l\u2019abolition de la servitude, il commen\u00e7a par l\u2019abolir lui-m\u00eame dans ses domaines ; le peuple sollicitait des r\u00e9formes dans la l\u00e9gislation criminelle pour l\u2019adoucissement du sort des accus\u00e9s, il fit ces r\u00e9formes ; le peuple voulait que des milliers de Fran\u00e7ais que la rigueur de nos usages avait priv\u00e9s jusqu\u2019alors des droits qui appartient aux citoyens, acquissent ces droits ou les recouvrassent, il les en fit jouir par ses lois. Le peuple voulut la libert\u00e9, il la lui donna ! Il vint m\u00eame au devant de lui par ses sacrifices, et cependant c\u2019est au nom de ce m\u00eame peuple qu\u2019on demande aujourd\u2019hui... Citoyens, je n\u2019ach\u00e8ve pas... JE M\u2019ARR\u00caTE DEVANT L\u2019HISTOIRE : songez qu\u2019elle jugera votre jugement et que le sien sera celui des si\u00e8cles\". En venant \u00e0 la r\u00e9futation des chefs d\u2019accusation, Romain de S\u00e8ze les divisa adroitement : tenant pour nuls ceux qui \u00e9taient ant\u00e9rieurs \u00e0 la Constitution ou qui avaient \u00e9t\u00e9 amnisti\u00e9s par elle, et ceux qui lui \u00e9taient post\u00e9rieurs mais dont les ministres assumaient l\u00e9galement, la responsabilit\u00e9, il nia l\u2019appel \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9tranger et d\u00e9clara Louis XVI irresponsable des tractations men\u00e9es par ses fr\u00e8res avec l\u2019Autriche. Il nia pareillement l\u2019envoi des subsides aux \u00e9migr\u00e9s, l\u2019accusation manquant \u00e0 vrai dire de preuves formelles. Ce fut la partie la moins solide de la d\u00e9fense, ce qui importait d\u2019ailleurs assez peu, les d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la Convention ayant la conviction que Louis XVI avait pactis\u00e9 avec l\u2019ennemi.}}\n--->\n\n==The defense, 26 December 1792==\n\n=== The defense team ===\n\nLouis XVI sought the most illustrious legal minds in France as his defense team. He first asked [[Gui-Jean-Baptiste Target]], former deputy of the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]] and hero of the [[Parlement]]s of the [[ancien r\u00e9gime]], to lead his defense, but the elderly lawyer refused on account of his age. The task of lead counsel fell to [[Raymond Des\u00e8ze]], who was assisted by [[Fran\u00e7ois Denis Tronchet]] (Target's closest colleague, who came on board reluctantly, only at the King's insistence) and [[Guillaume-Chr\u00e9tien de Lamoignon de Malesherbes]] (Louis XVI's former [[Secretary of State of the Maison du Roi|Secretary of State]]).\n\nThough he had only two weeks to prepare his defense arguments. Des\u00e8ze's brilliance so shone through in a first draft that, although it was moving, Louis rejected it as too rhetorical, saying, \"I do not want to play on their (the Convention's) feelings\".\n\nWhen the time came to deliver the defense (26 December 1792), despite having had no sleep for over four days, he pleaded the king's case for three hours, arguing eloquently yet discreetly that the revolution spare his life. Beginning with a description of why the charges were invalid (under the terms of the [[French Constitution of 1791|Constitution of 1791]] Louis, as king, was immune from prosecution), he attacked the right of [[National Convention]] to stand as judge and jury. Finally, he moved to a rejection of the charges in the ''acte enonciatif'' drawn up by the constitution charge by charge, with a royalist history of the revolution, portraying Louis as \"the restorer of French Liberty\". He finished, like many of the set-piece speeches of the revolution, with an appeal to history:\n{{quote|Louis ascended the throne at the age of twenty, and at the age of twenty he gave to the throne the example of character. He brought to the throne no wicked weaknesses, no corrupting passions. He was economical, just, severe. He showed himself always the constant friend of the people. The people wanted the abolition of servitude. He began by abolishing it on his own lands. The people asked for reforms in the criminal law... he carried out these reforms. The people wanted liberty: he gave it to them. The people themselves came before him in his sacrifices. Nevertheless, it is in the name of these very people that one today demands... Citizens, I cannot finish... I stop myself before History. Think how it will judge your judgement, and that the judgement of him will be judged by the centuries.}}\n\n=== Declaration of Louis XVI in his defense. ===\n\"You have heard my defense, I would not repeat the details. In talking to you perhaps for the last time, I declare that my conscience reproaches me with nothing, and my defenders have told you the truth. I never feared the public examination of my conduct, but my heart is torn by the imputation that I would want to shed the blood of the people and especially that the misfortunes of August 10th be attributed to me. I avow that the many proofs that I have always acted from my love of the people, and the manner in which I have always conducted myself, seemed to prove that I did not fear to put myself forward in order to spare their blood, and forever prevent such an imputation.\"\n<!---\n{{On vient de vous exposer mes moyens de d\u00e9fense, je ne les renouvellerai point ! En vous parlant peut-\u00eatre pour la derni\u00e8re fois, je vous d\u00e9clare que ma conscience ne me reproche rien, et que mes d\u00e9fenseurs ne vous ont dit que la v\u00e9rit\u00e9.\nJe n\u2019ai jamais craint que ma conduite f\u00fbt examin\u00e9e publiquement, mais mon c\u0153ur est d\u00e9chir\u00e9 de trouver dans l\u2019acte d\u2019accusation l\u2019imputation d\u2019avoir voulu r\u00e9pandre le sang du peuple, et surtout que les malheurs du 10 ao\u00fbt me soient attribu\u00e9s.\nJ\u2019avoue que les preuves multipli\u00e9es que j\u2019avais donn\u00e9es dans tous les temps de mon amour pour le peuple, et la mani\u00e8re dont je m\u2019\u00e9tais toujours conduit, me paraissaient devoir prouver que je craignais peu de m\u2019exposer pour \u00e9pargner son sang, et \u00e9loigner \u00e0 jamais de moi une pareille imputation}}m\n--->\n\n==The verdict, 14\u201315 January==\nGiven overwhelming evidence of Louis' collusion with the invaders, the verdict was a foregone conclusion.  Ultimately, 693 deputies voted to convict the former king. Not a single deputy voted \"no,\" though 26 attached some condition to their votes.  Twenty-six deputies were absent from the vote, most on official business. Twenty-three deputies abstained, for various reasons. Several abstained because they felt they had been elected to make laws rather than to judge.\n\n==The punishment, 16\u201317 January==\n\n===The Mailhe amendment===\nFor the king's sentence, deputy [[Jean-Baptiste Mailhe]] proposed  \"Death, but [...] I think it would be worthy of the Convention to consider whether it would be useful to policy to delay the execution\" which was supported by twenty-six deputies. This \"Mailhe amendment\" was regarded by some of Mailhe's contemporaries as a conspiracy to save the king's life. It was even suggested that Mailhe had been paid, perhaps by Spanish gold.\n\n===The vote===\nParis voted overwhelmingly for death, 21 to 3. Robespierre voted first, and said \"The sentiment that led me to call for the abolition of the death penalty is the same that today forces me to demand that it be applied to the tyrant of my country.\" [[Louis Philippe II, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Philippe \u00c9galit\u00e9]], formerly the Duke of Orl\u00e9ans and Louis' own cousin, voted for his execution, a cause of much future bitterness among French monarchists.\n\nThere were 721 voters in total. 34 voted for death with attached conditions (23 of whom invoked the Mailhe amendment), 2 voted for life imprisonment in irons, 319 voted for imprisonment until the end of the war (to be followed by banishment). 361 voted for death without conditions, just carrying the vote by a marginal majority. Louis was to be put to death.\n\n===Execution===\n{{main|Execution of Louis XVI}} \nLouis was [[guillotine]]d on 21 January 1793 in the Place de la R\u00e9volution (renamed [[Place de la Concorde]] in 1795).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* David P. Jordan, ''The King's Trial - Louis XVI vs. the French Revolution'', University of California Press, 1979. {{ISBN|0-520-04399-5}}.\n*{{Cite book |last1=Pfeiffer|first1=Laura Belle|title=The Uprising of June 20, 1792|publisher=University of Nebraska|url=https://archive.org/details/uprisingjune00unkngoog|year=1793|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Trapp|first1=Joseph|authorlink=Joseph Trapp|title=Proceedings of the French National Convention on the Trial of Louis XVI|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D4pJAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=1913|ref=harv}}\n* Michael Walzer, ''Regicide and Revolution - Speeches at the Trial of Louis XVI'', Columbia University Press, 1993. {{ISBN|978-0-231-08259-4}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://les.guillotines.free.fr/les%20deputes%20regicides.htm The regicide d\u00e9put\u00e9s.]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trial Of Louis Xvi}}\n[[Category:Regicides of Louis XVI|*]]\n[[Category:1792 events of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:1793 events of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Trials in France|Louis XVI]]\n[[Category:Louis XVI of France]]\n[[Category:1792 in law]]\n[[Category:1793 in law]]\n[[Category:Trials of political people]]\n[[Category:French National Convention]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor nitpicking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trial_of_Louis_XVI"}
{"title_page": "Clarion (magazine)", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n|title = Clarion\n|image_file = Front_cover_of_Clarion_magazine_issue_16,_Summer_2013.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|image_caption = Clarion #16, Summer 2013\n|editor = Jon Maniscalco & Frances Gossen (2013- )\n|editor_title = Editors\n|previous_editor = Jennifer Herron (1997-99)<br/>Josette Akresh (1999-2000)<br/>Zachary Bos (2001-2)<br />Elizabeth Moss (2002-3)<br/>Garrison Gudenas (2004)<br/>Nicole Norman (2004-5)<br/>Bora Panduku (2005-6)<br/>Tom Simmons & Matthew Lemoyne (2006-7)<br>Juliet Johnson (2007-8)<br/>Sandy SooHoo (2008-9)<br/>Sara Trotta (2009-10)<br/>Monica Gribouski (2011-2)\n|staff_writer =\n|frequency = Annually\n|readership = 5,000\n|category = Poetry<br/>Prose<br/>Reviews<br/>Interviews\n|company =\n|publisher = [[Pen & Anvil Press|The Pen & Anvil Press]] and [[Boston University]]\n|firstdate = Spring 1998\n|country = United States\n|based = [[Boston]], Massachusetts\n|language = English\n|website = [http://www.bu.edu/clarion/ bu.edu/clarion]\n|issn = 2150-6795\n}}\n\n'''''Clarion''''' is a  [[literary magazine]] founded at [[Boston University]] in 1998.\n\n==History==\nThe first issue, titled ''?'' (stylized as ''The Staff Issue of ?'') was published by an undergraduate student group named the Boston University Literary Society. Subsequent issues were released under the name ''Clarion''.\n\nIn the beginning ''Clarion'' only published the writing of [[Boston University]] students. In 2008, the editors opened submissions to all writers, regardless of their affiliation with the University.\n\nIn 2011, The Pen & Anvil Press, a Boston-based imprint operated by the nonprofit Boston Poetry Union, took over responsibility for publishing ''Clarion'', in agreement with BULS and the BU Literary Organizations liaison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clarion at Boston University|url=http://www.bu.edu/clarion/about.htm|publisher=Boston University|accessdate=17 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508003510/http://www.bu.edu/clarion/about.htm|archivedate=8 May 2010}}</ref> Through its cooperation with the BULS, the Creative Writing department, and the BU Creative Writing Club, Clarion continues to employ undergraduate editors on its staff, alongside graduate editors and persons independent of the University.\n\nIn 2013, ''[[The Review Review]]'' included ''Clarion'' on its list of notable Boston-based literary magazines.<ref name=\"The Review Review\">{{cite web|title=Boston-based literary magazines|url=http://www.thereviewreview.net/contests/boston-based-literary-magazines|work=The Review Review|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Boston University Literary Society==\nThe '''Boston University Literary Society''' was founded as ''Boston University Students for Literary Awareness'' in Fall 1997, under the leadership of Jennifer Herron. The original members intended to publish a magazine titled ''The View from a Window'', though it was then renamed, becoming ''?'' (and then ''Clarion'') and ultimately released in Spring 1998.\n\nIn 2009, the Literary Society started ''Burn'', a students-only showcase of edgier experimental writing, and in 2010 offered the editors of formerly independent publications, ''Back Bay Review'' (art criticism) and ''Pusteblume'' (literary translation) a home under the Boston University Literary Society administration.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bu.edu/clarion Online archive]\n* [http://www.duotrope.com/market_4040.aspx Clarion at Duotrope]\n* [http://www.bu.edu/bridge/archive/1999/11-19/features4.html ''Clarion'' in the ''BU Bridge'']\n\n{{Boston University}}\n\n[[Category:American poetry magazines]]\n[[Category:American annual magazines]]\n[[Category:American student magazines]]\n[[Category:Boston University]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Boston]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n|title = Clarion\n|image_file = Front_cover_of_Clarion_magazine_issue_16,_Summer_2013.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|image_caption = Clarion #16, Summer 2013\n|editor = Jon Maniscalco & Frances Gossen (2013- )\n|editor_title = Editors\n|previous_editor = Jennifer Herron (1997-99)<br/>Josette Akresh (1999-2000)<br/>Zachary Bos (2001-2)<br />Elizabeth Moss (2002-3)<br/>Garrison Gudenas (2004)<br/>Nicole Norman (2004-5)<br/>Bora Panduku (2005-6)<br/>Tom Simmons & Matthew Lemoyne (2006-7)<br>Juliet Johnson (2007-8)<br/>Sandy SooHoo (2008-9)<br/>Sara Trotta (2009-10)<br/>Monica Gribouski (2011-2)\n|staff_writer =\n|frequency = Annually\n|readership = 5,000\n|category = Poetry<br/>Prose<br/>Reviews<br/>Interviews\n|company =\n|publisher = [[Pen & Anvil Press|The Pen & Anvil Press]] and [[Boston University]]\n|firstdate = Spring 1998\n|country = United States\n|based = [[Boston]], Massachusetts\n|language = English\n|website = [http://www.bu.edu/clarion/ bu.edu/clarion]\n|issn = 2150-6795\n}}\n\n'''''Clarion''''' is a  [[literary magazine]] founded at [[Boston University]] in 1998.\n\n==History==\nThe first issue, titled ''?'' (stylized as ''The Staff Issue of ?'') was published by an undergraduate student group named the Boston University Literary Society. Subsequent issues were released under the name ''Clarion''.\n\nIn the beginning ''Clarion'' only published the writing of [[Boston University]] students. In 2008, the editors opened submissions to all writers, regardless of their affiliation with the University.\n\nIn 2011, The Pen & Anvil Press, a Boston-based imprint operated by the nonprofit Boston Poetry Union, took over responsibility for publishing ''Clarion'', in agreement with BULS and the BU Literary Organizations liaison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clarion at Boston University|url=http://www.bu.edu/clarion/about.htm|publisher=Boston University|accessdate=17 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508003510/http://www.bu.edu/clarion/about.htm|archivedate=8 May 2010}}</ref> Through its cooperation with the BULS, the Creative Writing department, and the BU Creative Writing Club, Clarion continues to employ undergraduate editors on its staff, alongside graduate editors and persons independent of the University.\n\nIn 2013, ''[[The Review Review]]'' included ''Clarion'' on its list of notable Boston-based literary magazines.<ref name=\"The Review Review\">{{cite web|title=Boston-based literary magazines|url=http://www.thereviewreview.net/contests/boston-based-literary-magazines|work=The Review Review|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Boston University Literary Society==\nThe '''Boston University Literary Society''' was founded as ''Boston University Students for Literary Awareness'' in Fall 1997, under the leadership of Jennifer Herron. The original members intended to publish a magazine titled ''The View from a Window'', though it was then renamed, becoming ''?'' (and then ''Clarion'') and ultimately released in Spring 1998.\n\nIn 2009, the Literary Society started ''Burn'', a students-only showcase of edgier experimental writing, and in 2010 offered the editors of formerly independent publications, ''Back Bay Review'' (art criticism) and ''Pusteblume'' (literary translation) a home under the Boston University Literary Society administration.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bu.edu/clarion Online archive]\n* [http://www.duotrope.com/market_4040.aspx Clarion at Duotrope]\n* [http://www.bu.edu/bridge/archive/1999/11-19/features4.html ''Clarion'' in the ''BU Bridge'']\n\n{{Boston University}}\n\n[[Category:American poetry magazines]]\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:American student magazines]]\n[[Category:Boston University]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Boston]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarion_(magazine)"}
{"title_page": "Chips (literary magazine)", "text_new": "'''''Chips''''' is [[Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School|Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School's]] award-winning [[literary magazine]].<ref name=monts>{{cite web|title=Chips - B-CC's Literary Arts Magazine|url=http://www.montgomeryschoolsmd.org/schools/bcchs/academics/english/chips.aspx|publisher=Montgomery Schools|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> The magazine was started in 1937 and is published annually.<ref name=monts/>\n\n==Awards==\nChips has, throughout its existence, been honored with many awards, notably from the [[Columbia Scholastic Press Association]] (CSPA) and the [[National Council of Teachers of English]] (NCTE).\n\n* CSPA, High School Silver Magazine Crown<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/cspa/docs/contests-and-critiques/crown-awards/recipients/2007-scholastic-crown.html#N1010E |title=CSPA presents 42 Gold, 83 Silver Crowns at 2007 Student Awards Convocation |accessdate=March 15, 2008|work=[[Columbia Scholastic Press Association]]}}</ref>\n* Maryland District of Columbia Scholastic Press Association Gold Rating:  2009-2011<ref name=monts/>\n* National Council of Teachers of English Highest Award:  2001, 2002, 2005, 2009-2011<ref name=monts/>\n* Journalism Education Association Best of Show Award:  2001<ref name=monts/>\n\n== Staff ==\n* [[Editor in chief|Editor In Chief]]: Morgan Powell\n* Writing Editor: Angela White\n* Art Editors: Catherina Leipold and Haley Wessel\n* Music Editor: Greg Picard\n* Financial Editor: Sasha Harper\n* Creative Writing Editor: Matt Whitstock \n* Layout Editor: Alexia Chatfield \n* Faculty Sponsor: Dawn Charles\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bccchipsmagazine.com/ Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517041340/http://montgomeryschoolsmd.org/schools/bcchs/activities/clubs/chips.html Information on school website]\n\n{{italic title}}\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:American annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1937]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Maryland]]\n[[Category:1937 establishments in Maryland]]\n\n\n{{US-lit-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''''Chips''''' is [[Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School|Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School's]] award-winning [[literary magazine]].<ref name=monts>{{cite web|title=Chips - B-CC's Literary Arts Magazine|url=http://www.montgomeryschoolsmd.org/schools/bcchs/academics/english/chips.aspx|publisher=Montgomery Schools|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> The magazine was started in 1937 and is published annually.<ref name=monts/>\n\n==Awards==\nChips has, throughout its existence, been honored with many awards, notably from the [[Columbia Scholastic Press Association]] (CSPA) and the [[National Council of Teachers of English]] (NCTE). \n\n* CSPA, High School Silver Magazine Crown<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/cspa/docs/contests-and-critiques/crown-awards/recipients/2007-scholastic-crown.html#N1010E |title=CSPA presents 42 Gold, 83 Silver Crowns at 2007 Student Awards Convocation |accessdate=March 15, 2008|work=[[Columbia Scholastic Press Association]]}}</ref>\n* Maryland District of Columbia Scholastic Press Association Gold Rating:  2009-2011<ref name=monts/>\n* National Council of Teachers of English Highest Award:  2001, 2002, 2005, 2009-2011<ref name=monts/>\n* Journalism Education Association Best of Show Award:  2001<ref name=monts/>\n\n== Staff ==\n* [[Editor in chief|Editor In Chief]]: Morgan Powell\n* Writing Editor: Angela White\n* Art Editors: Catherina Leipold and Haley Wessel\n* Music Editor: Greg Picard\n* Financial Editor: Sasha Harper\n* Creative Writing Editor: Matt Whitstock \n* Layout Editor: Alexia Chatfield \n* Faculty Sponsor: Dawn Charles\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bccchipsmagazine.com/ Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517041340/http://montgomeryschoolsmd.org/schools/bcchs/activities/clubs/